<1ST_LINE>u w AM-North-Hostage     03-17 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Hostage,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Gave Ransom Courier Presidential Authorization For Carrying
Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An employee of Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot
carried a letter from White House aide Oliver L. North giving him
presidential authority for transporting $100,000 to Canada as part
of a plan to free a U.S. hostage in Lebanon, according to a
published report.
   North sent the courier, Jay Coburn, to Canada in January 1986
with a letter on National Security Council stationery that said
Coburn ``is acting on official U.S. Government business on behalf
of the President of the United States,'' according to a copy of the
letter obtained by The Washington Post.
   ``In support of this mission he has the authority to transport
and disburse as necessary, U.S. $100,000,'' the letter said. ``In
the event of emergency or clarification, please contact: Oliver L.
North.''
   Perot had provided the money, at North's request, to help free
Peter C. Kilburn, the librarian at the American University in
Beirut who was kidnapped Dec. 3, 1984. Kilburn was killed by a
Libyan terrorist group in April 1986 in apparent retaliation for
the U.S. bombing of Libya.
   Coburn needed the North letter in case U.S. Customs Service
agents stopped him at the border, the Post said in Friday's
editions. Travelers must file a disclosure statement if they take
more than $10,000 out of the country. Failure to file is punishable
by up to $250,000 in fines and five years in prison.
   The Post said Coburn has told associates that he filed no
disclosure statement and planned to rely on North's letter if he
ran into trouble at the border.
   Coburn got into Canada without difficulty and in Montreal, he
gave the money to a Canadian citizen who had provided proof of
contact with Kilburn's captors. The Canadian said the $100,000 was
a down payment and that with it, he could arrange Kilburn's release
for $1 million more, said the Post, which did not identify the man.
   The Canadian contact took the money, but never came through with
his end of the deal and was later observed by the CIA in Damascus,
spending the money on high living, the Post said, citing
unidentified sources for the information.
   The Post said that a senior FBI official has told Congress that
then-FBI Director William H. Webster _ who is now CIA director _
approved the FBI's participation in the plan. The newspaper said
the plan also was discussed with Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   North has said repeatedly that he had express authority from his
superiors for his actions.
   However, the White House has said Reagan had no knowledge of any
efforts to ransom U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
   North, who was fired from his job as an NSC aide in late 1986
following revelations of the secret sales of arms to Iran and the
diversion of profits from those sales to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels, was indicted Wednesday.
   He was charged with conspiracy to defraud the government and
commit criminal offenses against it, theft of government property
and wire fraud arising from the diversion of arms-sales proceeds.
He was named in nine counts charging him with obstruction of
Congress, making false statements, obstructing Meese's Nov. 21-23,
1986 inquiry by making false statements and concealing, falsifying
and destroying classified government documents in NSC files.
   Also indicted Wednesday were former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Richard V. Secord and Albert
Hakim.
</TEXT>
