<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InmateDegrees     03-17 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Degrees,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Education Program Lauds Three New Graduates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men in red academic robes and mortarboards
walked across the platform at Boston University to receive their
master's degrees, and later walked back into prison.
   Steven Kelleher, Robert Layne and Gene Perry, inmates at the
medium-security Bay State Correctional Center in Norfolk, became
the first master's recipients under a 16-year-old prison education
program.
   ``You begin to see your relationship with society and what you
owe to it,'' said Kelleher, 36, in the seventh year of a 12- to
20-year sentence for armed robbery. ``It puts everything in a
different light.''
   Layne, 41, serving two consecutive terms for possession of a
firearm and receiving stolen property, said higher education leads
to more responsible action in society.
   ``Life is decision making,'' said Layne. ``Bad decisions put you
in jail. The more complex and complicated the decision, the more
education is needed to make the right choice.''
   ``It was tough to study after being away for all those years,''
said Perry, 41, who has served eight years for second-degree
murder. ``But after I got the hunger to learn, it was something
that just took over.''
   All three, bestowed Master of Liberal Arts degrees Wednesday,
got their undergraduate degrees in prison and each expressed a
desire to perform counseling or social work once free.
   The three graduates join about 60 other degree recipients in the
program, which has served more than 500 inmates at the medium
security state prison at Norfolk prison and the adjacent minimum
security correctional center with classes from high school
equivalency to postgraduate.
   ``This is the true model for education for all,'' said Elizabeth
``Ma'' Barker, a BU professor emeritus and founder of the school's
Prison Program. ``This is truly education befitting all free men.''
   BU pays for textbooks and teacher salaries and the state
subsidizes tutition for the inmates. In 1985, the non-profit
Massachusetts Council on Prison Education was formed representing
11 higher education institutions offering classes to inmates,
including BU and Curry College in Milton.
   BU President John Silber told the nearly 100 friends, family and
educators at Wednesday's ceremony that some consider the program an
unnecessary frill.
   ``These are individuals who society deemed not worthy of being
free,'' said Silber. ``Through education, they become useful
citizens catering to the society they depend on. They are earning
their right to be free.''
</TEXT>
