<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Diabetes     03-17 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diabetes,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Caution Against Routine Use of Treatment of Juvenile
Diabetes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite promising preliminary results, physicians
should not routinely use a transplant drug to treat childhood
diabetes until experts learn its long-term safety and
effectiveness, doctors cautioned today.
   A report by French doctors is the latest in a series of studies
demonstrating that the drug cyclosporine seems to help victims of
juvenile diabetes, also known as Type 1 or insulin-dependent
diabetes.
   The report showed that half of the youngsters treated with the
drug did not need insulin shots one year after their therapy began.
   The study was conducted by Dr. P.F. Bougneres and colleagues at
St. Vincent de Paul Hospital in Paris and published in today's New
England Journal of Medicine.
   An accompanying editorial noted that cyclosporine can harm the
kidneys and ``is not an ideal drug.''
   ``We believe that it is still premature to advocate the use of
cyclosporine for patients who are not enrolled in clinical trials
in which the response to treatment and adverse effects are
carefully monitored,'' wrote Drs. Kevan C. Herold and Arthur H.
Rubenstein of the University of Chicago.
   Cyclosporine suppresses the body's immune system. It is widely
used after transplants to prevent rejection of the new organ.
   Although cyclosporine has been the subject of studies by several
research groups in recent years, experts still do not know the
long-term effects and hazards of the drug when used to treat
juvenile diabetes.
   The National Center for Health Statistics estimates that about 7
percent of all Americans are diabetic. The disease is the
underlying cause of 36,000 deaths each year.
   Usually the disease strikes during adulthood and can be
controlled without insulin shots. Only about one in 10 diabetics
has the juvenile-onset form of the disease, which usually destroys
the body's ability to make insulin. People with the juvenile form
face an increased risk of such complications as blindness, heart
disease and kidney failure.
   In the French study, 40 youngsters with recently diagnosed
diabetes were treated with cyclosporine. The researchers found that
two-thirds were in remission after four months, and half after 12
months.
   Those helped by the drug started getting treatment an average of
three weeks after diagnosis. Those for whom it failed started
therapy seven weeks after diagnosis.
</TEXT>
