<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KillerBees     03-17 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Killer Bees,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Swarms of Africanized Bees Found In New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two swarms of so-called killer bees were
discovered on the waterfront earlier this month in a leaking
shipment of honey from Guatemala but were apparently trapped and
destroyed, authorities said Wednesday.
   ``We have begun a two-week trapping program at the wharf to
ensure none escaped, however,'' said state Agriculture Commissioner
Bob Odom.
   Africanized, or killer, bees are more aggressive than the
domestic honey bee. Since they take over other hives, they are
considered a threat to the U.S. honey industry.
   The bees were taken from Africa to South America where they
escaped in the 1950s. They have been advancing northward since
then, but their movement is believed to have been stopped near
Tehuantepec, south of Mexico City.
   Odom said Customs officials spotted them buzzing around two
containers.
   ``The swarms were destroyed. The queens were found,'' said Tom
Rinderer, director of the Lousiana State University laboratory that
is the federal government's main research center on Africanized
bees.
   ``That's an important discovery. This is a complete destruction.
No question about it,'' he said.
   Rinderer said most of the bees were workers, which are not
involved in reproduction. ``If one or two of them got loose, it
doesn't mean a thing,'' he said.
   The shipment on which the bees were found originated in El
Salvador, said state entomologist John Impson.
   Odom said that killer bees have been found in Florida and
California, but officials believe the swarms were contained.
</TEXT>
