<1ST_LINE>r a PM-North-Hometown     03-17 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North-Hometown,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`We Still Believe In Ollie,' Mayor Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILMONT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Lt. Col. Oliver North's
hometown are steadfast in their belief that he's a hero, even after
he was indicted on charges of conspiracy in the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``We still believe in Ollie,'' Mayor Philip Mossman said
Wednesday night. ``If I took a poll right now I'd find that most
people here are in favor of Ollie. He's a folk hero around here.''
   ``I think he's taking the fall for higher-ups,'' added the
mayor's son Nick, the lone judge in this village of 1,600
residents. ``What I gather is that most people believe in him and I
think they'll support him to the end.''
   In rural Philmont, located about 30 miles south of Albany,
negative words about North are seldom heard. Hometown supporters
remember North, voted ``most handsome'' and ``most courteous'' by
his senior class in high school, as a go-getter.
   ``I remember him as a conscientious student, industrious and not
political,'' Thomas Givens, one of North's high school teachers and
a former neighbor, said of the fired National Security Council aide.
   Another teacher echoed the sentiment. ``North was a real swell
young kid, and now he's getting raked over the coals,'' said Robert
Bowes.
   ``The majority of the people down here are behind him,'' said
Russ Robertson, North's high school track coach. ``I think he was
just acting under orders. He was trying to do the best for his
country. It looks like Larry is the fall guy.''
   Residents know North as Larry, his middle name, to distinguish
him from his late father, Oliver Clay North, an Army colonel who
earned a Silver Star for valor in World War II.
   The younger North graduated in 1961 in a class of fewer than 50,
then left Philmont to attend the U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis,
Md. His mother, Ann, lives in Guilderland, a suburb of Albany. His
two younger brothers and a sister also have moved away from
Philmont.
</TEXT>
