<DOCNO> AP880317-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gore-What'sNext Bjt   03-17 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore-What's Next, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Week After Southern Wins, Gore Still Searching For Northern
Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week and a half after his breakthrough in the
South, Democrat Albert Gore Jr. is in need of another one: in a
state where a win will sustain his claim to be a real contender.
But Gore's campaign still is trying to find that state.
   He never expected it would be Illinois, although Gore's
presidential campaign poured an estimated $200,000 to $300,000 into
late television ads there in hopes of a surprisingly strong showing.
   And it's not likely to be the next big state, either. Michigan's
Democratic caucuses March 26 will determine a big chunk of
delegates _ 138. But the process here requires organization _ a
commodity Gore's campaign is short on.
   ``I think he's got to win some states, but I'm not saying which
one right now,'' said Larry Harrington, Gore's deputy campaign
manager and political director.
   Gore rocketed to the top tier of Democratic presidential
contenders on Super Tuesday by doing what he said he would do:
carry a good chunk of the South.
   He claimed five Southern states. Gore took a split decision in
Wyoming three days days earlier, which he points to as a win that,
with his victory in Nevada's caucuses, proves drawing power outside
the South.
   But no one will ride to the nomination on the strength of those
two small Western states. While Gore contends he has already
established himself as the moderate with national appeal, the rest
of the Democratic Party is awaiting proof in the series of Northern
and Midwestern states that stretch from now until the California
primary June 7.
   Still serving as a principal strategist for his own campaign,
Gore is studying the primary calender.
   The Gore campaign plans to set up some organization in virtually
all the remaining primary states, supporting his claim to be more
than a regional candidate.
   They don't want to single out any state as holding the best
potential for Gore, to avoid being drawn into a make-or-break
contest.
   Yet Gore must establish a Northern beachhead somewhere if he is
to continue to argue that he is the most electable candidate and
only real alternative to Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis. And
more importantly, if he is to keep up in delegates.
   He must single out some state or states to focus his budget for
television commercials.
   ``That's the real decision,'' said Harrington.
   A state to punch through, Gore called it.
   ``We've got a whole series of contests between now and June 7,''
Gore said, talking aboard his campaign plane this week. ``We're
going to compete in all of them, and in some we're going to punch
through.
   ``We're pushing everywhere ... and looking for the best
opportunity to make an all-out push to break through, and I think
there are a lot of opportunities,'' Gore said.
   A look at the primary calender reveals no easy choice, however.
None of the upcoming states offers the comfort of a natural base.
   He named nearly all the big ones as posing opportunity:
Connecticut, Ohio, Pennsylvania, New York, Indiana, Wisconsin,
California and New Jersey.
   He called Connecticut ``an opportunity to demonstrate real
strength,'' but at the same time a Dukakis ``backyard.''
   The campaign also considers New York as having potential, and
Wisconsin is another candidate.
   As it wrestles with the decision, Gore's campaign is
experiencing the growing pains associated with the new demands of a
national effort.
   It is struggling to add depth. This week it hired departed
candidate Bruce Babbitt's issues director, Bart Gellman, to help
craft policy positions. It has also put Harrington and press aide
Mike Kopp with the candidate to beef up Gore's traveling staff.
   Gore also says fund-raising has been spurred by Super Tuesday,
and he took in as much as $150,000 a day immediately after that
showing.
   Even so, the campaign is hardly a match for the well-heeled
Dukakis organization. Gore's schedule is being made up practically
on the fly.
   Gore sought endorsements from Democratic figures in Southern
states, and he has turned to state legislators in states like
Michigan and Connecticut.
   But Harrington called Michigan a particularly tough state for
Gore because of the need for an organization that can deliver in
the caucuses. Gore had virtually no organization there before this
week, and even now it is based primarily on the state House speaker
and other legislative leaders.
   Fewer than half a dozen supporters turned out for Gore's arrival
in Detroit Monday night, and his campaign advance man had only been
in the state a few hours before the candidate arrived.
   ``We're not going to blow the doors off there,'' Harrington said.
</TEXT>
