<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     03-17 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abbey Theater of Dublin Visits New York</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19th century Irish farmer longs for more of
the world than his family's farm but is reined in by his mother's
apron strings in ``The Great Hunger,'' presented by Dublin's Abbey
Theater, the national theater of Ireland.
   Based on a poem of the same title by Patrick Kavanagh, the play
by Tom MacIntyre develops as a series of episodes rather than
narrative. Some of Wednesday's second-night audience in the Triplex
at Manhattan Community College, apparently not enjoying theater of
indirection, left at intermission.
   One is reminded of a Beckett play. Actor Tom Hickey has the
more-than-scruffy clothes, aged, unshaven look and anguished
expressions of a Beckett protagonist. There's also a lot of noises,
nonsense syllables and silence. But there's more speech _ and a lot
more lively moving around _ than is usual in Beckett.
   The farmer, Paddy Maguire, lacks education and money and the
ability to escape from his small world. In one articulate passage
between Paddy and his sister toward the end of the play, they
exchange phrases: ``The young men and women. I might have joined
them. I remember a night we walked through the moon the four of us.
Seeking adventure.''
   The mother is represented on stage by a primitive wood carving,
seated, her lap a chair. There are seven in the cast, who sometimes
are children, Paddy's pigs, chickens or team of horses.
   Audience members who were interested seemed to be concentrating
so hard they didn't relax to laugh. One very funny few moments came
when a girl selling raffle tickets for the Catholic church joined
Paddy in a superior cluck-and-strut rooster-hen mating dance in his
barnyard.
   Much of the time Paddy sits on his gate or compensates for his
lack of female companionship. This may have sent some of the
audience home.
   Director Patrick Mason joined the company in 1977 and has
directed five Tom MacIntyre works. The current engagement, through
March 27, ends a tour of the Soviet Union and the United States.
   The last time the Abbey Theater was in New York was in 1976,
when it presented ``The Plough and the Stars'' at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music. Its last Manhattan appearance was on Broadway in
1937, with ``Juno and the Paycock'' and ``The Playboy of the
Western World.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ElderlyConsumers     03-17 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly Consumers,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lobbying and `Medigap' Fraud Against Elderly Denounced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shady organizations with official-sounding
names are using fear over the future of Social Security to get the
elderly to send them money, according to Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
who denounced the practice as a ``sham.''
   The solicitations are little more than efforts to raise money
for the organizations, which prey on the fears of the aged, McCain
told a Federal Trade Commission hearing on Wednesday.
   He called on the agency to investigate several organizations
which, he said, Consumer Reports magazine has identified as using
fraudulent fund-raising techniques.
   ``What all these mailings have in common is official-sounding
names and letterhead implying a special connection with Social
Security which simply does not exist,'' McCain said. ``In addition,
their messages imply that Social Security is in trouble _ which ...
is simply not the case.''
   While there are worthwhile organizations for the elderly, McCain
said, many of those sending out such solicitations do nothing more
than raise funds for their own coffers and send postcards to
congressional offices.
   ``Pure and simple ... this is a sham,'' McCain said, ``and its
victims are those who can least afford to take money needed for
their basic day-to-day needs and send it to such organizations.''
   ``Fraud against the elderly is a problem of increasing magnitude
_ one that deserves our active attention,'' McCain said at a
special FTC hearing on the problems of the aged.
   ``The number of people in the United States over the age of 65
now exceeds the entire population of Canada, and Americans 65 and
older make the fastest growing population segment in this
country,'' observed FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver in opening the
session.
   The Census Bureau estimated that there were about 29 million
Americans aged 65 and over as of 1986, while Canada was estimated
to have a total population of about 26 million.
   The FTC, which investigates fraud and antitrust matters, called
in a series of witnesses to discuss the problems of the elderly,
and what can be done to help.
   Testimony also focused on the so-called Medigap insurance plans,
designed to supplement Medicare and Medicaid benefits for the
elderly.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., said sales fraud in that industry is
costing the elderly as much as $3 billion annually.
   Commissioner Terri Calvani noted that the FTC is looking into
sales practices in this industry, which consumer groups say induce
many elderly people to purchase duplicative and unneeded coverage.
   However, Calvani noted that the commission is specifically
prohibited from regulating the insurance industry, so that
regardless of what it finds in the investigation, any action would
have to come from Congress or from the states.
   Telephone marketing fraud and medical quackery also are major
problems for elderly Americans, the witnesses said.
</TEXT>
