<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0351EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ireland'sAgony     03-17 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland's Agony,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>And Again: `The Politics of the Last Atrocity'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-IRA Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a Protestant gunman opened fire and
hurled grenades at a Roman Catholic funeral, another Protestant was
receiving a medal from a different group of Catholics for his
fortitude in a different atrocity.
   While three people lay dying in the Milltown cemetery in Belfast
on Wednesday, Gordon Wilson of Northern Ireland was in Limerick in
the Irish Republic, being honored for his words of love and
forgiveness after losing his daughter in an IRA bombing that killed
11 Protestants.
   Thus, as often happens in the 19-year cycle of violence savaging
Northern Ireland, two dreadful deeds four months apart came
together in a mixture of horror and poignancy.
   After the Nov. 8 bombing in Enniskillen, some optimists hoped
56-year-old Wilson's courageous example would ignite a grass-roots
rebellion against violence of all political stripes.
   Cynics, however, talked of ``the politics of the last atrocity''
_ the notion that no single bloodbath can turn hearts and minds to
peace, because sooner or later the other side will try to square
the books with a similar atrocity.
   Wednesday's attack is a severe setback to Northern Ireland's
British rulers, who believed they were on the way to shoving the
Irish Republican Army out of the Catholic mainstream.
   That was the purpose of the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement, which
gave the Irish government a say in the running of Northern Ireland
on the assumption that Catholics would come to see Dublin, rather
than the IRA, as their protector.
   The funeral bloodbath is bound to help the IRA, which is
fighting to drive the British from Protestant-dominated Northern
Ireland and recoup the loss of face it suffered over the
Enniskillen bombing.
   Wednesday's atrocity also showed just how thin a tightrope
Northern Ireland can be.
   The three people being buried were IRA guerrillas shot and
killed in Gibraltar March 6 as they allegedly prepared to plant a
car bomb, and the fact that they died unarmed had already scored
propaganda points for the IRA against Britain.
   Had the Belfast police turned out in force as they usually do at
IRA funerals, the unmasked gunman might never have mounted such a
blatant attack.
   But the police, reluctant to get into a fight with the mourners
that might hand the IRA yet more sympathy, stayed well away, and
none was around to disarm the attacker.
   Meanwhile, Gibraltar put the Irish government in a vice as well.
   On the one hand, Dublin was condemning the British for slaying
unarmed Irish people. But, then, it too regards the IRA as a mortal
enemy.
   So, while wringing its hands over the deaths, Dublin made sure
the guerrillas' cortege was shunted out of Irish territory with
minimal fanfare, and a state radio journalist was suspended for
airing interviews with leaders of Sinn Fein, the legal political
wing of the outlawed IRA, as the hearses drove north to Belfast.
   Ireland feels it has enough problems of unemployment,
emigration, crime and high taxes without having to deal with a
crisis it regards as being of Britain's making.
   The funeral shootings came on the eve of St. Patrick's Day, when
Dublin was preparing an extra big parade to commemorate its
millennium. The deaths had no visible impact on the shoppers
cramming central Dublin.
   But trouble was clearly brewing from the moment the Gibraltar
coffins crossed the border into Northern Ireland.
   Ulster Protestants have grown increasingly frustrated at their
failure to topple the Anglo-Irish Agreement, which they see as an
intolerable intrusion in affairs by a hostile Catholic state.
   Dublin's protests about the Gibraltar killings were, to
Protestants, an outrageous abuse of its rights of intervention
under the Anglo-Irish accord, considering that a car bombing was
allgedly being planned.
   As soon as the cortege entered Northern Ireland on Monday night
it was jeered and stoned by Protestants. Thus the prospect of a
Protestant gunman opening fire on the funeral was not as
far-fetched as might be imagined.
   The incidents come at a troubled time for Anglo-Irish relations
after the honeymoon engendered by the 1985 pact.
   A series of rancorous incidents have occurred over British
behavior in Ulster-related matters, in which the Gibraltar
shootings were only the latest irritant.
   However, at least one man remained optimistic. Gordon Wilson
told his audience in Limerick:
   ``I believe in the fundamental decency of all Irish people and
the longing for peace in all Irish hearts. I have no doubt about
that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Marcus Eliason, AP's London news editor, has
been covering Northern Ireland for 3{ years.
</TEXT>
