<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   03-17 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Question Honduras Move; Dole Backers Point To
Iran-Contra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contenders are expressing concern about
President Reagan's decision to send U.S. troops to Honduras today,
with Jesse Jackson calling it ``heavy-handed,'' while indictments
in the Iran-Contra affair are putting some political heat on George
Bush.
   Bob Dole's backers were quick to suggest that if Bush is the
Republican nominee, the Democrats will use the re-ignited
Iran-Contra affair as ammunition against him this fall.
   The Democrats didn't wait that long, however, with Richard
Gephardt calling the indictments evidence that the Reagan
administration has put the Constitution ``through the shredder.''
   Dole's beleaguered GOP campaign, meanwhile, came in for some
serious scrutiny on Wednesday, with Republican Party Chairman Frank
Fahrenkopf hinting that the Kansas senator should think about
throwing in the towel after his latest loss to Bush, in Illinois.
   But Dole, whose aides said he would stay in the race at least
until the Wisconsin primary on April 5, got some encouragement from
a dozen Senate supporters who met to talk about his prospects.
   ``I believe he should stay in,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley of
Iowa, one of the group. Grassley said the four indictments on
Wednesday in connection with the Iran-Contra affair were not
directly discussed but said: ``There's going to be some Reagan
baggage that George Bush has to contend with, and realistically
it's going to be problems for the Republicans this fall.''
   Former National Security Adviser John Poindexter, Lt. Col.
Oliver L. North, retired Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord and Secord's
business partner Albert Hakim were indicted on conspiracy charges
stemming from the diversion of secret Iran arms sale profits to
Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   ``What is going on with those four gentlemen has nothing to do
with this campaign,'' said Bush spokesman Pete Teeley.
   But Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., said, ``George can't duck
the issue. He's going to have to explain his role.''
   Fahrenkopf's remarks, however, seemed aimed at suggesting that
the Senate minority leader should abandon his bid. While stressing
his neutrality in the GOP campaign, the party chief said he had a
responsibility to ask Bush's rivals ``for some reflection.''
   Dole and former television evangelist Pat Robertson, he said,
should ``start thinking past the convention and start thinking
about November'' and the general election. Robertson has indicated
he will drastically scale back his campaign but remain in the race.
   Meanwhile, the Democrats, who have been eyeing each other warily
amid prospects of a deadlocked race, turned their fire on the
Reagan administration over both the Iran-Contra indictments and the
sending of four military battalions to Honduras in response to a
reported Nicaraguan incursion there.
   ``Sending in our troops is a bit heavy-handed,'' said Jackson.
``It's just not necessary.''
   Sen. Paul Simon also expressed concern, saying ``there is
skepticism on the part of all of us about anything'' the
administration does in Central America.
   Simon also hit the administration over the Iran-Contra affair,
saying the indictments underscore ``something fundamental'' _ that
the administration cannot be trusted to obey the law.
   ``We need a government we can trust,'' he said.
   That view was echoed by Democratic rival Gephardt.
   ``Whatever the outcome of these prosecutions, I think the
special prosecutor has given us fresh evidence that the Reagan
administration generally has put the Constitution of the United
States through the shredder,'' Gephardt said.
   Gephardt and Simon both campaigned Wednesday in Michigan, which
holds its Democratic caucuses March 26. Gephardt, running dead last
in Democratic delegate totals, desperately needs a strong showing
in the state.
   ``They say I'm the underdog,'' he said at a stop in Lansing. ``I
like being the underdog because the underdog usually does well.''
   The Missouri congressman will soon have to decide whether to
continue his presidential campaign or file for re-election to his
House seat. The filing deadline is March 29, three days after the
Michigan contest.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., still seeking a strong showing
outside the South, was campaigning today in Kansas, which holds
local party caucuses on Saturday. Gore was addressing the Kansas
House.
   Simon, who revived his campaign with a home-state victory in
Illinois on Tuesday, continued to predict that no one will be able
to patch together enough delegates for a first-ballot victory at
the national convention. He said he doubted he'd win in Michigan,
but added: ``I'd like to pick up as many delegates as I can.''
   Dukakis again expressed hopes that the Democratic contest
wouldn't come down to a fight at the convention. ``I think there is
agreement on the part of most Democrats across the country that
somebody will come out of this primary process with, if not an
absolute majority, a substantial plurality ... and that people will
rally behind that person,'' he said in Boston.
   ``Obviously, I hope I will be that person.''
   Dukakis remained the Democratic delegate leader even after being
shut out of the delegate race in Illinois. The latest AP delegate
count gave him 464.5; Jackson 460.55; Gore 354.8; Simon 171.5 and
Gephardt 145, with 2,082 needed to nominate.
   Dukakis also continued to lead the Democratic field in federal
matching funds. The Federal Election Commission on Wednesday
certified Dukakis for another $600,000 in matching funds, bringing
his total to nearly $5.7 million.
</TEXT>
