<DOCNO> AP880317-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IrishDiscrimination     03-17 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish Discrimination,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy, King Protest Discrimination In N. Ireland, British `Death
Squads'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II and leading civil
rights activists say British troops are acting like Latin American
``death squads'' where Northern Ireland is concerned.
   ``The British today, under the rule of Mrs. (Prime Minister
Margaret) Thatcher, are advocating just the kind of death squads
the Congress of the United States condemns every day,'' the
Massachusetts Democrat said outside the British Embassy on the eve
of St. Patrick's Day.
   Kennedy, the great-great-grandson of Irish immigrants, was
joined by Martin Luther King III, Cesar Chavez, the Rev. Joseph
Lowery, Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., and Rep. Albert Bustamante,
D-Texas, for a 50-minute meeting with British Ambassador Antony
Acland.
   The long-scheduled embassy meeting came just hours after
attackers lobbed grenades and fired shots into a heavily attended
funeral in Belfast for three slain Irish Republican Army
guerrillas. The trio, unarmed, were shot March 6 by British troops
in Gilbraltar.
   British authorities say the three IRA members were on a bombing
mission. The outlawed IRA is fighting to push the British out of
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland, which remains part of the
United Kingdom.
   Kennedy and the other activists condemned the violence of the
Catholic IRA and rival Protestant paramilitary units. But they
blamed the British government for providing ``enthusiastic
support'' to the British security forces and for not prosecuting
soldiers.
   ``Killers and perjurers should be brought to justice and the
world should know the truth,'' the group wrote in a letter to Mrs.
Thatcher delivered to the ambassador.
   After the closed meeting, Kennedy said Acland's comments
exemplified the ``callousness'' the British show toward the Irish.
   ``What we see today in Northern Ireland is complete abandonment
by the British government of real justice issues,'' Kennedy told
reporters outside the embassy compound. ``They're not fundamentally
committed to change in Northern Ireland.''
   The embassy said only that ``it was a frank discussion on both
sides.''
   But an embassy official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, derided the ``death squad'' analogy.
   ``We regard that frankly as over the top,'' the official said.
``Death squads imply shooting at will.'' British troops, the
official said, have strict orders to fire only if their lives or
others are in danger.
   Kennedy urged Britain to impose new laws to protect Catholics
against the type of discrimination that has resulted in up to 80
percent unemployment among Catholic men in some parts of Northern
Ireland.
   ``Unless you get people employed in that country, you're not
going to see the cycle of violence change,'' said Kennedy, a
freshman congressman and the eldest son of the late Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy.
   ``The fact is, folks, what we still face today in Northern
Ireland is discrimination, discrimination just as bad as we faced
in the 1960s and earlier in our country,'' he said.
   Kennedy lambasted new British proposals for fair employment
legislation as ``empty rhetoric'' that lack timetables demanding
tangible improvement.
   King, the son of the late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., and
Lowery, president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
said the arguments the ambassador gave against affirmative action
programs were the same ones voiced by opponents of the U.S. civil
rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
   King, who said his father would have been at the embassy
Wednesday to protest Britain's actions if he were alive, said
discrimination ``in all its forms is wrong, whether it's in a
public place or a private boardroom in the United States, in South
Africa or in Ireland.''
   Quoting his slain father, King said: ``Injustice which is
allowed to flourish anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
