<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Japan-Trade     03-17 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Trade,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delay Urged In Action Aimed At Opening Japanese Construction
Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's top economic advisers have
urged a two-week delay in proposed action seeking to open Japan's
multibillion construction market to U.S. companies, administration
officials say.
   The delay, backed on Tuesday by Reagan's Cabinet-level Economic
Policy Committee, will permit time for last-ditch negotiations,
requested by Japan, to resolve the dispute, said officials who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   However, if the negotiations _ to begin this weekend _ fail,
then the administration is likely to proceed with the trade case,
which could result in stiff retaliatory tariffs against Japan, the
sources said.
   The council, headed by Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III,
put off a recommendation by senior staff members calling for
presidential action against Japan on the issue, pending the result
of the talks, the sources said.
   Japan will send a special negotiating team to Washington this
weekend to meet with U.S. officials in an effort to end the bitter
dispute, said the officials.
   ``They proposed sending a high-level representative to meet with
us. We've taken them up on it,'' said one administration official
present at the Cabinet session.
   The Cabinet unit agreed that there ``would be no
pre-conditions'' on the negotiations, and that the results would
have to be satisfactory to both nations for further action to be
abandoned, the official said.
   Failure of U.S. construction companies to win contracts on
Japanese public works projects, including the new $8 billion Kansai
International Airport, has been a major trade irritant between the
two nations.
   Last month, top administration staff members recommended that
President Reagan initiate a trade action against Japan on grounds
that Japan has resisted opening its construction market to U.S.
companies.
   According to the sources, Commerce Secretary C. William Verity
opened Tuesday's session with a call for initiation of the trade
action against Japan _ an action that could result in tariffs equal
to the amount of lost business to U.S. construction companies.
   However, the Cabinet was told of a new offer by Japan to resolve
the dispute, and the group agreed to await the result of the
two-week talks before recommending further action to President
Reagan, the sources said.
   U.S. construction companies claim they have been all but barred
from bidding on such projects in Japan. Some $60 billion of
Japanese construction projects are at stake, according to industry
officials.
   Japanese Prime Minister Naburo Takeshita, in his visit with
President Reagan earlier this year, brought with him a proposal he
said would open more Japanese construction projects to U.S.
companies.
   However, the administration said that the proposal _ which
focused on joint ventures between U.S. and Japanese companies _ did
not go nearly far enough.
   Japanse construction firms, by contrast, do an estimated $1.8
billion worth of business each year in the United States.
   However, Congress late last year voted to ban future Japanese
participation in U.S. public works projects _ which include planned
work on a segment of the Washington subway system _ until the issue
is resolved.
   U.S. construction industry officials have claimed that Japanese
red tape for bidding on such projects in Japan makes it virtually
impossible for Americans to win contracts.
   For instance, they claim, one requirement for participation in
such projects is extensive prior experience on similar Japanese
projects _ experience that U.S. industry officials claim it is
almost impossible for American outfits to acquire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
