<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Iran-Contra-Thumbnails     03-17 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iran-Contra-Thumbnails,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the men indicted by
a federal grand jury Wednesday on charges stemming from the
Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OLIVER L. NORTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   North, a Marine lieutenant colonel, is a former member of the
National Security Council staff. He played the central role in
supervising the arms shipments to Iran and in helping coordinate
assistance to the Nicaraguan rebels during the 1985-86 period when
Congress barred U.S. government aid for the rebels.
   He was fired from his NSC post in November 1986 when the
Iran-Contra affair first became public.
   Born in San Antonio, Texas, North, 44, was raised in Philmont,
N.Y. He graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy, where he was a
boxing champion. He received numerous medals for heroism in the
Vietnam War. North and his wife, Betsy, have four children. He
lives in Great Falls, Va.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JOHN M. POINDEXTER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Poindexter, a retired rear admiral, had a lifelong career with
the Navy. Born in Odom, Ind., Poindexter, 51, received a Ph.D in
nuclear physics from California Institute of Technology in 1964.
   He joined the National Security Council staff in June 1981 as a
military assistant, succeeding Robert C. McFarlane as President
Reagan's national security adviser in December 1985. Earlier in his
career he was on the personal staff of three Navy secretaries and
was the top assistant to the chief of naval operations.
   His wife, Linda, is an ordained Episcopal priest. They have five
sons.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RICHARD V. SECORD</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Secord, 55, a retired major general in the Air Force, spent
virtually his entire career in the military. A native of LaRue,
Ohio, Secord graduated from West Point. He was one of the first
American combat pilots in Vietnam. Early in his career, he also ran
bombing missions for the CIA from Laos. He resigned from the Air
Force in 1983 after federal investigators looked into his
relationship with former CIA agent Edwin Wilson, who was convicted
of selling weapons to Libya.
   Secord and his business associate, Albert Hakim, were the two
most prominent figures among the clandestine operators who assisted
North in supplying the Nicaraguan Contras.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALBERT HAKIM</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hakim, 51, a naturalized American born in Iran, is a businessman
based in Los Gatos, Calif. Hakim left Iran for good in 1978 when
the shah of Iran was forced from power. In the mid-1970s, Hakim met
Secord in Tehran; the two later became business partners.
   Hakim travels frequently, rarely staying in the same place for
long. His second wife was born in South Korea. Investigators say
Hakim was the money man who handled the accounts and financial
arrangements in the Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-WhiteHouse-HondurasText     03-17 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-White House-Honduras Text,220</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the statement
Wednesday night by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater on
President Reagan's decision to send U.S. military battalions on an
``emergency deployment readiness exercise'' to Honduras:
   In light of the significant cross-border incursion by Sandinista
armed forces into Honduras from Nicaragua, and at the request of
the government of Honduras, the president has ordered the immediate
deployment of an infantry brigade task force consisting of two
battalions of the 82nd Airborne Division from Fort Bragg (N.C.),
two battalions from the 7th Infantry Division at Fort Ord, Calif.,
plus supporting units to Palmerola Air Force Base in Honduras for
an emergency deployment readiness exercise.
   In addition to its value as a test of the proficiency of our
military units, this exercise is a measured response designed to
show our staunch support to the democratic government of Honduras,
at a time when its territorial integrity is being violated by the
Cuban- and Soviet-supported Sandinista army.
   This exercise is also intended as a signal to the governments
and peoples of Central America of the seriousness with which the
U.S. government views the current situation in the region.
   The duration of this exercise has not been decided.
   The brigade task force will not be deployed to any area of
ongoing hostilities.
</TEXT>
