<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiuKilling     03-17 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liu Killing,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gangster Convicted In Murder Of Chinese-American Journalist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gangster who testified he killed a
Chinese-American journalist on orders of the Taiwanese government
was convicted of murder by a jury that deliberated just 45 minutes.
   Tung Kuie-sen, a member of the international United Bamboo Gang,
was convicted Wednesday of first-degree murder in the Oct. 15,
1984, slaying of dissident writer Henry Liu, who was gunned down in
his garage in Daly City.
   Tung, 36, admitted to the San Mateo County Superior Court jury
that he killed Liu, but he claimed he carried out the act for
patriotic rfused to
offer a plea bargain and Tung wanted to tell his side of the story
in public, said defense attorney Douglas Gray.
   Judge Margaret J. Kemp set Tung's sentencing for May 11. Tung
faces 25 years to life in prison for murder and two years for use
of a firearm.
   Earlier Wednesday, during cross-examination, Tung testified the
plot to murder Liu went as high as the then-head of Taiwan's secret
police, who also was the son of President Chiang Ching-kuo, who
died in January.
   Liu was known for his writings critical of Chiang. Some of the
writings included personal details of the lives of Taiwan's ruling
family.
   Tung is the only one of Liu's suspected killers to be brought to
trial in the United States.
   Wang Hsi-ling, the Taiwanese vice admiral who some believe
orchestrated the plot, and his two aides were convicted in Taiwan
of the murder and are serving life sentences.
   Wang reportedly wanted Liu killed because he feared he was about
to embarrass Chiang by publishing memoirs of a former high-ranking
Taiwanese official.
   Tung testified he believed he was duped by his own government
into killing a man who was not a traitor. Tung asked in a written
statement sent to the judge Wednesday that a written apology be
given to Liu's widow, Helen.
   Tung confessed to his role in Liu's killing two years ago during
a heroin smuggling trial in federal court in New York. Tung was
acquitted of racketeering in that case, but found guilty of
smuggling 660 pounds of heroin into the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
