<HEAD>Carlucci Keeping Abreast Of Central American Developments From
Switzerland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci was
monitoring events in Central America while in the Swiss capital for
meetings with his Soviet counterpart, aides say.
   Carlucci discussed Nicaragua in general terms with Soviet
Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov on Wednesday, said a Pentagon
spokesman, but it was not clear how deeply they delved into that
issue.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon spokesman, told reporters that
``regional issues were discussed .... Angola, Afghanistan,
Nicaragua, Korea.'' But he declined to disclose the substance of
the talks.
   Carlucci and Yazov met for 10 minutes with only their
translators present at the beginning of an afternoon session at the
Soviet Embassy, but the topic of that conversation remained secret.
   Aides to Carlucci worked through the night Wednesday and early
today, remaining in close contact with the Pentagon and White
House. They declined, however, to divulge the secretary's exact
role in the decision to send 3,200 U.S. troops to Honduras for what
the White House called ``an emergency deployment readiness
exercise''
