<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Prime-TimeThief     03-17 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime-Time Thief,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thief Targets Occupied Homes During Prime-Time Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are looking for a prime-time prowler
who slips into homes to take cash and jewelry while the residents
are watching television.
   At least 55 such burglaries have occurred since December in the
Denver area, police say.
   ``It's a little bizarre,'' Sgt. Pat Whitman of nearby Cherry
Hills Village said Wednesday. ``Most burglars would rather find an
empty house than a resident inside.''
   Denver Sgt. Bill Wiederspan says he's no psychiatrist, but he
has theories.
   ``Either it's psychological and he does it for the thrills. Or,
he's imitating burglars on TV shows and he's been watching too much
TV,'' he said.
   In as many as six houses a night, a prowler has entered, usually
through unlocked doors or windows, and fled with a few selected
items such as rifles, jewelry boxes, wallets or purses.
   The first possible confrontation with the prime-time prowler
occurred Monday night when a Cherry Hills resident came out of the
shower to find a stranger in his home.
   ``What are you doing here?'' the resident asked.
   ``Don't worry. I'm just leaving,'' said the tall, slender young
stranger, backing away and fleeing out a back door. A watch later
was discovered missing, authorities said.
   The intruder, whose visits last only a few minutes, is so neat
that many victims don't realize for some time that anyone has been
in the house. In a few instances, the homeowner has heard something
and the prowler has fled empty-handed.
   But authorities fear violence is not far away.
   ``I think it's just a matter of time,'' Wiederspan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
