<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama-Macias     03-17 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Macias,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coup Leader Had Been Noriega Defender</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Leonidas Macias, the alleged
leader of a failed coup, in recent months had been a staunch
defender of the nation's military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   When President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried unsuccessfully to
remove Noriega as chief of the 15,000-member Defense Forces on Feb.
25, it was Macias who heatedly told reporters that Delvalle himself
would go before Noriega.
   Within hours, Delvalle was deposed by the Legislative Assembly
in a Noriega-orchestrated move.
   During the past year Macias, about 50, has been chief of police,
a job that put him in charge of about 5,000 officers and
administrative employees.
   They include the riot police, who have forcibly put down street
demonstrations against the government since last June.
   But after light arms fire broke out in the Defense Forces
headquarters on Wednesday, the military said that Macias, three
majors, a captain and some civilians were arrested after ``an
attempt by several officers to take over the headquarters of our
institution was foiled.''
   Panama's civil unrest began after accusations last summer that
Noriega was involved in crimes ranging from political assassination
to drug trafficking.
   Noriega was indicted on federal drug charges in Florida last
month.
   Some of those arrested in the anti-Noriega demonstrations have
accused Macias of allowing others to beat them while in custody.
One of those detained told the opposition-aligned Human Rights
Association that Macias took part in at least one beating. Macias
denied the accusations.
   Macias had conducted a public relations campaign with reporters
to counter the anti-Noriega drive, holding several news conferences
to report on events in the Defense Forces. He was the only
high-ranking officer to do so.
   In recent months, Macias called three news conferences, one
Christmas lunch and invited journalists to his home, always saying
in a jovial manner that nothing was happening.
   During a protest strike that began Feb. 29, Macias took
journalists around the city on a bus saying: ``Look, there's
nothing happening here. Everything is fine. Look at me, I'm
unarmed. What policeman like myself can move around the streets of
his city without being armed?''
   But he could be harsh with the opposition.
   On Feb. 29, he took Chamber of Commerce President Aurelio
Barria, who had been arrested a few hours earlier, before
reporters. ``Clown!'' he yelled at Barria. ``Look at him, he's
fine. You can go home!''
   Barria was detained for trying to enter the Chamber of Commerce
building, which had been closed by the government four days earlier.
   Although Macias was considered one of the colonels most loyal to
Noriega, there had been rumors before Wednesday that while they
kept up the appearance of good relations, there were problems
between the two men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
