<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     03-17 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$3.5 Million In Matching Funds Certified By FEC For 11 Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission has certified
almost $3.5 million in new federal matching funds for 11
presidential candidates, including nearly $900,000 for Pat
Robertson whose Republican campaign is winding down.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis continued to lead the
Democratic money race, qualifying for more than $600,000 in new
matching funds and raising his matching total to more than twice
that of his competitors for his party's nomination.
   Dukakis' closest Democratic rivals Jesse Jackson and Tennesee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. qualify for a little more than $300,000 and
$336,000 respectively.
   Vice President George Bush, who has a big lead in the Republican
contest, got in line for a new quarter of a million dollars in
federal funds, keeping his edge in the category.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole is eligible for almost $390,000.
   In all, the new funds certified on Wednesday raise the total
certified thus far for 14 candidates to $45.44 million.
   Presidential candidates qualify for matching funds by raising at
least $5,000 in individual contributions of $250 or less in at
least 20 states. After qualifying, every individual contribution of
$250 or less is matched dollar-for-dollar by federal funds. The
money comes from the voluntary $1 checkoff on federal tax returns.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Illinois Couple Backs Rival Republican Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl and Karen Hawkinson will be taking a
trip to New Orleans together this summer as delegates to the
Republican National Convention _ but that's where the togetherness
ends.
   The couple were elected Tuesday as GOP delegates, but he
supports Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and she backs Vice President George
Bush.
   ``We didn't really expect to both be elected but that's the way
it turned out,'' Hawkinson said.
   Even though Bush is the front-runner, Mrs. Hawkinson said
winning her delegate slot was a surprise because Dole was
considered the favorite in their congressional district.
   Her husband's win was not as as unpredictable, she said.
   ``Carl has held office since 1976 _ people are used to voting
for him,'' she said. ``But I had never been on a ballot before.''
   The two said campaigning for rival candidates made their home
life a little hectic, but they avoided the kind of spats that have
colored the Bush-Dole battle for the nomination.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cuomo Authorizes State Primary Date Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo has signed legislation to
switch the date of the New York state primary to keep it from
falling on the Jewish holiday of Rosh Hashana.
   The primary, not to be confused with New York's April 19
presidential primary, will be held Thursday, Sept. 15. It was
originally scheduled two days earlier.
   Three other states had switched their primaries already to
prevent the conflict. Connecticut and Rhode Island will hold their
primaries Sept. 14, while Massachusetts will join New York with a
primary Sept. 15.
   Six states _ Arizona, Minnesota, New Hampshire, Utah, Vermont
and Wisconsin _ will hold primaries on Rosh Hashana, Sept. 13.
   In New York, Jews usually represent 20 percent or more of the
vote in Democratic primary contests.
   The state primaries which were swithced on Wednesday determine
nominations for governor, state legislative seats, Congress and
local offices.
</TEXT>
