<1ST_LINE>r w PM-North     03-17 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tearful North Vows To Fight Allegations: `I Will Never Give Up'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North says he will fight the
criminal allegations against him ``for as long as necessary''
despite heavy personal and financial costs.
   ``I did not commit any crime,'' North said Wednesday a few hours
after a federal grand jury indicted him and three others on
conspiracy charges stemming from the Iran-Contra affair. ``I intend
to fight allegations of wrongdoing for as long as necessary.''
   Appearing ashen-faced and grim, North said he was aware of the
high personal and financial costs of fighting the charges, but ``I
can assure you, I will never give up, we will win.''
   North thanked the American people ``who have shown so much love
and concern these past 16 months by their millions of telegrams and
letters and prayers and support.''
   The Marine officer said that he was caught in the cross-fire of
a bitter dispute between Congress and the president over Central
America, and that ``it is a shame the new battleground for such a
fight will be in a courtroom.''
   Beside North was his lawyer, Brendan Sullivan, who also
represented North at last summer's hearings before joint committees
of the Senate and House.
   Sullivan, whose spirited defense of his client was one of the
highlights of the hearings, said that seeking Wednesday's
indictment ``was one of the worst prosecutorial decisions in the
history of our country.''
   ``It is a decision of an unaccountable prosecutor who came to
Washington determined to allege that some crime, any crime had been
committed,'' Sullivan said.
   Sullivan added that Lawrence E. Walsh, the independent counsel
``presents an indictment after 15 months (of investigation) based
on mistaken facts, novel and sometimes ridiculous legal theories.''
   ``Everyone must seriously wonder about a decision to indict a
man like Oliver North, a highly decorated Marine Corps officer,
based on his tireless effort in the interests of his country,''
Sullivan said.
   For his part, North said it was a sad irony that the decision to
indict should occur on the fourth anniversary of the abduction in
Lebanon of William Buckley and the third anniversary of the
kidnapping of Terry Anderson, The Associated Press' chief Middle
East correspondent.
</TEXT>
