<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Rejects Iroquois Gas Pipeline Plan, Cites Applachian
Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The developer of a proposed 358-mile Northeast
natural gas pipeline is vowing to find a more suitable place for
the project to cross the Appalachian Trail.
   Officials at Iroquois Gas Transmission System said Wednesday
they are confident of finding a new cross-over site that would
satisfy Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel, who rejected the
current plan.
   Hodel, in a letter to Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr. R-Conn.
released Wednesday, said the current Iroquois pipeline plan would
cross the 2,000-mile Appalachian Trail at a point in New York near
the Connecticut border where it would have ``significant
environmental and scenic impacts.''
   ``The plan now is to find a place along the New York-Connecticut
border where we can cross,'' said company spokesman Gary B. Davis.
``We will have to sit down with the Park Service again and discuss
our concern. ... Something will have to be worked out.''
   The pipeline would have to cross the Appalachian Trail at some
point. The project would bring Canadian natural gas from Ontario
through New York and Connecticut to Long Island, serving New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut. The hiking trail runs from Maine to
Georgia.
   The $384 million project is the first and most prominent
Northeast gas line proposal under consideration by the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Minority Leader Given Humanitarian Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel expected to
accept a humanitarian award without much fanfare, but he ended up
singing for his supper.
   After first being serenaded by James Maloof, the mayor of his
hometown of Peoria, Ill., Michel listened Wednesday night as 22 of
his congressional colleagues began a less than skillful rendition
of ``Old Man River.''
   They gave up after struggling through a few bars, called Michel
to the stage and resumed with the Republican leader doing the
leading.
   ``He is to singing what Frank Sinatra is to legislating,''
quipped White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker, one of the
speakers toasting Michel at the Variety Club of Greater
Washington's awards dinner.
   The GOP leader was presented with the Humanitarian of the Year
award in recognition of his charity work during 32 years on Capitol
Hill, said former Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, the
chairman of the dinner committee and a fellow Illinoisan who served
with Michel in the House.
   The Variety Club of Greater Washington, a non-profit, charitable
organization which helps handicapped and underprivileged children,
said proceeds from the $500 a plate event will provide money for
children who need artificial limbs.
