<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0554 03-17 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-LaRouche, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0554,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Say They Learned Lesson And So Did Voters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``Ms. Pucinski'' to restore dropped word
``clerk.'' CORRECTS category code.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defeats of extremist Lyndon LaRouche and his
followers in the Illinois primary show the state Democratic party
learned a lesson two years ago and passed it on to voters, party
officials say.
   ``The nation became aware of what happened in Illinois in 1986,
and I think we have pretty well put that to rest,'' said George
Sangmeister, who won his Democratic congressional primary Tuesday
over a LaRouche-backed opponent, George M. Laurence of Romeoville.
   No one answered the telephone at Laurence's home or at LaRouche
headquarters late Wednesday to comment on the primary results.
   Sangmeister, of Mokena, was one of two party-endorsed candidates
who went down in a surprising defeat to LaRouche supporters in
1986, sending shock waves throughout the state Democratic party.
   Mark Fairchild defeated Sangmeister for the Democratic
nomination for lieutenant governor that year. Another LaRouche
disciple, Janice Hart, beat party candidate Aurelia Pucinski for
the nomination for secretary of state.
   The party's state central committee declared the nominations
void, and neither LaRouche candidate won office.
   This year, despite Democratic court challenges, LaRouche and
more than 20 of his supporters were on Tuesday's primary ballot for
offices from president to county recorder of deeds. Democrats
countered with a mail campaign.
   Ms. Pucinski defeated Mrs. Hart in the Democratic primary race
for Cook County Circuit Court clerk, and Sangmeister easily
defeated Laurence for the congressional nomination.
   Unofficial vote totals gave Sangmeister 26,979 votes to
Laurence's 7,518. In the clerk's race, Ms. Pucinski had 283,504,
former Mayor Jane Byrne had 199,306 and Ms. Hart had 12,530 for 2
percent of the vote.
   LaRouche got 6,036 votes in the presidential primary, according
to unofficial totals _ not even 1 percent.
   Two years ago, the Fairchild victory caused Adlai E. Stevenson
to give up his Democratic nomination for governor, saying he would
not run with a LaRouche extremist. Stevenson, calling LaRouche's
views ``neo-Nazi,'' then formed the Illinois Solidarity Party but
subsequently lost to the incumbent, Republican Gov. James R.
Thompson.
   LaRouche, whose headquarters are in Leesburg, Va., is seeking
the Democratic nomination on a platform that includes quarantining
AIDS patients and populating Mars.
   LaRouche is on trial in Boston on federal fraud and conspiracy
charges.
   ``The party and I decided we were not going to afford these and
other fringe candidates the opportunity to have a refuge here,''
declared Vince Demuzio, who became state party chairman after the
LaRouche victories.
   The LaRouche forces did win an upset this month in Houston, when
Claude Jones was elected Harris County Democratic Party chairman in
the Texas primary on March 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
