<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan-Spy     03-17 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Spy,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Journalist Convicted of Spying in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan court sentenced an Italian journalist to
seven years in prison after convicting him of spying while
accompanying anti-government guerrillas, the official Soviet news
agency Tass reported.
   Fausto Balezlavo of Trieste entered Afghanistan illegally in
July and followed Ahmad Shahom, one of the guerrilla leaders
fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government, Tass said.
   Balezlavo was a social sciences student at a university in
Trieste, Tass said in a report Wednesday. It did not say when he
was convicted, but indicated Balezlavo was sentenced Wednesday in
Kabul, the Afghan capital.
   It also did not say whether Balezlavo challenged the charges or
for whom he was accused of spying. Tass also did not say for whom
Balezlavo was working.
   The Afghan rebels are supported by Pakistan and the United
States.
   Balezlavo is the second European journalist to be convicted of
spying in Afghanistan.
   Alain Guillo, a French freelance filmmaker, was convicted Jan. 4
of spying while accompanying guerrillas. He was sentenced to 10
years in prison.
   Two Americans were killed last year while making a documentary
film in Afghanistan.
   Western correspondents are not allowed into Afghanistan except
on government-arranged trips.
   The seven main Afghan guerrilla groups, based in Pakistan,
routinely take Western journalists into Afghanistan illegally to
report on the fighting against government troops supported by an
estimated 115,000 Soviet soldiers.
</TEXT>
