<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NudeModels     03-17 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nude Models,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cobb County Bans Nude Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art students will have to stretch their
imaginations in life-drawing class now that a county official has
banned nude models.
   Bob Ash, head of the Cobb County Community Services Department,
who a few weeks ago asked that models wear bathing suits, leotards
or ``just basically anything,'' because of fear about how nude
modeling might be perceived.
   ``The community might react in a negative way,'' Ash said.
   ``My students don't understand,'' said Stephen Smith, an Atlanta
artist who has taught life drawing and life sculpting courses at
the county-run Steeple House Arts Center since shortly after its
January 1987 opening. Nude models had been used only in Smith's
advanced, adults-only art classes.
   The issue of nudity in art will be addressed tonight by the
county's five-member Arts Commission. Ash has said he will abide by
the commission's decision, though he may disagree with it.
   ``I am surprised that it would become an issue in this day and
time,'' said Carolyn Duncan, director of the Marietta-Cobb Fine
Arts Center, which is funded in part by Cobb County but not bound
by Ash's decision. The Steeple House is fully funded by the county.
   Cobb Arts Commissioner Pat Wayman said prohibiting the study of
nudes in art ``would take us back 300 years.'' She said the fact
that a piece features a nude figure does not mean it is
pornographic.
</TEXT>
