<2ND_LINE>PM-$1,157 Glasses,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Squished Eyeglasses Dispute Costs City, Union, $1,157</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal dispute over a $135 pair of
glasses damaged on the seat of a fire truck will cost the city and
firefighters union $1,157.
   ``If nothing else, it was a good learning experience,'' Lt.
Cecil Cornish, president of International Association of
Firefighters Local 2445, said Wednesday of the union's $578.50
share.
   The union filed a grievance after Frank Neeld, vice president of
the local, left his glasses on the seat Sept. 19. The next day,
firefighter Timothy Gutman sat on them as he climbed behind the
wheel.
   Neeld demanded reimbursement under a contract clause calling for
repair or replacement of glasses damaged or destroyed ``in the line
of duty.''
   ``Leaving glasses on the seat of a firetruck where anyone could
have reason to drive it was negligent,'' contended City Manager
Randall Reid. ``And being on duty or at work was not what the
contract intended by `in the line of duty.'
   Arbitrator J.A. Raffaele of Philadelphia sided with the city in
a March 13 ruling on the grievance. ``The dignity of a
collective-bargaining agreement,'' he wrote, ``should not be
compromised by an interpretation that reduces its meaning to
absurdity.''
</TEXT>
