<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Carlucci-Honduras 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 03-17 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-Honduras, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0569,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Defense Chiefs Discuss Central America</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with Yazov's comments. Pick
up 7th graf pvs: `Carlucci described...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
said he and his Soviet counterpart briefly debated the reported
Nicaraguan incursion into Honduras today before concluding three
days of talks on an upbeat note.
   Carlucci said he protested the incursion to Soviet Defense
Minister Dmitri Yazov, who ``made some attempt to defend the
Sandinista action.''
   ``I would not characterize it as a vigorous defense,'' Carlucci
told a news conference before leaving Bern for Washington.
   Carlucci said he consulted with the White House overnight and
endorsed the decision to send an emergency U.S. force to Honduras
on exercises.
   The Sandinistas said they had chased Contra rebels to the
Honduran border, but the Nicaraguan defense ministry denied
Sandinista troops entered Honduras.
   The Soviet Union provides Nicaragua with military and economic
aid. At a news conference, Yazov did not address the issue of
Nicaragua specifically.
   ``We spoke out in favor of greater predictability and stability
in the Soviet-U.S. military balance,'' he said. ``We tried to
better understand the logic of and rationale for U.S. actions in
the military field.''
   Carlucci described his talks with Yazov, which were closed to
reporters, as ``cordial and businesslike'' and said he had been
invited to Moscow to continue the discussions at an unspecified
date.
   He said he had not obtained the apology he requested for the
fatal shooting by a Soviet soldier of U.S. Army Maj. Arthur
Nicholson in East Germany three years ago. Yazov said the incident
occurred before he became defense minister last May, said Carlucci.
   ``He said he would undertake to investigate it'' through the
Soviet Foreign Ministry, which has been handling the issue Carlucci
said.
   To avoid such ``dangerous activities,'' Carlucci said, ``Gen.
Yazov and I agreed that more would be done in this area.''
   Both agreed that ``there is no need for shooting,'' said
Carlucci. ``Gen. Yazov was firm on that.''
   Carlucci said the chairman of the U.S. joint chiefs of staff,
Adm. William Crowe, and the Soviet Chief of Staff, Marshal Sergei
Akhomeyev, would meet soon, probably in Washington, to work out
guidelines to prevent friction between U.S. and Soviet ground, air
and sea, forces.
   Yazov repeated Kremlin assurances that Soviet troops would be
withdrawn from Afghanistan, but was unable to set a timetable,
pending the outcome of stalled peace talks in Geneva, said Carlucci.
   The two sides also discussed space-based missile defense,
negotiations to reduce strategic nuclear arsenals, and regional
conflicts, including Angola, Cambodia and Korea, he said.
   The Soviets proposed an experiment of a new method of
determining the presence of nuclear-tipped, sea-launched cruise
missiles aboard vessels, a technique mentioned last December by
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev but never explained to the West.
   Carlucci expressed doubt about the technique, but said the
United States was willing to review the propsed experiment, details
of which were not available.
   The Soviets want to impose a limit on such weapons as part of
the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty now under negotiation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
