<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0573 03-17 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0573,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers On Trial For Brutality Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with trials, reports Shultz may
return, other details. Changes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Israeli soldiers went on trial today on
charges of brutality against Palestinians in the first such cases
to reach court since violence erupted in the occupied territories
more than three months ago.
   Two soldiers pleaded guilty to reduced charges in the burying
alive of four Palestinians in the occupied West Bank, and two
others pleaded innocent in the televised beating of two
Palestinians.
   Also today, Israeli warplanes raided PLO bases in the Chouf
Mountains south of Beirut, and the army said all targets were
destroyed. One guerrilla was reported killed and two people were
injured.
   Israeli newspapers said Secretary of State George P. Shultz
might return to the Middle East in late March or early April to
continue his mission to reach an accord between Israel and the
Arabs for starting peace talks.
   Senior military officials said Israel imposed new restrictions
against Palestinians, ruling for the first time that any Arab
wishing to bring $1,000 or more into Israeli-held territories from
Jordan must receive permission.
   The measure was intended to curb Palestine Liberation
Organization-provided funding for the current unrest. The money has
helped shopkeepers on strike and aided Arab families whose homes
were destroyed by the Israeli army.
   In addition, dairy and produce deliveries were not permitted to
enter the cities of Nablus, Tulkarm and Jericho, Arab reports said.
The army said it was checking the report.
   In a military court in Jaffa, Pvts. Yair Nissimi and Dror
Segen-Cohen were accused of assault and abuse for helping bury
alive four Palestinians with a bulldozer after a Feb. 5
demonstration in the West Bank village of Kfar Salem.
   A third soldier, Sgt. Mjr. Charlie Danino, was being tried
separately on the same charges, as well as unbecoming conduct.
   Nissimi and Segen-Cohen accepted a reduced charge of shameful
conduct under a plea bargain placed before a panel of three
military judges. They were to be sentenced to two months and 2{
months in jail, respectively.
   ``I'm sorry about everything that happened,'' Nissimi told the
court. ``I know I made a mistake.''
   Attorneys for the two soldiers charged in the beating incident
filmed by CBS Television _ Pvts. Sagi Harpaz and Yehuda Angel _
said the soldiers entered pleas of not guilty and the trial was
recessed.
   Attorney Uri Slonim, representing Harpaz, said his client would
argue he had carried out his mission of dispersing a demonstration
``in a way that seemed correct under the circumstances'' and had
only used the ``amount of force needed to carry out his mission.''
   About 250 reserve soldiers, meanwhile, submitted a petition to
government leaders today supporting the Israeli army in its attempt
to quell the unrest in the territories.
   The dailies Yediot Ahronot, Maariv, Haaretz and Jerusalem Post
all reported that Shultz, having received an equivocal answer about
the U.S. peace plan from visiting Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, is expected to return to the region either late this month
or early next month.
   Haaretz also reported that despite Shamir's opposition to an
international conference, Shultz, who meets next week with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in Washington, would propose
the two leaders jointly appeal to the United Nations to convene
such a session.
   The attack on Lebanon came a day after a volley of Katyusha
rockets was fired from south Lebanon into a community in north
Israel. An Israeli army spokesman said the rockets shattered
windows and damaged citrus trees, but caused no injuries.
   In clashes Wednesday, four Arabs were shot and killed by troops,
bringing the Palestinian death toll to 100 since the uprising began
Dec. 8, according to the United Nations.
   Also Wednesday, the occupied lands were paralyzed by a general
strike, ordered by the PLO-affiliated underground leadership of the
uprising in a clandestine leaflet. Most stores were shuttered,
public transportation halted and most of the 110,000 Arabs who work
in Israel stayed home.
</TEXT>
