<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ireland-StPatrick's     03-17 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-St Patrick's,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Throng Downtown Dublin for St. Patrick's Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300,000 people turned out under
cloudy skies today for Dublin's St. Patrick's Day parade in a
celebration intensified this year by the 1,000th birthday of the
Irish capital.
   Street vendors did a brisk trade selling sprigs of shamrock, and
a hamburger chain sold ``shamrock-flavored'' shakes in the
traditional Irish color _ green.
   Across the border in the British province of Northern Ireland,
the festivities were overshadowed by Wednesday's deadly attack on
an Irish Republican Army funeral in Belfast. Three people were
killed and 68 wounded.
   But in Ireland, theaters, pubs and hotels have been throbbing
with traditional Irish music, drama and folk dancing this week,
which has been designated St. Patrick's Week.
   Patrick, who tradition says brought Christianity to the pagan
Irish in the 5th century, is the patron saint of Ireland.
   About 6,000 people took part in the Dublin parade, which winds
along a three-mile route from St. Stephen's Green to O'Connell
Street, the main thoroughfare.
   Police estimated that more than 300,000 people, including about
10,000 tourists, mainly Americans, turned out to watch the
procession of dancers, marching bands and historical-theme floats
pass by.
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey took his place on a reviewing
stand outside the General Post Office in O'Connell Street and
called the colorful carnival ``one of the best ever.''
   Government offices, schools, banks and most businesses were
closed in the south for the national holiday, but many industries,
offices and department stores remained open in Northern Ireland.
Churches were thronged for morning Mass and pubs were packed with
imbibers.
   Organizers said the Dublin parade was being televised by more
than 80 TV stations in the United States and Canada.
   Patrick, the son of a deacon and apparently born in Wales, was
consecrated a Catholic priest in A.D. 432 and sent to Ireland,
where he was largely credited with organizing the Christian
communities.
   In Belfast, mourners wearing shamrocks and green armbands
attended the funeral of a slain IRA guerrilla a day after a man
opened fire and hurled grenades in Milltown Cemetery during the
burial of three IRA guerrillas shot by British commandos in
Gibraltar March 6.
   On Wednesday, Haughey appealed to Ulster's Roman Catholic
minority to ``to respond with calm'' to the attack at the IRA
funeral.
   The IRA, outlawed in Britain and Ireland, is fighting to drive
the British out of Northern Ireland and unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
