<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForcedFeeding     03-17 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forced Feeding,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nursing Homes Allowed To Withhold Force-Feeding Of Terminal
Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terminally ill nursing home patients
will be able to reject forced tube-feedings under a new state rule
that takes effect July 1.
   Florida's Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services filed
an admininstrative rule change Wednesday that will allow nursing
homes to continue care for dying patients who reject tube-feedings.
Homes now have to discharge patients if they don't accept forced
feedings.
   ``It's important because it gives more options and more freedoms
to somebody dying in a nursing home,'' said Connie Cheren, director
of the HRS licensing office. She said seven people who testified on
the forced-feeding issue at a January public hearing all favored
the change.
   There are at least 50,000 nursing home residents in Florida.
   ``It's better because sometimes forced feeding is more harmful
to the person than helpful,'' Ms. Cheren said. ``Sometimes taking
the food during the dying stages is more painful for the person
because the body is shutting down at this time.''
   HRS spokesman Ray Wise said the department filed the rule change
early to give the Legislature time to look at it. The change does
not require the Legislature's approval but it could block the new
rule.
   ``If there will be a challenge to it, we want to give the
Legislature the benefit of time to address this in the regular
session,'' Wise said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
