<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0452 03-17 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs McCain, Byrd comments; picks up 5th graf
pvs, ``President Reagan</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican senator predicted today that the
Senate would override President Reagan's veto of a sweeping
anti-discrimination bill and said the administration has only
itself to blame.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the White House should have
proposed a compromise while the Civil Rights Restoration Act was in
the hearing process or on the floor _ not after both chambers had
passed it by overwhelming margins.
   Reagan offered a less sweeping alternative to the bill Wednesday
along with his veto.
   But McCain said its chances of success were ``very poor... It's
very tough around here to switch your vote. It's very, very
difficult to ask people to take new positions when this whole issue
has been percolating for four years.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said he was hoping
for a vote on overriding the veto today. But he said he had been
hearing reports that the opposition strategy involved ``a long
debate.''
   Civil rights leaders called the veto one more entry in a dismal
civil rights record and said Congress will prevail as it has before
in the last seven years.
   ``This administration is compiling the worst civil rights record
of any administration in half a century,'' officials of the
200-group Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said in a statement
Wednesday.
   ``This will hurt Mr. Bush more than anybody else,'' said Rep.
Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House Education and
Labor Committee, referring to Vice President George Bush's
presidential candidacy.
   Both the Senate and the House passed the Civil Rights
Restoration Act by huge margins that were expected to hold up
during override votes in the Senate and the House, which is
scheduled to take up the matter Tuesday. A two-thirds majority is
needed to override.
   ``President Reagan may want to turn the clock back on civil
rights, but the American people do not,'' said House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor and
Human Resources Committee, said Congress has repeatedly thwarted
administration officials' attempts to change the nation's civil
rights course.
   He accused Justice Department officials, including Attorney
General Edwin Meese III, of ``distorting the meaning of the bill,
pandering to the Republican right and engaging in an unseemly
effort to escalate their long-standing anti-civil rights vendetta.''
   The restoration act is also known as the Grove City bill for the
Pennsylvania college involved in the Supreme Court case that
started the controversy.
   The 1984 decision said only specific programs or activities
receiving federal aid must comply with the anti-discrimination
statutes. That meant discrimination could continue in a school's
athletic department, for example, if only the English department
received federal money.
   The new bill would require institution-wide compliance with
civil rights laws by educational institutions, state and local
government agencies and many corporations if any part received
federal aid. It applies to discrimination against women,
minorities, the aged and the disabled.
   The House passed the Grove City bill 315-98 on March 2. The
Senate passed it 75-14 on Jan. 28.
   Supporters of the bill said Congress had always intended wide
protections in order to make sure taxpayers don't end up
subsidizing discrimination.
   But Reagan said the bill would ``vastly and unjustifiably extend
the power of the federal government over the decisions and affairs
of private organizations, such as churches and synagogues, farms,
businesses, and state and local governments.''
   The Moral Majority mounted a last-minute effort to win enough
support to block a veto override. The group said Wednesday it had
sent a letter and a 40-page legal memo to the district offices of
all House members this week echoing Reagan's views on the bill.
   In a message last week to tens of thousands of pastors, the
Moral Majority said failure to obey ``this perverted law could
result in lawsuits costing millions of dollars being brought
against our churches by militant gays, feminists and others who
have no respect for God's laws.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
