<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     03-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers Guild Rejects Interim Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Writers Guild of America has refused to
approve temporary contracts with independent movie and television
producers, a move that will keep in reruns such programs as ``The
Tonight Show.''
   ``Both coasts have voted against granting interim agreements,''
guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said Wednesday after the union's
East Coast board of directors voted in agreement with the West
Coast board's Monday night decision.
   About 80 independent production companies, including Carson
Productions, had sought interim agreements to continue work despite
the writers' strike against the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers.
   ``He'd like to work. He's certainly unhappy,'' said Johnny
Carson spokesman Jim Mahoney after learning of the decision. ``He
doesn't like to stand around. But he certainly understands.''
   Another official strike casualty is ``Late Night With David
Letterman,'' which had its first unscheduled rerun Tuesday night
after a week-long scheduled hiatus. Production already has been
postponed on two new mid-season shows for CBS, ``The Smothers
Brothers Show'' and ``The Dictator.''
   The guild previously rejected a request to exempt from the
strike the April 11 Academy Awards show.
   The 9,000-member guild went on strike against producers and
studios March 7 over residuals from foreign distribution, creative
control and a management proposal to restructure residuals for
one-hour television shows sold into syndication. No new talks are
scheduled.
   The continuation of the strike also is likely to shorten the
season of some top television series, including NBC's ``L.A. Law,''
``The Cosby Show''' and ``Cheers,'' and ABC's ``Moonlighting.''
   The Hollywood Reporter said delays could affect some planned
cliffhanger endings designed to draw viewers back for new-season
debuts.
   ``Moonlighting'' star Cybill Shepherd told the paper the show
had no material beyond Wednesday, and ``L.A. Law'' star Richard
Dysart reportedly said the last two shows of the season may have to
be canceled.
</TEXT>
