<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Armenia     03-17 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenia,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Strike in Disputed Region; Official Fired For Rioting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenians stayed away from work and school for a
second day today in a disputed region of Azerbaijan, an Armenian
official said.
   An official radio report said the mayor was fired in in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait, where government officials said 32
people were killed in ethnic rioting last month.
   The actions stem from a dispute over whether the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan should be annexed to
neighboring Armenia. The region, north of Iran and east of Turkey,
has a large Armenian population.
   Armenians touched off a wave of unrest to press that demand on
Feb. 13 in Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, Stepanakert. Protests
spread to Armenia's capital, Yerevan, and led to violence in at
least two cities in Azerbaijan.
   Gamlet Kocharyan, an industrial worker and member of the
governing council of the Armenian city of Kafar, said workers
struck for a second day in Stepanakert to demand annexation to
Armenia. Factories and schools were closed because of the strike,
and 40,000 people demonstrated outside Communist Party offices, he
said.
   Kocharyan said he received the information from Armenian
activists in Stepanakert. He spoke in a telephone interview.
   The report could not be confirmed because the government has
barred Western journalists from traveling to the region, and
telephone calls to officials of the area were cut off.
   The official media in Moscow did not report the strike, and
representatives of the Azerbaijani government in Moscow said they
had no information about the matter.
   Baku Radio, the mouthpiece of the government in the Azerbaijani
capital, reported that the mayor of Sumgait had been fired by the
ruling council.
   The station, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in
London, said Tavakkula Yagub Ogly Mamedov was relieved of his
duties for ``serious shortcomings in the work of maintaining
appropriate law and order and discipline in the city, and for the
lack of political foresight he has shown which has resulted in
tragic consequences.''
   Government spokesmen have said 32 people were killed in rioting
in Sumgait on Feb. 28 by ``young hooligans'' provoked by ethnic
unrest elsewhere. Armenian activists say the victims were Armenians
killed by ethnic Azeris, the dominant group in Azerbaijan that is
mostly Shiite Moslem. Armenians are predominantly Christian.
   The regional party committee of Nagorno-Karabakh scheduled a
meeting Thursday at which the annexation demand was expected to be
discussed, Kocharyan said.
</TEXT>
