<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-China,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Agrees Not to Block Rescue Ships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China agreed today not to block rescue
ships from three Vietnamese freighters it allegedly set ablaze, and
Vietnam proposed talks to resolve the clash near disputed islands
in the South China Sea, official media said.
   The Vietnam News Agency said Beijing's ambassador to Vietnam, Li
Shuching, gave the assurance in a meeting in Hanoi with Vietnam's
First Deputy Foreign Minister, Dinh Nho Liem.
   ``The Chinese side has agreed not to let its warships prevent
Vietnamese rescue vessels from rescuing Vietnamese sailors on board
the freighters, which were set ablaze at the Sinh Ton group of
islands of Vietnam,'' said the report monitored in Bangkok.
   Vietnam had charged that the warships had intercepted two
unarmed Vietnamese vessels flying Red Cross banners.
   The freighters were allegedly attacked Monday in the Spratly
islands, which Vietnam calls the Truong Sa archipelago and China
calls the Nansha islands. Both nations claim the islands.
   A Vietnamese agency report Wednesday said some Vietnamese
sailors were wounded in Monday's clash and that 76 crewmen remained
aboard the freighters, which continued burning after the attack.
Vietnam's ambassador to Thailand, Le Mai, told a press conference
in Bangkok today that some Vietnamese were killed.
   The Chinese Foreign Ministry on Wednesday said some Chinese were
wounded.
   The Voice of Vietnam radio, monitored in Bangkok, said the
proposal for talks came in a letter from Vietnam's Foreign Ministry
to its Chinese counterpart. Liem delivered the letter to Li, it
said.
   ``The Vietnamese side ... advocates talks to solve disputes
between the two countries concerning the Truong Sa archipelago as
well as their common border, and the Hoang Sa archipelago,'' the
letter said.
   The Hoang Sa, called the Xisha by China and also known as the
Paracels, is the second major island group in the South China Sea
over which both countries claim sovereignty. Vietnam and China also
share a long, tense land border where they fought a war in early
1979.
   China was a major supporter of the Vietnamese communists during
the wars against the French and Americans, but relations have been
poor since the late 1970s, particularly after Vietnam ousted a
pro-Chinese government in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
