<1ST_LINE>u i PM-IRAFuneral 3rdLd-Writethru a0602 03-17 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA Funeral, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0602,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Buries Slain Guerrilla in Peaceful Ceremony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with funeral ending peacefully,
adds quote from Sinn Fein. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `During the ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners wearing shamrocks and
green armbands today streamed through the streets of Belfast in a
funeral procession for a slain IRA guerrilla.
   The Irish Republican Army appealed for calm during the funeral
for 33-year Kevin McCracken, who was buried a day after gunmen
killed three people and wounded 68 at another IRA funeral.
   McCracken was shot to death Monday by a British army patrol that
he fired upon.
   Mourners followed the coffin through West Belfast to the Roman
Catholic Milltown cemetery, the scene of Wednesday's attack by
Protestant gunmen.
   IRA gunmen, in their traditional salute to their movement's
dead, fired three volleys of gunfire in a side street near
McCracken's home. They lined up on a sidewalk next to a photograph
of McCracken, which was surrounded by wreaths.
   ``Britain attacked us yesterday. ... Let Britain take a lesson
from our presence here today: you can never defeat us,'' Jim
McAllister, a leading member of the IRA's political wing, Sinn
Fein, said at the graveside.
   The funeral passed quietly. The outlawed IRA had advised police
earlier to stay away, and they did.
   During the night, rioters enraged by Wednesday's cemetery attack
firebombed five houses in Protestant North Belfast and burned
buses. One woman was treated for smoke inhalation, but there were
no other injuries reported.
   The attack occurred during a funeral for three IRA guerrillas
who were shot by British commandos in Gibraltar on March 6. They
were unarmed and allegedly planning a bombing attack.
   Police said they were holding a Protestant, Michael Stone, who
allegedly mounted the cemetery attack, and an accomplice. Police
gave no other details on the two, who can be held without charge
for seven days.
   Police kept out of sight as more than 1,000 mourners followed
McCracken's coffin, draped with the Irish flag, from his family's
two-story rowhouse to the nearby Holy Trinity Church for a Mass.
   Stewards from Sinn Fein removed McCracken's black beret and
gloves from the coffin before it entered the church.
   Black flags adorned the windows of homes along the route of the
slow procession, headed by a piper playing a lament.
   Relative calm returned to this British-ruled province in time
for McCracken's funeral.
   Overnight, police said Catholic gangs stole 24 vehicles in
Belfast and two in Londonderry, setting many of them ablaze. They
said rioters bombarded security forces with gasoline bombs, rocks
and bottles filled with acid.
   In Belfast, police fired plastic bullets to disperse the rioters.
   There were no injuries reported.
   Mainstream Protestant organizations disavowed the cemetery
attack. The Rev. Ian Paisley, hard-line leader of the Protestant
Democratic Unionist Party, said Wednesday that all ``right-thinking
Protestants'' would condemn it.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said an anonymous caller
telephoned its Belfast office and claimed responsibility for the
attack on behalf of a little-known extremist faction, the
Protestant Action Force. The BBC said the caller gave no code word
establishing authenticity.
   The group has claimed responsibility for previous sectarian
assassinations.
   Belfast city councilman Brian Feeney of the moderate Catholic
Social Democratic and Labor Party predicted in a BBC radio
interview today that the funeral attack could trigger fierce new
sectarian strife in the province.
   ``It was a dreadful provocation for the (Irish) nationalist
community. ... People who support the IRA will be asking that there
should be some retaliation,'' he said.
   Authorities said 16 of the 68 people injured in the funeral
attack remained hospitalized today. One was in critical condition
with severe head injuries and four others were seriously wounded.
   The British government called the attack ``insane and depraved''
and appealed for calm. So did Sinn Fein.
   The gunman could have been emboldened by the deliberate absence
of police at the funerals of Mairead Farrell, 31, Daniel McCann,
30, and Sean Savage, 24.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
it had agreed to appeals by the families to keep away after the
Catholic Church assured it there would be no graveside military
displays by the IRA.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to drive the British from
Northern Ireland and unite the province with the maily Catholic
Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
