<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CruiseFire     03-17 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cruise Fire,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Firm: Passengers Of Fire-Crippled Ship To Receive Refunds,
Free Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers of the fire-crippled cruise ship
Scandinavian Star, under tow to port in Cancun today, will receive
refunds and tickets for another Mexican cruise, a company
spokeswoman said.
   The 465-foot ship, built in France in 1971 as a ferry and
converted to a cruise liner in 1984, was disabled by an engine fire
early Wednesday about 35 miles off Isla Mujeres in the Yucatan
peninsula. It was under tow today by a Mexican Naval destroyer,
escorted by a U.S. Coast Guard cutter.
   Capt. Garcia Silva, commander of the Mexican naval base at Isla
Mujeres, said the fire apparently was sparked by a broken fuel line.
   None of the ship's 449 passengers or 266 crew members was
injured by the fire, although two passengers were flown to a
hospital in St. Petersburg.
   A 71-year-old Florida resident was admitted in stable condition
overnight for observation. A Florida man was treated for a back
injury and released.
   Jill DeChello of Miami-based SeaEscape Ltd., which runs the
Star, said the passengers would be reimbursed their $179 to $499
fares, and get a free cruise. When the ship reaches Cancun,
passengers will be flown on chartered planes to St. Petersburg, the
Star's port, she said.
   It was unclear when the Star might resume operations because
damage couldn't immediatley be assessed, Ms. DeChello said.
</TEXT>
