<HEAD>Fawn Hall Maintains North Innocent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf after 3rd pvs bgng ``The federal'' to include
that she was granted immunity.</NOTE>
<HEAD>PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TAC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North's former secretary,
Fawn Hall, said charges against the Marine and others in the
Iran-Contra scandal are no surprise, as she defended him in a
speech to a university audience.
   Ms. Hall conceded mistakes were made in the sale of arms to Iran
and distribution of some of the proceeds to the Contras in
Nicaragua, but she added Wednesday, ``You have to look at the
intention. I think Lieutenant Colonel Oliver North's intentions
were good.''
   The federal grand jury indictment ``was something that we have
expected for some time,'' she told about 300 people at the
University of Puget Sound. The mostly supportive crowd listened
over the chants of 30 to 40 protesters outside carrying signs with
messages such as ``Fawn Go Home.''
   Ms. Hall was granted immunity from prosecution in exchange for
her testimony before the grand jury investigating the case.
   The issue ``is still quite emotional for me, especially today,''
she said. ``There are a lot of questions that I won't be able to
answer tonight because there is a pending investigation going on.''
   When a woman in the audience asked whether Ms. Hall believed two
wrongs made a right, Ms. Hall raised her voice and replied,
``That's not what I said.''
   She blamed the news media and Congress for what she said were
distortions, including ``sexual innuendoes repeated by our members
of Congress'' on her role in removing documents from her office.
   ``The Iran-Contra hearings were a circus,'' she said. The
hearings could be considered a ``cleansing process to see where the
policy went wrong, but there were many members (of Congress) who
wanted this to be another Watergate and get their names in
history.''
