<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Africa-Pope     03-17 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Africa-Pope,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trip Schedule for Southern Africa Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will visit
five countries in southern Africa as a messenger of peace and
brotherhood, a Vatican representative said today.
   The pope will not visit South Africa, but will make brief stops
in Zimbabwe, Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland and Mozambique from Sept.
10 to 19.
   Southern Africa is ``an area of war, of violence and a place
where, very often, the dignity of man and his rights are trod
upon,'' said the announcement by the apostolic delegation in
Pretoria.
   The pope is scheduled to beatify a French priest during a Mass
at the race course in the Lesotho capital, Maseru, on Sept. 15.
   The priest, the Rev. Joseph Gerard, spent more than 50 years
traveling by horseback to visit the shepherds and farmers in 19th
century Basutoland (now Lesotho) and in the South African province
of Natal. In 1928, 14 years after his death, local people
attributed a miracle to Gerard _ the restoration of a blind girl's
eyesight.
   The pope begins his trip in Zimbabwe on Sept. 10, where he will
attend a regional meeting of Roman Catholic bishops.
   On Sept. 13, he makes a one-day trip to Botswana. He will meet
with priests in the Gaborone Cathedral and celeberate Mass in the
National Stadium.
   John Paul will go to Swaziland on Sept. 16 and arrive in
Mozambique that evening. He will return to Rome on Sept. 19.
</TEXT>
