<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0626 03-17 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0626,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 11 grafs, Shultz testimony, picks up 5th graf pvs,
Apparently ruling</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir ended
his talks here today after offering to go to Moscow this spring to
launch negotiations with the Arabs as a way of breaking a deadlock
over an international Mideast
   peace conference.
   But Secretary of State George P. Shultz, testifying in Congress
after a final session with Shamir, said ``the Arab parties require
a conference to launch negotiations.''
   Therefore, Shultz told the Senate Budget Committee, ``there will
be no negotiations without a properly structured conference.''
   Shamir, who had a one-hour breakfast session with Shultz to wind
up a four-day visit, flatly rejected a U.S. proposal for a
full-scale Mideast conference.
   It ``is not conducive to peace,'' he said Wednesday after
meeting for two hours with President Reagan at the White House.
   Shamir suggested direct Arab-Israeli negotiations be hold under
U.S. and Soviet auspices, but without a substantive role for Moscow.
   Shultz told the committee the United States has always been
willing to consider any approach that could lead to direct
negotiations.
   In fact, he said, ``the United States opposes, and will not
participate in, an international conference designed to replace
bilaterial negotiations.''
   Shultz said the U.S. proposal is designed to prevent
interference by the hosts in the Arab-Israel talks.
   ``This is a time for decision,'' he said. ``The situation on the
ground does not serve anyone's interests. Rapid, positive change
can occur.''
   Reagan on Wednesday cautioned that ``those who will say no to
the U.S. plan _ and the prime minister has not used this word _
need not answer to us. They'll need to answer to themselves and
their people as to why they turned down a realistic and sensible
plan to achieve negotiations.''
   Apparently ruling out any compromise, Reagan said ``the United
States will not slice this initiative apart and will not abandon
it.''
   Shamir, however, reaffirmed his willingness to hold direct
negotiations with Jordan and Palestinians under U.S. and Soviet
auspices.
   He said later at a news conference that Reagan and Soviet
General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who will meet in Moscow in
the spring, could invite Israel and the Arabs to an ``international
ceremony'' and then step aside, allowing them to hold direct
negotiations.
   ``If there would be such a proposal, I am ready,'' Shamir said.
``It would be useful.''
   The prime minister said he would attend even if the Soviets did
not repair a 21-year break in diplomatic relations with Israel.
``It has nothing to do with it,'' he said.
   ``Such an international ceremony will give King Hussein and
other parties a clear international legitimacy for direct
negotiations,'' Shamir said.
   The idea of having the United States and the Soviets convene the
negotiations, but not participate in them, was broached to Shamir
in Jerusalem last October by Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Shamir accepted, but King Hussein of Jordan rejected the
proposal. He called for an international conference held by the
five permament members of the U.N. Security Council _ the United
States, the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
   Despite his own reservations, Shultz included an international
conference in the plan for negotiations he presented two weeks ago
to Israel, Jordan and Syria. It would be convened next month and
set the stage for negotiations starting May 1.
   According to a senior U.S. official, Reagan's meeting with
Shamir focused almost exclusively on the issue.
   The official, who briefed under rules of anonymity, said the two
did not review Israel's concerns about the U.S. proposal that it
cede at least part of the West Bank and Gaza in exchange for Arab
recognition.
   Shamir will report to the Israeli Cabinet on Sunday on his talks
here. Until then, the prime minister refused to either accept or
reject the U.S. proposal.
   Whatever the outcome, Shamir said, Israel intends to work with
the United States in behalf of peace in the Middle East.
   ``Sometimes there are differences between best friends,'' Shamir
said. ``And we regard the Americans as our best friends. Now we
have such a situation we have some differences with them. We will
try to overcome these differences.''
   Vice President George Bush, hosting a dinner for Shamir on
Wednesday night at the State Department, assured him ``no wedge
will be driven between the United States and Israel.''
   Toasting Shamir, the vice president said: ``We are like
brothers; our two countries, friends and allies forever.''
   Shamir, in reply, said Israel was proud of its record as the
most consistent supporter of the United States in the United
Nations and of sharing military technology with Washington. He said
the U.S.-Israeli relationship ``is stronger than ever.''
</TEXT>
