<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Punjab Robbery,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill Five Bank Staffers, Escape With Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants shot and killed five Hindu
employees of a bank Thursday after stealing the equivalent of about
$3,700 from the cashier, police said.
   Eight militants armed with Chinese-made AK-47 rifles raided a
branch of the Punjab National Bank at Bholka village, 17 miles
north of here, said district police chief Izhar Alam.
   The militants snatched the bank's cash box from cashier Kulwant
Rai at gunpoint, he said. Rai, bank manager Juni Lal and three
other Hindu employees were shot and killed after the militants
separated them from Sikh workers, Alam said. The other victims were
identified as Amrit Lal, 42, Ramesh Kumar, 36, and Yog Raj, 32.
   At least 466 people have been killed this year in attacks blamed
on Sikh militants. More than 1,000 people were killed last year in
the Sikh guerrilla war for a separate state.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are in a
majority in Punjab. The militants claim that Sikhs are
discriminated against by nation's Hindu majority, which makes up
more than 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
