<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DolphinCatch     03-17 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dolphin Catch,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Steps To Save Dolphins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service on
Thursday ordered foreign nations that export tuna to the United
States to reduce the number of dolphins killed during fishing.
   Countries that do not reduce dolphin deaths will no longer be
allowed to export tuna to the United States, the Commerce
Department agency said.
   The order covers foreign fleets that catch yellowfin tuna in
purse seine nets, and requires them to establish dolphin protection
rules similar to those that already cover U.S. fishermen.
   The regulation will take effect in mid-April, and requires that
the rate of dolphins killed by the foreign fleets be reduced to the
U.S. fishing fleet level by 1991, the Fisheries Service said.
   The problem occurs primarily in the eastern tropical Pacific
Ocean, where fishing vessels search for schools of dolphins.
Yellowfin tuna tend to congregate beneath the dolphins, and thus
fishermen can more easily find the tuna.
   Fishermen then encircle both groups of fish with their nets. The
majority of dolphins are able to escape or are released by the
fishermen, officials said, but some become tangled in the nets and
drown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeroicGolfer     03-17 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroic Golfer,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golfer Revives Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Bea Porter couldn't save her golf
game, but she made a much more important save _ the life of a
3-year-old boy.
   Porter was trying to qualify for next week's LPGA tournament
when she jumped a 6-foot fence and revived the boy, who almost
drowned Wednesday in a backyard pool bordering the Moon Valley
Country Club course.
   Porter, 38, said she was lining up her second shot on the 13th
fairway when she saw Jonathon Smucker face down in the water. The
child's father, Christian, jumped into the pool fully clothed and
pulled out his son.
   ``But when I saw the father begin to shake the child and yell at
his wife (Anna) if she knew CPR, I knew that we were in trouble,''
said Porter, who added that she had no previous experience in
cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
   Porter said her caddy, who also didn't know CPR, helped her jump
the fence and she approached the father, who handed her the child.
   ``I thought he was dead. He was turning grey,'' she said. ``I
knew I had to do something. ... So I threw him on the ground,
reached in and cleaned out his mouth, moved his tongue to the side
and blew.''
   Finally, she said, she saw ``his little lungs inflate.''
   The child was crying in Porter's arms by the time paradmedics
arrived. He was in good condition Thursday at St. Joseph's Hospital
and Medical Center. The boy was visiting Phoenix from Ronks, Pa.,
with his parents.
   ``There is no doubt in our minds that Porter saved his life,''
said Fire Department spokesman Steve Jensen.
   And the golf game?
   Porter, who has won $50,000 in 15 years on the ladies pro golf
tour, bogeyed two of the next three holes, finished the round at 76
and missed qualifying for the Standard Register Turquoise Classic
by three shots.
   Still, she said, ``I feel like I just won a million
tournaments.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
