<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--BusStrike     03-17 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bus Strike,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Buses Off City Streets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus workers began an indefinite strike
for more pay on Thursday, forcing the capital's 5 million commuters
to find alternate transportation.
   More than 550 employees of the Delhi Transport Corp. were
arrested under the Essential Services Maintenance Act, which
prohibits employees of essential services such as police, hospitals
and the fire brigade from going on strike, said police spokesman
Ravi Pawar.
   The strike, which idled the city's 5,000 passenger buses, forced
many people to walk or cycle to work.
   A lucky few managed to engage three-wheeled scooter rickshaws
and taxis, which increased fares because of the strike. Some
private buses transported commuters for a flat rate of about 16
cents, double the normal city service fare.
   School examinations scheduled for Thursday were postponed
because of the strike.
   In Parliament, Transport Minister Rajesh Pilot said the strike
was illegal and said the government would take action against the
workers.
   Buses are the main form of transport in New Delhi, a city of 8
million people. A rail system is used by few people because of its
limited area of operation.
</TEXT>
