<DOCNO> AP880317-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NASABudget     03-17 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASA Budget,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget `Disaster' Facing Space Program, NASA Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENBELT, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top NASA official warned the space
community Thursday that ``an absolute disaster to NASA'' looms if
Congress votes only a small increase in the space agency's budget
for next year.
   President Reagan has proposed a budget of $11.5 billion for the
year that begins in October, an increase of 20 percent over the
current year.
   Dale Myers, deputy administrator of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, told a symposium that where the 20 percent
increase is concerned ``we are probably not going to make it.''
   He said it probably will be closer to 2 percent.
   Myers told the American Astronautical Society there probably
wouldn't be any problem if NASA was dealing with only the
congressional committees that have oversight responsibility for the
agency.
   ``The problem is we're caught in this terrible budget crunch;
decisions are being made by a budget committee which is not that
familiar with the space program,'' he said at the Goddard Space
Flight Center.
   ``Last year we got hurt very badly,'' Myers said. ``We got a
budget cut and because of that now we are showing a 20 percent
increase in outlays this year compared to last year, and the
average increase is going to be something like 2 percent.''
   ``If we get the 2 percent increase, which is an easy out for
Congress, it is an absolute disaster to NASA,'' he said. ``We have
not even imagined what we would have to cut back if we are given a
2 percent situation. I just can't imagine that would happen _ but
it could happen,'' he said.
   Myers said it was unfortunate that space activities are in a
part of the budget ``where NASA, the National Science Foundation
and all the high technologies activity of the government are all
tangled up with some social programs where tradeoffs are being made
in a very isolated area.''
   Last week Rep. Edward Boland, D-Mass., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on housing and independent agencies,
threatened to cancel money for NASA's proposed space station if
housing programs were cut.
   Myers said NASA has never been caught in such a difficult budget
situation.
</TEXT>
