<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CalPoly-Harassment     03-17 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cal Poly-Harassment,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Painter Awarded $20,000 for Sex Harassment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state civil rights agency has ordered
California Polytechnic State University at San Luis Obispo to pay
$20,000 to a woman for four years of ``vicious treatment'' in a
campus industrial paint shop.
   The harassment of Carol Bowlby, the first woman hired by the
shop, included name-calling, placing a pictures of a naked woman in
her lunch box, and refusing to work with her, said the Fair
Employment and Housing Commission.
   Ms. Bowlby's work environment was ``offensive, hostile,
oppressive and intimidating,'' and contributed to her medical
problems and need for psychiatric care, the commission said in a
4-1 decision released Wednesday. It also said the university failed
to investigate her complaints properly or discipline her co-workers.
   Commissioner Michael Johnson dissented. He described Ms. Bowlby
as a ``substandard employee'' and said the shop was ``a
rough-and-tumble workplace where strong language and name-calling
were common.''
   The commission's majority said the university's ``sincere and
laudable effort ... to bring a woman into a male-dominated field,''
did not excuse ``the vicious treatment she did receive because of
her sex.''
   The commission awarded her $20,000 for emotional distress, but
concluded her departure from the job in 1982 was voluntary and
refused additional damages for lost wages.
   Attorney Gloria Barrios, who prosecuted the case for the state
Fair Employment and Housing Department, said Ms. Bowlby, whose
disability and rehabilitation costs have already been paid by the
university, now works at a grocery in San Luis Obispo.
   University lawyer Thomas Trager said no decision has been made
on an appeal to Superior Court. But he said the school denies that
Ms. Bowlby was harassed because of her sex.
   The commission said Ms. Bowlby's difficulties began almost
immediately after she was hired as the first woman in the
university's new trainee program for women and minorities in its
Plant Operations paint shop.
   Her job evaluations were satisfactory at first, but got worse as
time went on, and she was never rated as qualified to become a
full-fledged painter. She reacted badly to criticism and was
considered difficult to work with, the commission said.
   But those difficulties were caused at least in part by ``the
hostility she suffered because of her sex,'' the commission said.
</TEXT>
