<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Greece-Warplanes,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Air Force to Receive 97 Used Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece will receive 97 used jet fighters
free of charge from the United States and West Germany in order to
renew its air force's equipment, the Defense Ministry said Thursday.
   Defense Minister Yannis Haralambopoulos said Greece would
receive 69 F-4C and F-4D Phantom fighter bombers from the United
States and 28 F-104G Starfighter interceptors from West Germany.
   Greece has about 300 combat aircraft in seven air force combat
wings.
   The defense minister also said that Greece would take delivery
of its first French-built Mirage 2000 fighter bomber on March 21 in
Bordeux, France.
   Greece has ordered 40 Mirage aircraft and 40 U.S.-built F-16
fighter bombers to modernize its air force.
