<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0495 03-17 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,0924</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takes The Stand At His Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs of testimony today and to conform; picks
up 10th graf, `Before Wednesday's...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham testified today that he
never ordered anyone to hamper an investigation into an aide's
alleged death threat, but said he told Arizona's top police officer
not to cooperate with the probe.
   In his second day of testimony in his impeachment trial, Mecham
confirmed that in a Nov. 15 conversation with Department of Public
Safety Director Ralph Milstead, ``I said, `If you want my
permission you don't have it.'''
   Mecham acknowledged he told Milstead, ``The attorney general is
trying to hang me and I'm not going to help him.'' However, he said
he had never ordered anyone to hamper the investigation and denied
any intent to break the law.
   He said he told Milstead to tell Attorney General Bob Corbin's
office ``we have looked into this matter and there's nothing to
it.''
   The 63-year-old first-term governor said he had been told by
Department of Administration Director Max Hawkins that the alleged
threat was ``a bunch of hot air'' that would go away.
   Mecham said that when he was first told of the alleged threat,
the head of his security details, DPS Lt. Beau Johnson, did not
specify that it was reported to be an actual death threat.
   ``Did you ever hear the words from Lt. Johnson `death threat'?''
asked defense attorney Fred Craft.
   ``I absolutely did not,'' said Mecham. He insisted that Johnson
also did not say it involved a possible felony of tampering with a
grand jury witness.
   Johnson has testified that he told the governor the alleged
threat involved a possible felony of tampering a grand jury witness.
   Milstead testified last week that Mecham ordered him not to
cooperate with a Corbin investigation. The attorney general was
looking into an alleged death threat against former Mecham aide
Donna Carlson, who was about to testify before a grand jury on
Mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The governor, whose lawyers have been trying to undermine the
credibility of the state's top police official, testified Wednesday
he would have had ample grounds to fire Milstead. He said he also
would have fired Ms. Carlson had he known she told Milstead last
year the governor was considering replacing him.
   ``I had to trust the people I was dealing with,'' Mecham said.
Asked by Craft if the governor still trusted those people, Mecham
answered, ``Not some of them. ... It was a trust misplaced.''
   The governor contended an internal investigation showed that
Milstead misused state vehicles for personal purposes and used a
state secretary to type his masters' thesis.
   In response, DPS spokesman Sgt. Allan Schmidt said the
investigators ``found no reason not to retain him (Milstead) and no
problems, save his management style.''
   Mecham appeared calm and soft-spoken during his testimony
Wednesday. All 29 senators, who are serving as Mecham's judge and
jury, stood when he entered the Senate chamber and was sworn in.
Later, some said the action was suggested in a note passed around
by President Carl Kunasek, a Republican.
   Before Wednesday's session, Mecham had been away from the
capital for more than a month, operating out of a suburban office
he calls his ``government in exile.''
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in
six decades, retains his salary and title, but Secretary of State
Rose Mofford, a Democrat, has gubernatorial power pending the
outcome of the trial.
   Testimony so far has focused on the charge that Mecham confidant
Lee Watkins, a former state prison construction chief, made a death
threat on Nov. 12 against Ms. Carlson. Watkins has denied any
threat, and has pleaded the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination in refusing to testify.
   Mecham said he did not consider Watkins, who arranged the
$350,000 campaign loan, to be a major fund-raiser for his 1986
campaign and that he did not seek to protect him, as Ms. Carlson
said he did.
   ``Protect him from what?'' the governor asserted. ``I'd like for
somebody to tell me what I protected him from.''
   The governor denied jobs were doled out in his administration
based on how much money a person contributed or raised for his
campaign.
   Ms. Carlson testified last week that when she once complained
about Watkins' position in the governor's inner circle she was told
by the governor's then-chief of staff: ``We have to take care of
Lee. He raised a lot of money for the campaign.''
   On Wednesday, Sam Udall, Mecham's former appointments secretary,
testified that campaign contributions were a criterion, although
not a major one, in making appointments to boards and commissions.
   Mecham said he felt he could not trust Corbin after the governor
sought his advice on a legal issue early last year and the matter
wound up under investigation.
   ``That's when I knew we were in big trouble,'' Mecham said,
adding that after that ``we had as little relationship with the
attorney general's office as possible.''
   Corbin's office led the investigation that resulted in Mecham's
indictment on six felony counts of allegedly concealing the
$350,000 loan. The governor faces an April 21 criminal trial on
those charges, and a May 17 recall election.
   In the impeachment, a two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is
required to convict Mecham.
</TEXT>
