<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     03-17 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kim's Resignation Raises Hopes for United Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Dae-jung stepped down as leader of
his party Thursday, reviving hopes for reuniting the fractured
opposition before crucial legislative elections next month.
   Kim Dae-jung said he was resigning as president of the Party for
Peace and Democracy to help unite the two leading opposition
parties.
   The departure of Kim Dea-jung follows the resignation last month
of rival opposition leader Kim Young-sam, who headed the
Reunification Democratic Party. Both Kims ran for president in
December's presidential election, thus ensuring victory for the
government candidate, Roh Tae-woo.
   Since their presidential defeat, the two Kims have been under
pressure to step aside to clear the way for a merger of the two
parties.
   ``Standing at the crossroads of unification or division, I have
decided to step down to help facilitate the opposition merger,
which is our supreme task,'' Kim said in a statement.
   Park Young-sook, who read the statement, said the 62-year-old
Kim could not make the announcement personally because he was not
feeling well. Kim was reported to be in seclusion.
   Mrs. Park was named acting party president. She declined to
answer questions about what would happen if the opposition merger
failed. She said time was running out and expressed hope the
opposition would unite by Sunday.
   It was unclear, however, whether Kim Dae-jung's resignation
would lead to an opposition merger. Unification talks are expected
to start Friday, but such thorny issues as power distribution
remain to be solved.
   Kim Young-sam's party reserved official comment, but some party
officials privately expressed distrust and said they feared the
resignation would be a trick.
   ``We are skeptical in view of Kim Dae-jung's duplicity in the
past,'' said one party official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified.
   The two Kims have been bitter rivals. Kim Dae-jung and his
supporters split from the Reunification Democratic Party to mount a
separate presidential campaign.
   Months of efforts to unite the opposition collapsed last week
when Kim Dae-jung rejected a last-minute demand from the
Reunification Democratic Party that he step down and take a back
seat if a unified opposition party is formed.
   Kim Dae-jung has been a major figure in South Korean politics
for three decades. He gained international fame with his
unflinching opposition to the country's past authoritarian
governments and devotion to human rights activity.
   Kim Dae-jung's party officials could not comment on their
leader's political future but assumed he would continue to work for
the opposition.
   Kim Dae-jung said in his resignation statement, ``I make it
clear that I will make all the efforts I can in the vanguard of the
people in order to win the general elections.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
