<DOCNO> AP880317-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Secord     03-17 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Secord,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secord Vows to `Crush' Iran-Contra Charges Against Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard V. Secord, one of four men indicted in
the Iran-Contra affair, vowed Thursday to ``crush this whole case''
with a barrage of legal maneuvers against the independent counsel.
   Shortly after a federal grand jury returned the indictments
Wednesday, Secord, a feisty retired Air Force major general,
embarked on a series of interviews with reporters to denounce the
case.
   He called the charges initiated by independent counsel Lawrence
E. Walsh a ``creation of fantasy ... ludicrous.''
   Secord, 55, an arms dealer who helped former White House aide
Oliver L. North sell weapons to Iran and divert the proceeds to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels, has been charged with conspiracy, theft,
wire fraud and conspiring to pay North illegal gratuities.
   After his arraignment next week, Secord said his attorneys will
file motions to dismiss the case on a number of grounds. For one
thing, Secord claims Walsh did not follow all the Justice
Department's guidelines for independent counsels.
   ``I am going to crush this whole case in hopes that nobody else
has to go through what I have,'' Secord said in a telephone
interview. ``I view this in military terms: they have committed an
assault on me and I am going to launch a counterattack.''
   Last month Walsh hired Herbert Stern, a former federal judge, to
handle legal challenges stemming from the Iran-Contra case.
   Secord said he had not talked with North or the other defendants
_ his ex-business partner, Albert Hakim, and former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter _ about a coordinated defense
strategy.
   His big problem, Secord said, is raising money for his defense.
``The only guys who win in this are lawyers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
