<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bigamist 1stLd-Writethru a0631 03-17 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bigamist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow's Benefits Jeopardized After Dead Husband Revealed As
Bigamist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to clarify where woman living</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A widow who learned that her husband of
27 years had been a bigamist has been asked to return $610 in
Social Security benefits.
   Mazella Bouknight Lever, 80, said she learned after her
estranged husband Noisey died July 29 that the woman who was living
with him was his first wife, Carrie. She filed suit in February
seeking to evict the first Mrs. Lever.
   The government has written Mrs. Lever demanding repayment of
$610 in Social Security widow's benefits. ``Obviously, this is not
something that she did intentionally. She thought that, in fact,
she was the only Mrs. Lever,'' said her attorney, Stephen G. Smith.
   ``The point is, she received benefits as a basis of being
married to this man,'' said Berion Mouton, Social Security
assistant district manager. She must show she is unable to repay
the money if she wants to avoid it, he said.
   Mrs. Lever said she hadn't seen her husband since she moved out
in November 1982. They were married in 1960.
   Since his death, Mrs. Lever said, she has thought much about
Noisey's motive for not divorcing Carrie. ``I guess he was just
using me,'' she said. ``I could always keep a good job.''
</TEXT>
