<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nancy     03-17 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Cancel Camp David Trip Because of First Lady's Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and his wife Nancy will
remain at the White House this weekend to give the first lady a
chance to recuperate from a bout of laryngitis, the president's
spokesman announced Thursday.
   White House physician John Hutton ``recommended she take it
easy'' and advised the couple to cancel their regular weekend visit
to the Camp David, Md., presidential retreat, spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   The first lady canceled a planned trip to Nashville, Tenn., on
Wednesday because of her voice loss.
   Mrs. Reagan, who has been using a steam vaporizer to alleviate
the condition, has been resting in the White House living quarters
``and taking home remedies,'' said a spokeswoman, Wendy Weber Toler.
