<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1319EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Demolitions Bjt   03-17 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Demolitions, Bjt,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Destroys Houses as Punishment for Attacks on Collaborators</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIDU, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yusra al Shiah wrapped her
3-month-old daughter in a ragged blanket and took her nine other
children into the rainy night. An Israeli army bulldozer leveled
their cinderblock house moments later.
   Then the machine clanked along the dirt street in this West Bank
village, eight miles west of Jerusalem, to the home of Ibrahim
Hamed Bedwan.
   Bedwan said he and his wife, parents and nine children were
ordered out. Soldiers piled the furniture in the street and the
bulldozer knocked down the two-story stone building.
   Palestinians have begun to turn on alleged collaborators during
the rebellion that has swept the occupied territories for more than
three months, and the army is demolishing houses in response.
   Leaflets distributed by the Palestine Liberation Organization
have ordered revenge attacks on collaborators. Fellow villagers in
Qabatiyeh lynched a man Feb. 24 who was suspected of aiding the
Israelis and another was stabbed to death last week in the Aqbat
Jaber refugee camp.
   Law in the Service of Man, a human rights group founded by
Palestinian lawyers says the army has knocked down 10 houses since
the first killing.
   Destroying or sealing the houses of those accused of terror
attacks has been a common tactic since Israel captured the West
Bank and Gaza Strip from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. The Palestinian rights group said the total has reached more
than 1,300 in the generation of occupation.
   An army spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said:
``Demolishing houses is very effective. It serves as a warning to
everyone in a village not to take action against people they
suspect of working with Israel.''
   People whose homes are razed are not allowed to rebuild them, so
most have resorted to living in tents.
   Among those opposing the policy are the United States,
International Committee of the Red Cross and United Nations.
   They denounce it as collective punishment usually imposed
without court review or due process. In most cases, the penalty
does not affect the suspect, who may be dead, jailed or a fugitive
abroad.
   In the case of Bidu, the suspects were a son of Mrs. al Shiah
and two sons of Bedwan. The parents said they did not even know
Ibrahim al Shiah, 17; Nissam Bedwan, 23, and Mohammed Bedwan, 20,
were accused of anything until their houses were bulldozed the
night of March 7.
   Mrs. al Shiah stood weeping beside the rubble that had been a
five-room home and said: ``I begged the soldiers `Tell me, for
God's sake, what have we done?''' With her were three small
daughters dressed in plastic sandles and thin, mud-caked dresses on
the chilly morning.
   ``The soldiers wouldn't tell us anything,'' she said. ``They
just took the children from their beds and carried them out of the
house.'' Her husband Khalid is an unemployed handyman.
   Pools of muddy rainwater covered the plastic floors of two white
tents the Red Cross provided. Tattered blankets were piled at the
back of one, which reeked of mildew.
   Discarded in a muddy olive grove were family furniture and
possessions: two smashed beds, a refrigerator on its side, a
mud-caked gas stove, two rain-soaked quilts, pieces of a cabinet, a
child's red boot.
   Metal chairs, pots, pans and a red pillow could be seen buried
in the debris of the house.
   Mrs. al Shiah said the soldiers arrived at about midnight, put
the village's 4,000 residents under curfew and cut off the
electricity before bring in the bulldozer.
   Bedwan said: ``Now everybody in this village feels he is not
safe.'' He stood quietly at the site of the 10-room home he had
built over a period of 20 years. All that remained was part of one
wall, painted bright pink.
   Felicia Langer, an Israeli lawyer who represents Palestinians,
said leveling houses ``punishes people who are not accused of any
offense, much less guilty.''
   She says it violates the 1949 Geneva Convention on treatment of
civilians in occupied zones, which forbids destruction of property
as a punishment or deterrent.
   Israel's Supreme Court has ruled the practice legal under
emergency regulations issued in 1945 by the British administration
governing Palestine at the time. Those regulations have been the
basis for several extraordinary measures, including censorship.
</TEXT>
