<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Radicals     03-17 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Radicals,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Sentenced in Railroad Station Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo District Court sentenced 11 members of a
radical leftist group Thursday to prison terms ranging from three
to eight years for an attack on a downtown railway station three
years ago.
   Minoru Kajii was sentenced to eight years, while the other 10
received sentences ranging from three to five years, said a court
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The 11 have been identified as members of the Chukaku-ha, or
Middle Core Faction, Japan's most active extremist group.
   They were arrested after attackers set fire to the Asakusabashi
station in downtown Tokyo on Nov. 29, 1985, when saboteurs also cut
telecommunications lines and cables controlling railway signals at
various places across Japan.
   The coordinated attacks paralyzed operations of the then
government-run Japan National Railways, affecting about 6 million
commuters.
   The radicals were believed to have acted in sympathy with former
rail employees who were protesting government plans to turn the
debt-ridden railway network into a private company. The railroad
turned private in April 1987.
</TEXT>
