<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessEvictions 1stLd-Writethru a0620 03-17 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Evictions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Follow Eviction of Squatters From House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with university tearing down house.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of California today began
tearing down an abandoned house following a day of confrontations
between rock-throwing squatters and baton-wielding police.
   A crane crumpled the roof and walls of the house a day after
more than 350 protesters rampaged through the neighborhood south of
the university setting trash fires and battling helmeted police in
the worst clashes since 1986 anti-apartheid confrontations, the
university said.
   ``The house was a continuing hazard and a target for street
attacks,'' said university spokesman Ray Colvig. ``Rather than have
repeated attacks we decided to take it out.''
   University police said the demonstrators are no longer occupying
property and have dispersed.
   The protests Wednesday started after University of California
police evicted about 35 activists for the homeless from a house
owned by UC-Berkeley. Protesters rampaged up side streets, knocking
over garbage cans, setting trash fires and breaking the window on a
police car.
   Later in the day, protesters tried to lunge through city police
barricades in an unsuccessful attempt to take back the off-campus
house.
   The protesters contended that the three-story house, taken over
by squatters March 9, should not stand vacant when the city has 800
to 1,600 homeless people. The school ordered the eviction after the
city fire marshal Tuesday declared the house a fire hazard, said
spokesman Tom Debley.
   The school plans to demolish the house to make way for student
housing in the next few days, Debley said.
</TEXT>
