<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1430EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hess     03-17 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hess,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Nazi Leader Buried Seven Months After Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WUNSIEDEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi leader Rudolf Hess was
buried in his family's plot Thursday, seven months after his
suicide in a West Berlin prison. Police stood guard at the cemetery
to prevent any disturbances.
   Hess' burial was postponed last August after Nazi sympathizers
began gathering at the graveyard in Wunsiedel in northern Bavaria.
   ``Germany was his life,'' read the inscription on a large
bouquet of flowers left at the gravesite.
   The former deputy of Adolf Hitler hanged himself at age 93 on
Aug. 17 in Spandau prison. He was the last imprisoned leader of
Nazi Germany.
   Hess' final wish was to be buried at the family plot in
Wunsiedel, in northern Bavaria. But after the sympathizers began
massing, his family decided to bury Hess temporarily at a secret
location.
   The family had kept secret the time and date of Thursday's
burial at Wundsiedel until it was over.
   The Wunsiedel cemetery was temporarily sealed off and police
officers stood guard to prevent any disturbances, said police
spokesman Rainer Meier.
   Witnesses who later spoke to The Associated Press on the
condition of anonymity said Thursday's service was videotaped.
Hess' widow, Ilse, has been in failing health for years and the
witnesses said she was not present.
   Among those attending were the former Nazi leader's son,
Wolf-Ruediger Hess, and his wife, Andrea, according to funeral home
director Charlotte Koerzdoerffer.
   Ms. Koerzdoerffer told the AP that about a dozen people attended
the burial. ``He was buried quietly and quickly,'' she said.
   Meier said police had been informed of the burial well in
advance and that authorities were able to ``take appropriate
measures.''
   He said he did not know where Hess' body had been before
Thursday's burial.
   About half a dozen elderly people strolled near Hess' grave
later Thursday.
   ``He should be left in peace,'' said a woman in her 70s. She
declined to give her name.
   As another elderly couple walked up to view the grave, the woman
muttered: ``After all these years he's home.''
   Hess' grave was covered with green ivy and several bouquets of
flowers, including a large yellow one with a white ribbon.
   Inscribed on the ribbon in bold gold lettering was the name
``Rudolf Hess,'' and the words ``Deutschland war sein Leben''
(Germany was his life).
   Two policemen standing by their vans declined to discuss why
they had been posted there. A typewritten sign encased in plastic
and tied to the cemetery gate said that taking photographs in the
cemetery was not allowed without the permission of the management.
   ``Demonstrations in the cemetery are banned,'' the sign also
said.
   At the Nuremberg War Crimes trial, Hess was found guilty of
``preparing and waging an aggressive war.'' The court sentenced him
to life imprisonment without the possibility of parole.
   Hess had been the only inmate in Spandau prison since 1966. He
was nearly blind at the end of his life and spent most of the day
in his cell.
   He had been imprisoned since 1941, when he parachuted into
Scotland in a bizarre, self-proclaimed bid to end World War II.
   After his death, dozens of neo-Nazis converged on Wunsiedel, to
show their support for the dead Nazi.
   Wunsiedel, a town of 10,200 people nestled in rolling hills 11
miles from the Czech border, is known for fine porcelain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
