<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolarBear     03-17 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polar Bear,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raising of funds snowballs to get replacement for polar bear shot
a zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign to replace a polar bear killed
by police at Vilas Park Zoo has drawn $50,000 in contributions, not
counting a company's offer to cover the full cost of one bear,
officials say.
   ``It's really unbelievable,'' zoo director David Hall said
Wednesday.
   The zoo's only polar bear, Chief, was shot and later destroyed
by police Sunday after a man with a history of mental problems
climbed into the cage and was injured by the animal. The man, who
authorities won't identify, sustained a head wound and is in a
mental health facility pending a committment hearing.
   Radio station WMGN reported raising $27,700 on Wednesday, when
it broadcast live from the zoo all day. In addition, the zoo has
gotten direct donations of about $17,000, including two quarters
ttaped to an index card and several dollar bills tucked inside a
child's drawing of a bear, Hall said.
   The Wisconsin State Journal said it had received checks and cash
amounting to $2,400 through donations to a ``Bring a Polar Bear
Back to Our Zoo'' fund.
   The Rayovac Corp., a Madison-based battery manufacturer, pledged
to cover the entire cost for one bear. ``We just decided that this
thing has great support from the community,'' spokesman John
Daggett said.
   Hall said he is hoping to obtain a pair of bears but, even if
they are found, the money raised will more than cover the expense.
He estimated the cost of a polar bear at $10,000 to $15,000. A
young, mating pair would cost an additional $20,000 to $30,000.
   But Hall said finding polar bears for the zoo may prove to be a
much harder task than raising the money. ``We're working on it, but
they're a difficult animal to acquire.''
   Polar bears in the wild are endangered, and records from zoos in
the United States and Europe indicate only eight were born in
captivity in 1986.
   ``Finding a mate the same age is not an easy task,'' Hall added.
``If we can't get a cub, we'll try for an older animal.''
   Money left over will go to the construction of the new Vilas Zoo
Education Building, which will cost about $450,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
