<DOCNO> AP880317-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     03-17 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Sees 126 Kilograms Of Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the cocaine-smuggling
trial of Carlos Lehder Rivas got its first look at a large amount
of cocaine Thursday _ 126 kilograms, worth $6.3 million.
   Lehder, 38, a reputed Colombian drug lord, is on trial on
charges he and others conspired to bring 3.3 tons of cocaine into
the United States from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas.
   The 277 pounds of cocaine, brought into court on a cart covered
with a sheet, was seized on March 5, 1980, from a large safe at a
Miami-area stash house, according to court testimony.
   Extra drug agents were in the courtroom when the cocaine was
displayed. The halls outside the courtroom were cleared as the cart
was wheeled to and from the chamber.
   Richard Crawford, a federal drug agent with the New York drug
enforcement task force, displayed a two-kilo package that carried
the initials ``C-I-A.''
   Crawford said he came to Miami in February 1980 to trace the
source of cocaine coming into the New York area.
   In arguments earlier this week over the admissability of the
cocaine as evidence, U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle said the
cocaine would be linked to Lehder through testimony and documents.
   In 1980, Tulio E. Ayerbe was arrested in connection with the
seizure, one of the largest in U.S. history.
   Defense attorneys had argued that the cocaine was not tied to
Lehder and that its admission was ``irrelevant and prejudicial.''
   The government has said it can tie the Miami cocaine to Lehder
through car rental records and because the warehouse it was
delivered to was used by one of Lehder's business fronts.
   Merkle has claimed the cocaine shown the jury was part of a
500-kilogram shipment from Colombia that was flown to Reidsville,
Ga., by Lehder pilots Ed Ward and Gregory Von Eberstein in February
1980 and then driven to Fort Lauderdale by Paul Alexander.
   Alexander testified earlier this week that he delivered the
cocaine to a Lehder employee named Jackie Mowerman. Mowerman took
Alexander's station wagon and returned three hours later in a blue
Ford Mustang, saying there had been problems getting the stash
house opened, Alexander testified.
   Crawford testified Thursday that the Mustang rented by Mowerman
was seen in late February at the Opa-locka warehouse that was used
as the stash house.
   He estimated the cocaine was worth $50,000 a kilogram in 1980.
   This is only the second time in the cocaine-smuggling trial, now
in its 15th week of testimony, that the drug has been displayed in
the courtroom. In December, two kilos seized from a suitcase in
West Palm Beach were shown to jurors.
   Lehder, said to be one of the leaders of the violent Colombian
Medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine
with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
