<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1406EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TradeDeficit Bjt   03-17 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Deficit, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Widens To $12.44 Billion In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened to
$12.44 billion in January, the government reported Thursday, but
economists said the 1.9 percent increase was too small to cause
alarm.
   Both exports and imports fell _ exports by 10 percent to $22.33
billion and imports by 6 percent to $34.77 billion. The trade
deficit is the difference between the two.
   Analysts said the export drop was expected and happens every
January. But the decline in imports was greeted as good news and a
further indication that the trade balance is slowly improving.
   The Commerce Department said that January's deficit was up from
$12.20 billion in December, but down from those of $13.21 billion
in November and $17.63 billion in October.
   If the January level continued for 12 consecutive months, it
would yield an annual trade deficit of about $149 billion. In 1987,
the merchandise trade deficit was $171.22 billion.
   ``There was a seasonal decline in exports, which have dropped in
January every year of this decade,'' said Commerce Secretary C.
William Verity. ``There is obviously a long way to go to eliminate
the trade deficit. But we are on the right track.''
   Private economists appeared to agree.
   ``We tend to be very impatient and all expect dramatic
improvements every month. But the trade numbers are very time
consuming to change,'' said Jay Goldinger, chief economist for
Capital Insight, a Los Angeles brokerage house. ``It's a large
vessel and it can't move that quickly. But I believe the ship
continues to travel in the right direction.''
   The January report represented a slight setback after two
consecutive monthly improvements and reclaimed some of the gains
won from surging exports at the end of 1987. But there were some
bright spots.
   For instance, the deficit with Japan _ still the largest
single-country imbalance _ fell by 17.6 percent in January to $3.95
billion, its lowest level since December 1986.
   Imports of Japanese cars registered a 19.5 percent drop in
January alone, to $1.62 billion.
   And the nation showed its first surplus in nearly three years
with Britain, with exports overtaking imports by $75 million.
   For all Western Europe, the deficit declined 51 percent, to
$1.33 billion.
   ``This is the first clear evidence that we are rooting out
imported products from Japan and Western Europe,'' said Jerry
Jasinowski, chief economist for the National Association of
Manufacturers.
   While disappointed by January's export figures, Jasinowski said
``the trade numbers are fabulous on the import side.''
   A weaker dollar _ worth roughly 50 percent less now than it was
three years ago against Japanese and European currencies _ is
credited with making U.S. goods more competitive abroad and imports
more costly at home.
   However, the deficit worsened in January with trading partners
who have not seen the same degree of dollar devaluation against
their currencies.
   It was up 77 percent with Canada to $1.12 billion, up 20 percent
with Taiwan to $1.32 billion, up 19 percent with South Korea to
$910.9 million and up 16 percent with the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to $1.03 billion.
   Unlike many other government economic statistics, the monthly
trade figures are not adjusted for seasonal fluctuations, although
they will be starting with April.
   Because exports always fall after the Christmas season, analysts
suggested that the January figures were misleading and overstated
the actual trade deficit.
   Robert Ortner, under secretary of Commerce for economic affairs,
said that if a seasonal adjustment calculation had been applied to
the January figures, instead of showing a $235 million
deterioration from December, the figures would have shown roughly a
$1 billion improvement.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called it ``an
excellent report.'' He said that ``in the last three months, we
have seen a dramatic drop in the trade deficit. Today's report
continues that trend.''
   However the AFL-CIO argued in a statement: ``The figures are the
reality, and no amount of theorizing can deny them. The U.S. trade
deficit, up over last month, is more than enough to show that
there's a need for a strong trade bill.''
   The report comes several days after the Commerce Department
reported that the current account deficit _ an even broader measure
of the trade balance than the merchandise figures _ increased in
1987 to a record $160.7 billion.
   The current account deficit also includes investment flows and
trade in services.
   In another economic report on Thursday, the Federal Reserve said
that America's factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4
percent of capacity in February _ the same rate as in January and
December. The level for the three months is the highest operating
rate in more than eight years.
</TEXT>
