<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT name of columnist Kilpatrick.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ President Reagan paid a surprise visit to an
Irish pub in a Washington suburb today, joining a noisy,
hand-clapping crowd in singing Irish songs to honor St. Patrick's
Day.
   Reagan sipped beer and munched on corned beef and cabbage at
Ireland's Own, a restaurant and bar, with columnist James J.
Kilpatrick.
   The president, a moderate drinker, left most of the beer in his
glass.
   He joined in singing ``When Irish Eyes are Smiling'' and other
favorites and in clapping to guitar and fiddle music.
   At the end of his stay, Reagan, who like most presidents is
seldom seen handling money, reached into his pocket for some
currency and paid the check.
   After leaving the bar, the president was going the Capitol to
drop in on another St. Patrick's Day gathering hosted by House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
