<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FloridaWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0637 03-17 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Chill Looms Over Florida as Spring Approaches</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT Key West temperature to 53 degrees
sted 56 and that it ties the 1901 mark.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RUSKIN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With spring just three days away, the
Sunshine State is shivering, and forecasters say this week's
unseasonable cold _ including some freezing temperatures and
crop-damaging frost _ will be back again next week.
   Overnight lows in North Florida dropped below freezing today for
the second day. But temperatures in Central Florida down to the
Everglades apparently did not dip low enough for a second night of
scattered frost, as predicted.
   The mercury dipped to 25 in Tallahassee, the lowest for March 17
since 28 degrees in 1981. A 53-degree reading in Key West _ the
southernmost city in the contiguous United States _ tied a 1901
mark.
   Agricultural damage from the frost was slight and confined
primarily to fragile, nearly harvest-ready winter sweet corn and
other vegetables in western Palm Beach.
   R.C. Hatton Inc., near Belle Glade, lost 420 of 2,800 acres of
sweet corn, worth about $189,000, a company spokesman said. Hatton
flew three helicopters over the crop Tuesday night, circulating
warmer air.
   About 3,000 acres of sweet corn, a fourth of Belle Glade's crop,
suffered some damage, said Sam Scruggs of Hugh Branch Inc.
   Palm Beach County's corn production was almost $33 million last
season.
   Patchy frost in Immokalee, west of Palm Beach, caused some
scattered damage to peppers, tomatoes and other winter crops, said
Chuck Eggleton, meteorologist at the weather service's agriculture
forecasting office.
   But temperatures weren't cold enough for long enough to harm
Florida's citrus industry.
</TEXT>
