<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BigIkeLives     03-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Ike Lives,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Pecan Tree Gets New Shot At Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORINTH, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Ike, a pecan tree believed to be one
of the world's largest, will escape a chainsaw after all, its owner
says.
   ``It seemed I would lose Big Ike and I said, `God, if there's a
door, let me find it,''' Dewayne Davis, on whose family farm near
Corinth the 150-year-old tree stands, said this week.
   Davis has organized a prayer and letter-writing campaign to save
the tree, which way in the way of a proposed widening of U.S. 45.
Finally, a professor at Mississippi State University notified him
that a team of forestry and horticulture experts could move the
tree to safety, 50 yards away.
   John D. Hodges, a professor of forestry at Mississippi State and
a member of the team that will move the tree, said chances were
``probably no better than 50-50'' that the tree will survive the
move. No date for it has been set.
   Highway Departent officials determined earlier this year that it
would cost too much for them to move the tree, which is 210 inches
around at its base.
   Davis, who now lives in Richmond, Va., said he read a newspaper
account earlier his week about a 200-year-old magnolia in Virginia
that was being moved, so he called Mississippi State and told his
story to Rodney Foil, vice president of forestry and agriculture at
the university in Starkville.
   Foil agreed to recruit a team to supervise the move.
   Davis said fourth-graders in Kossuth adopted the tree and others
wrote letters to Gov. Ray Mabus urging him to save Big Ike.
   ``Youths at my church in Richmond prayed and more than 150
children have formed what we call the Big Ike Bunch,'' Davis said.
``We have a newsletter and a Big Ike T-shirt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
