<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1436EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-IRAFuneral Bjt   03-17 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA Funeral, Bjt,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Man Buried In Attacked Cemetery On Somber St. Patrick's Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army
buried a guerrilla Thursday alongside the trampled graves and
tumbled tombstones where a Protestant gunman killed three people
and wounded 68 at an IRA funeral a day earlier.
   Wearing shamrocks and green or black armbands on a somber St.
Patrick's Day, 3,000 mourners gathered in the Roman Catholic
Milltown cemetery to bury Kevin McCracken yards from where the
gunman opened fire and hurled grenades on Wednesday.
   At St. Patrick's Day services, Catholic leaders appealed for
calm amid fears the cemetery killings will herald new and prolonged
sectarian clashes. For the second day, police reported sporadic
rioting and car burning in Belfast's Catholic districts Thursday.
   Police kept a discreet distance while funeral speakers, standing
amid tombstones knocked over in Wednesday's pandemonium, renewed
charges that British authorities and Northern Ireland's mainly
Protestant police force colluded in the attack.
   ``Britain attacked us yesterday ... Let Britain take a lesson
from our presence here today: You can never defeat us,'' declared
Jim McAllister, a leading member of the outlawed IRA's political
wing, Sinn Fein.
   A British army patrol shot McCracken, 33, on Monday night in
Belfast after he fired on them, the army said.
   Before his funeral, three hooded IRA gunmen fired three volleys
_ the movement's traditional salute to its dead _ in a side street
near his home. They fired over a makeshift shrine of his photograph
surrounded by wreaths.
   Firing the volleys in a side street avoided attracting police
action at the funeral. Britain has banned paramilitary displays by
both Catholic and Protestant groups in the province.
   Black flags fluttered from the windows of row houses in West
Belfast's cramped streets as McCracken's coffin, topped with the
Irish tricolor flag and his guerrilla insignia of a black beret and
gloves, was driven to Milltown.
   Gerry Adams, president of the outlawed IRA's legal political
wing, Sinn Fein, said the Royal Ulster Constabulary's denial of
complicity in Wednesday's attack ``rings hollow.'' He claimed some
police officers were also members of Protestant paramilitary groups.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, Britain's top official in
the province, described the charges of police complicity as a
``disgraceful allegation.''
   Police said a Protestant, Michael Stone, who allegedly mounted
Wednesday's gun and grenade attack with an accomplice, remained
under armed guard in the hospital. The accomplice, who was not
identified, also was in police custody.
   Stone was grabbed by youths near the cemetery and badly beaten
before police arrived.
   Police can hold the two for a week without charge under
anti-terrorist laws.
   The gunman opened fire Wednesday from behind a gravestone as the
coffins of three guerrillas shot March 6 by British commandos in
Gibraltar were being lowered into a single grave.
   The IRA said one of the three men shot and killed during the
Milltown, 30-year-old Kevin Brady, was an IRA member.
   Eight of the people injured in the attack remained hospitalized,
including four who were in serious condition.
   The Ulster Defense Association, an umbrella organization of
Protestant vigilante groups, was quoted as saying Stone was turned
down for membership a year ago.
   ``He was just too extreme,'' said a UDA spokesman, who spoke on
condition he was not identified. ``There was no way a man like that
could have been disciplined.''
   Catholics who packed a St. Patrick's Day rally in Casement Park
soccer stadium Thursday hung a poster with Stone's picture and the
word ``Wanted,'' along with his name, address and telephone number.
   ``This St. Patrick's Day we are in mourning,'' Adams told the
crowd.
   More than 5,000 people marched behind pipe and drum bands to the
rally to protest the jailing in Britain of six Irishmen convicted
of bombing a Birmingham pub in 1974, killing 21 people. They have
long maintained they are innocent.
   Black streamers fluttered from the drums as the parade wound
through streets dotted with shells of cars burned in overnight
rioting.
   Sinn Fein said Brady, too, will likely be buried at Milltown,
the graveyard of dozens of guerrillas killed in the IRA's nearly
20-year bomb and bullet campaign to end British rule.
   The IRA aims to unite Northern Ireland, nearly two-thirds
Protestant, with the Catholic Republic of Ireland under a socialist
adminsitration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
