<2ND_LINE>AM-Nude Models,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cobb County Bans Nude Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cobb County officials have banned the buff
_ at least for models in drawing and sculpting classes.
   Officials said they feared negative community reaction to nude
models in the art classes so they ordered them to wear bathing
suits, leotards or ``just basically anything.''
   ``My students don't understand,'' said Stephen Smith, who
teaches life drawing and life sculpting at the county's Steeple
House Arts Center.
   Models in his advanced, adults-only art classes are wearing
bathing suits because of a rule by the county's Community Services
Department a few weeks ago. If the practice continues, Smith said
Wednesday, he'll leave Steeple House, the county's only fully
funded arts center.
   Bob Ash, who heads the Community Services Department, requested
the cover-up because of how ``that kind of activity'' might be
perceived. Ash said he stopped the use of nude models when he
became aware of them.
   ``The community might react in a negative way,'' by no longer
using the arts center, he said.
   Kathy Hoppe, director of the Cobb Arts and Cultural Affairs
Department, has asked the county's Arts Commission to consider
whether nudes should be permitted as subjects in art classes and
displays sponsored and shown by the county.
   Ash has said he will abide by the arts commission's decision.
</TEXT>
