<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Binder Twins,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patrick Binder Reported In Good Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors at Johns Hopkins Hospital said Thursday
they were encouraged by the rapid recovery of Patrick Binder, one
of the Siamese twins separated during a long operation in September.
   Patrick, now 13 months old, stopped breathing Sunday after
choking while feeding through a nasal tube, according to hospital
officials.
   The West German boy was listed in good condition, after spending
several days in the intensive care unit, and was returned to the
room he shares with his brother, Benjamin.
   According to hospital spokeswoman Lisa Hillman, doctors were
hopeful Patrick will return to his previous level of functioning,
which was that of an infant 3 or 4 months old.
   No decision has been made on when the twins might go home, she
said.
   The twins, joined at the back of head at birth, were separated
in a 23-hour operation.
