<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CountryAwards     03-17 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Country Awards,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Academy of Country Music Announces Instrumentalist Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drummer Archie Francis on Thursday won his
11th Academy of Country Music Award, and fiddler Johnny Gimble and
steel guitarist J.D. Maness each won their 10th trophies to lead
winners in instrumental categories.
   The winners were announced Thursday by academy Executive
Director Bill Boyd; trophies will be presented during the 23rd
annual Academy of Country Music Awards on Monday in Buena Park.
   Bass player Emory Gordy Jr., guitarist Chet Atkins and
keyboardist John Hobbs won their second consecutive academy
trophies, Boyd said. Winners were picked by ballots cast by the
2,500-member academy.
   David Hungate tied Gordy in the bass category, Ronnie Milsap
tied Hobbs in the keyboard category, and Ricky Skaggs, who plays
mandolin, tied with Jerry Douglas, who plays the dobro, in the
specialty instrument category.
   The Strangers won their eighth touring band trophy and Nashville
Now won the non-touring band award.
   The academy announced earlier that the nation's top country
music radio station was in Arizona, the favorite disc jockey was in
Tennessee and the wildest nightclub was in Southern California.
   Jim Tabor of radio WMC in Memphis, Tenn., was selected disc
jockey of the year, his first academy win, and KNIX radio in
Phoenix, Ariz., was picked the top radio station. KNIX also won the
award last year.
   The Crazyhorse Steakhouse & Saloon in Santa Ana won the
nightclub of the year honor for a second consecutive year.
   The winners are voted by record company promotion executives,
independent promoters, music industry trade publications and
executives of the academy, said Boyd.
   The Academy of Country Music votes by secret ballot on the
organization's major awards. Leading the list of nominees are Hank
Williams Jr., Randy Travis and George Strait.
   Others with multiple nominations include Alabama, newcomers K.T.
Oslin and Ricky Van Shelton, the Bellamy Brothers, Crystal Gayle,
The Judds, Reba McEntire and Restless Heart.
   Winners will be announced during a two-hour NBC-TV special with
Williams and Miss McEntire as hosts.
</TEXT>
