<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya     03-17 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenya Government Bans Christian Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned a church
magazine that criticized last month's preliminary election as a
``mockery of democracy.''
   Attorney General Matthew Muli on Tuesday banned ``all past and
future issues'' of Beyond magazine, which is sponsored by the
National Christian Council of Kenya.
   Staff members tried Wednesday to deliver a truckload of back
issues to police, but officers refused to accept them, the deputy
editor, Rev. Ibrahim Dmondi, said.
   ``We were told we can keep them until the government makes a
public announcement on what should be done with the old copies,''
Omondi told The Associated Press.
   Under Kenya's penal code, it is illegal to print, make, import,
publish, sell, offer for sale or supply, distribute, reproduce, or
have in one's possession a prohibited publication. Violation of the
law carries a prison term of up to three years.
   The ban came one week after Beyond, in a special edition,
criticized the Feb. 22 primary elections for Parliament as ``a
mockery of democracy.'' During the primary, voters were required to
line up behind candidates or their agents, and Beyond charged that
some voters were intimidated by administration officials into
voting for certain candidates.
   Officials of Kenya Africa National Union, the country's only
political party, have acknowledged there were problems with the
system, but they accused Beyond of exaggerating the problems and of
``sloppy journalism.''
   The general election is set for Monday and voting will be by
secret ballot.
   Beyond editor Bedan Mbugua, who attended Biola College in La
Mirada, Calif., said in an interview that he stood by Beyond's
claims.
   ``When we saw something going wrong in our society, we commented
without fear or favor,'' he said.
   ``I feel we have lived up to the journalism we were committed
to,'' said Mbugua.
   Police Special Branch officers, who are responsible for internal
security, questioned Mbugua for two hours March 10, the day after
Beyond went on sale.
   Beyond has been published since June 1985 and is sponsored by
the National Council of Churches of Kenya, a grouping of Protestant
churches.
   The only other local publication to be banned was the newspaper
Voice of Kenya, which was published by Nairobi North Co. and
sponsored by the Libyan Embassy. The government claimed the
newspaper was being used for political means.
</TEXT>
