<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LakeDispute     03-17 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lake Dispute,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thurmond Won't Help Citizens Restore Original Name To Thurmond
Lake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A citizens group upset over congressional
action to rename a lake after Sen. Strom Thurmond presented the
South Carolina Republican with petitions signed by 42,000 people
Thursday urging that the original name be restored.
   But Thurmond refused to become involved in the controversy after
meeting privately for 35 minutes with representatives of the group
and with South Carolina legislators supporting the name change to
honor Thurmond.
   Thurmond declined to answer questions as he left the meeting at
his Capitol office, referring them to his press secretary,
Christopher Simpson.
   ``He told them he feels the matter is settled and since he did
not instigate it or push for it, he feels it would be inappropriate
for him to get involved now,'' Simpson said.
   The dispute over the name of the Army Corps of Engineers-built
Clarks Hill Lake, which straddles the South Carolina-Georgia
border, began in December which Congress, acting quickly and with
no public hearings, enacted legislation changing the name of the
lake, dam and road to Strom Thurmond.
   Roy Giles, a Lincolnton, Ga., restaurant owner and one of the
leaders of the citizens group, said the petitions propose a
compromise that would restore the name of the lake to Clarks Hill
but would retain the new Strom Thurmond name for the dam and road.
   Rep. Doug Barnard, D-Ga., has introduced legislation paterned
after the compromise, which Giles said would permit Thurmond to
``have his monument and the people will have their lake back.''
   South Carolina state Sen. John Drummond of Greenwood said the
legislators told the citizens group that it would be an
embarrassment for Thurmond to ``ask the whole Congress and the
president to reverse what they've done.''
   Drummond said he told the group the two states need to work
together ``to save that lake, not the name'' because the low water
level in the lake is threatening its recreational potential.
   Giles said the name change will result in financial losses for
businesses that have built their reputations using the Clarks Hill
name. And he vowed that the group will continue its fight, even
without Thurmond's help.
</TEXT>
