<DOCNO> AP880317-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0720EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chamber-Lowery     03-17 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chamber-Lowery,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chamber President Wrote Lowery About Report of `Negative' News
Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chamber of Commerce has apologized to the
Rev. Joseph Lowery for including stories profiling civil rights
activists on a list of potentially negative stories journalists
might write during the Democratic National Convention.
   Chamber President Jerry Bartels had received complaints on
Lowery's behalf after reports that chamber officials regarded the
president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference as a
public relations liability.
   A chamber official said Wednesday the group made a mistake in
putting the subject of profiles of civil rights activists on a list
of potentially negative news stories about Atlanta.
   Barry King, the chamber's vice president for communication, said
lists of ``positive'' and ``negative'' potential media topics were
drafted to help the chamber prepare to respond to reporters'
questions during the convention this July.
   The lists appeared in the chamber's newsletter last month. The
Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution subsequently reported
that chamber officials considered Lowery among the ``negative''
news figures.
   Negative subjects on the chamber's list include Ku Klux Klan
activity, nude dance clubs and textbook banning. On the positive
list were Southern hospitality, the book and movie ``Gone With the
Wind,'' and Atlanta's Fortune 500 companies.
   Following the news reports, Bartels wrote Lowery, saying the
chamber considers him a positive force in Atlanta. No other letters
were sent, King said, because there were no other questions about
the chamber's views on a specific civil rights figure.
   However, Lowery said Tuesday that he didn't consider the letter
an apology. ``What he never did explain was how profiles of civil
rights leaders get in a negative category,'' he said.
   ``We never mentioned the names of anybody on any of these
lists,'' King said. He said he regretted that ``positive'' and
``negative'' labels were used.
   Many of the stories, he said, could turn out to be flattering or
derogatory depending on how they were written. A story about civil
rights might be negative, he said, because the ``overall record of
achievement could be questioned.''
   If reporters ask about civil rights leaders, he said, ``We would
simply put them in touch with the civil rights leaders.''
</TEXT>
