<HEAD>Illinois Victor Optimistic about Michigan, Wisconsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Simon, his Democratic presidential
candidacy rejuvenated by his homestate primary win, campaigned
Wednesday on the prospect of a brokered convention and said he was
``as acceptable as a second choice as anyone.''
   Simon toured Wisconsin and Michigan, both with important
contests in the coming weeks, and expressed hope he'll be the
mutual ``second choice'' who might emerge with the presidential
nomination once the front-runners have fallen short of victory.
   ``We're not going to have a first-ballot winner in Atlanta,'' he
said.
   ``I will have a significant block of delegates. ... I think Paul
Simon is as acceptable as a second choice as anyone,'' he said. ``I
think I stand in a very good position.''
   Simon did not predict victory for himself in Michigan's March 26
caucuses or Wisconsin's April 5 primary, but he said he would pick
up enough convention delegates to stay in the race.
   ``I've come to Michigan not expecting to carry Michigan, but I'd
like to pick up as many delegates as I can,'' Simon told a news
conference near the state Capitol.
   In Milwaukee earlier in the day, he said, ``I can't tell you
precisely where I think we'll come in, but I think we have a good
shot of winning here and I am going to make every effort to win.''
   Simon won a lopsided Illinois primary victory Tuesday, followed
by another favorite son, Jesse Jackson, in second, and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis relegated to a lackluster third.
   Dukakis and Jackson top the race for delegates with more than
400 apiece, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. is in second, while Simon and Rep.
Richard Gephardt stand far back in the count.
