<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Plane, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0784,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Colombian Plane with 136 Aboard Reportedly Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with police reporting plane crash; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CUCUTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A domestic jetliner with up to 136
people aboard crashed during a storm in the northern Colombia
mountains Thursday and burst into flames, with no immediate sign of
survivors, officials said.
   The Boeing 727 had just left Cucuta, about 250 miles northeast
of Bogota, and crashed at nearby Zulia, police at the town said,
quoting witnesses.
   There was no immediate confirmation from the Civil Aeronautics
Agency, which reported the Avianca flight missing soon after
takeoff.
   Zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane
clipped some trees, then slammed into the earth and burned, and
they saw no survivors.
   According to the government air transport agency, it left Cucuta
near the Venezuelan border at 1:16 p.m. for Barranquilla, a
Caribbean port 250 miles northwest.
   How many people were on the flight was not clear. The agency
said 136, including five crew members, but Avianca said there were
78 passengers and six crew.
   The control tower at Cucuta lost contact with the plane 15
minutes after takeoff as the aircraft traveled through the
mountainous region in stormy weather, the aeronatics agency said,
adding that it did not report mechanical problems.
   Colombia's last major air crash occurred July 27, 1985, when an
air force transport plane went down in the Amazon jungle, killing
74 people. It was transporting passengers because of an airline
strike.
</TEXT>
