<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy     03-17 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Mita Is Asked To Form New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francesco Cossiga on Wednesday asked
Ciriaco De Mita, leader of the dominant Christian Democrats, to try
to form Italy's 48th government since World War II.
   De Mita, 60, indicated he would seek to put together a coalition
of the same five parties that have governed off and on since 1981:
Christian Democrats, Socialists, Republicans, Social Democrats and
Liberals.
   Cossiga named De Mita premier-designate after three days of
consultations with political leaders following Premier Giovanni
Goria's resignation. Goria, a Christian Democrat, stepped down
Friday after 7{ turbulent months in office.
   De Mita told reporters at Quirinal Palace after meeting Cossiga
that he would open negotiations Friday with the other parties.
   He said the Christian Democrats want solidarity ``among the same
five parties of the coalition.''
   The key to De Mita's chances will be support of the Socialists,
the No. 2 party in the coalition. Socialist leader Bettino Craxi
said Wednesday he did not object to De Mita's candidacy but that
his support would depend on the program outlined.
   Among divisive issues facing De Mita is Italy's nuclear policy.
A government decision last week to resume construction of a nuclear
power plant near Rome angered the Socialists and helped force Goria
to resign.
   Also in dispute is the fate of the secret vote in Parliament.
The Socialists want the secret vote abolished.
   The bald-pated De Mita was elected in 1982 as secretary of the
Christian Democrats, a post many consider the most powerful
political position in Italy.
   De Mita, son of a tailor, was born in Nusco, a small hill town
near Naples. He entered politics in the 1950s after earning a law
degree. He was elected to Parliament in 1963 and has held his seat
since then, serving as a minister in several governments in the
1970s.
   Political commentators and cartoonists often poke fun at De
Mita's thick southern accent. He and his wife Anna Maria have four
children.
</TEXT>
