<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Candidates-Money 1stLd-Writethru a0789 03-17 0913</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Money, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Face New Fund-Raising</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS attribution in graf 21, bgng Dukakis has ... to
Leslie Dach, sted Gearan</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential candidates who made it
through the costly Super Tuesday and Illinois contests are now
lining up fund-raising events to see them through the rest of the
primary season.
   Some of the most cash-draining states are yet to come _ New
York, Pennsylvania, California and Ohio.
   Vice President George Bush has no money worries, and GOP rival
Pat Robertson has already shelled out nearly all he can legally
spend. But the Democrats continue hunting for cash for their
generally lighter treasuries, and Republican Sen. Bob Dole is also
seeking contributions.
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri both are scrimping along, looking to draw enough
contributions to keep their campaigns afloat beyond caucuses on
March 26 in Michigan and primaries March 29 in Connecticut and
April 5 in Wisconsin.
   The Democratic money leader, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
has ``an active April fund-raising schedule,'' and remains in good
financial shape, a spokesman said.
   Democrat Jesse Jackson, whose fund-raising has trailed that of
opponents, has been picking up money through an aggressive mail
program, and will appeal for money in California this weekend.
   Aides to Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee did not return calls
Thursday to discuss his financial picture.
   Bush's schedule includes a handful of dinners and receptions
through April, and then he can close up his fund-raising shop. That
is because he will have brought in as much as he can spend on his
primary campaign under election law rules, said campaign treasurer
Fred Bush, who is no relation to the candidate.
   The limit is $27 million, and the campaign figures on another $2
million or so for legal and accounting costs, which are exempt from
the limit.
   Money has been pouring into the Bush coffers as he heads to
all-but-certain nomination this summer.
   The vice president's push down the fund-raising home stretch
included a $1,000-a-person dinner Thursday night in Washington, for
which 170 people were signed up and another two dozen had to be
turned away, said the campaign treasurer.
   In addition to the events, Bush will mail one more appeal to his
70,000 or so donors who have not yet ``maxed out'' with the $1,000
maximum contribution they are allowed to give.
   Bush currently has more than $4 million in cash on hand,
spokeswoman Ede Holiday said Thursday. Although he has nearly
raised the limit, he can continue campaigning because he has not
spent it all.
   In a different situation is GOP rival Robertson, the former TV
evangelist, who must drastically scale back his campaign operation
to avoid exceeding the spending limit.
   Robertson has said he will rely heavily on volunteer efforts to
see him through the rest of the campaign.
   Dale Tate, a spokeswoman for Sen. Dole of Kansas said that after
Dole's poor showing on Super Tuesday and in Illinois, receipts had
not ``fallen off precipitously.''
   In fact, she said, people have been calling unsolicited to
pledge money and urge him not to drop out.
   ``These are Republicans saying we think there should be a
race,'' she said.
   On Friday, callers pledged $140,000, on Monday $95,000 and on
Tuesday $60,000, she said. Still, she added, ``we're not bathing in
dollars,'' and no decisions on TV advertising have been made for
the campaign's next targeted state, Wisconsin.
   Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said the campaign raised $100,000
Wednesday night in New York and is focusing on raising money for
the New York and Pennsylvania primaries. Dukakis' strong showing in
the 20-state Super Tuesday contests on March 8 has kept money
flowing to him, he said.
   Dukakis has about $1.5 million in the bank, not counting the
more than $600,000 he got this week in federal matching funds, said
spokesman Leslie Dach.
   For Simon and Gephardt, both of whom did poorly in the Super
Tuesday races, the situation was not so bright, although both said
they were not in debt.
   Both also said they had record fund-raising months in February _
Gephardt collecting $1.2 million and Simon more than $900,000. A
Simon spokesman conceded, ``March will not be a record for us as
February was.''
   ``It's a day-to-day thing,'' said Gephardt's spokesman Mark
Johnson. ``We're using aggressive fund-raising'' techniques, mostly
involving phone calls to contributors. ``You're at a point now
where cash flow is very important, and you need a quick
turnaround,'' he said.
   Gephardt is is targeting Michigan for a heavy advertising
campaign, but Johnson said he has no idea whether any loans will be
taken out.
   Simon spokesman David Carle said that after paying off remaining
bank debt Thursday the campaign had around $300,000 in cash on
hand. Simon has scaled back his operation, laying off about 15
people at the campaign headquarters, on the heels of more than 250
layoffs after the Iowa, New Hampshire and Super Tuesday contests,
Carle said.
   Simon collected about $60,000 at a Chicago event Monday night,
and expected to bring in another $25,000 Thursday night in New York.
   A mailing to Simon's 50,000 contributors will go out next week,
and unsolicited donations came in following Simon's victory in his
home state of Illinois, Carle said. He declined to give specific
figures.
   Simon will strongly contest Wisconsin, with a large TV campaign,
but will not buy ads in Michigan, he said.
</TEXT>
