<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusDrivers-Drugs     03-17 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Drivers-Drugs,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven People Arrested In Drug Sting Involving School Bus Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five current or former school bus drivers
were among seven people arrested in an investigation into drug
dealing and marijuana use, officials said Wednesday.
   More arrests are expected.
   ``The problem was so great, we decided not to end this
operation,'' said Officer Wayne Hoskins of the department's Drug
Enforcement Unit. ``To me, this is one of the biggest things we've
done. These guys were driving busloads of kids around. That bothers
me as a citizen, not just a cop. My kids have rode those buses.''
   Hoskins said Officer Harold Robinson posed as a bus driver to
gather evidence. Robinson made a drug buy within a week of being
hired Jan. 8, police said.
   ``He let it be known he was looking and it went down that
quick,'' Hoskins said. ``It's really unbelieveable how bad it was.
We're talking about a lot of people involved in drugs down there.''
   Linda Ethridge, president of the Waco Independent School
District board, said the police investigation was prompted by a
school district request.
   She said the WISD conducts background checks on those hired as
bus drivers, but that sometimes those reviews fall short. There are
about 150 drivers in the district.
   Board members have in the past discussed whether to start
drug-testing of drivers and will likely take up the matter in the
future, she said.
   Jafus Cavil, vice president of the school board, said he doubted
if the board could establish a drug-testing policy because ``I
think there are some legal problems to it.''
   Federal agents arrested the current and former drivers Monday
and Tuesday. The three current drivers were fired.
   Hoskins said police monitored the drivers suspected of using
drugs to ensure they were capable of driving.
   The undercover officer found both marijuana and cocaine sold and
used at the bus barn before morning routes, Hoskins said.
</TEXT>
