<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAfricaProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0781 03-17 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0781,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Activists Urge Commuting Of Death Sentences</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with Shultz protest phone call, INSERTS three grafs
after 3rd graf bgng ``She likened.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of anti-apartheid activists called on
the South African government Wednesday to commute the death
sentences of six blacks who were involved in a 1984 demonstration
during which a black deputy mayor was killed.
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women and
a member of the Free South Africa Committee, said the government of
Prime Minister P.W. Botha was using the death penalty in an effort
to intimidate the country's black protest movement.
   She likened such tactics to those of Nazi Germany, contending
that the Pretoria government is ``on the road to totally
obliterating all blacks except those who accept slavery.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz telephoned South African
Foreign Minister Roelof (Pik) Botha to protest the plans to execute
the six, department spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   A protest also was delivered to the South African government by
U.S. diplomats in Pretoria.
   ``As the president said yesterday, we do hope that the South
African government will heed this call for clemency,'' Redman said.
   Speaking at a news conference, Yard urged Congress to approve
stronger sanctions and require total withdrawal of American
business interests from South Africa.
   NOW was joined at the session by representatives from
TransAfrica, the Washington Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights and
the National Conference of Black Lawyers, as well as aides to
presidental candidate Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., and Rep. Mervyn
Dymally, D-Calif., chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus.
   The groups praised the Reagan administration for joining the
British and West German governments in asking for clemency in a
telegram to Botha.
   At the same time, they urged President Reagan to end diplomatic
relations with South Africa and ask the Western allies to join in a
trade embargo.
   ``We've seen what this government can do against Poland and
Panama,'' Yard said ``Why not South Africa?''
   The South African prisoners, known as the Sharpeville Six, were
convicted in the Sept. 3, 1984 killing of black township councilor
Jacob Dlamini in Sharpeville, about 40 miles south of Johannesburg.
   Evidence at their trial indicated that the six were not among
those who hacked and burned Dlamini to death. They were convicted
under the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds that they
were responsible for the killing by being part of the mob that
gathered outside of Dlamini's home with intent to kill him.
   Michael Prosper, of the lawyers committee, told the news
conference that Dlamini, who refused to leave his home when South
African police tried to take him to safety, had incited violence by
firing several shots into the crowd.
   The plea for clemency also is supported by Amnesty
International, the United Auto Workers, the National Coalition
Against the Death Penalty, the National Council of Churches and
other national religious groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
