<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1954EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Iditarod-Butcher     03-17 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iditarod-Butcher,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Butcher: `One-Third Musher, One-Third Dogs, One-Third Luck'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Butcher, winner for the third year in
row of the 1,150-mile Iditarod Sled Dog Race, is a transplanted
Easterner who pursues the arctic sport with a passion.
   Her victory was less than four minutes old Wednesday night, but
the intense, 34-year-old from Manley Hot Springs already was
thinking about next year's race _ and about breaking the magic
10-day mark.
   ``I think it can be done, and I'd like to be the one to do it,''
said Butcher, who crossed the finish line in 11 days, 11 hours and
41 minutes, a record for the race's longer northern route from
Anchorage to Nome.
   The record she broke was her own, set in 1986. Last year, her
winning time of 11 days, 2 hours set a record for the shorter
southern route.
   Butcher has run the race 11 times, finishing second twice and in
the money _ or among the top 20 _ all but once, in 1985, when she
scratched after a cow moose charged her 17-dog team, killing one
animal and injuring five others.
   Butcher is an outgoing, strongly built woman who works out daily
along with teams from her 150-dog kennel. She once took four dogs
to the summit of Mount McKinley, at 20,320 feet, the highest peak
in North America.
   Dave Monson, her lawyer husband, shares her passion for dog
racing and several weeks ago won the equally challenging Yukon
Quest International Sled Dog Race from Fairbanks to Whitehorse in
the Yukon Territory.
   Butcher grew up in Cambridge, Mass., moving to Colorado when she
was 16 along with two Siberian huskies she had bought as pets.
There she worked as a veterinary technician.
   She moved to Alaska in 1975 because she was looking for a
wilderness lifestyle.
   Butcher married Monson two years ago and they live 140 miles
from Fairbanks in a 16-by-19-foot cabin with no running water and a
gas-driven generator for electricity. She draws water for her 150
dogs from a nearby creek.
   Of her $50,000 Iditarod first-place prize in 1986, ``every cent
went back into the kennels,'' she said.
   ``I train them 12 months of the year,'' Butcher said in a recent
interview. ``In summer I run dogs in harness pulling a four-wheel
cart. Once the snow starts falling, I run eight to 10 to a team
from 10 to 50 miles a day.''
   ``They're worth $1,000 to $6,000 apiece, so they're precious,
besides the emotional involvement,'' she said.
   ``They love competition. They're professional athletes, and I'm
more like a coach. Coaching to victory is the job of a musher. The
formula for winning is one-third musher, one-third dogs and
one-third luck.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 2002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0834 03-17 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0834,0778</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Trials Begin, Arab Wounds Israeli</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Yair Nissimi ... CORRECTING 2nd reference
to Segen-Cohen, not Segen-Cohel. Picks up 9th graf pvs, A
three-judge ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAFFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel began its first major trials on
Thursday of soldiers charged with brutality in the Arab rebellion,
and Palestinians wounded an Israeli with gunfire for the first time
since the violence began Dec. 8.
   Israeli warplanes raided Palestinian guerrilla bases in the
mountains south of Beirut, and newspapers said Secretary of State
George P. Shultz may return to the Middle East early next month to
promote the U.S. peace plan. The raid came a day after rockets
landed in northern Israel, causing light damage.
   Authorities increased restrictions in the occupied territories,
which already include travel bans and a cut-off of telephone
service to the outside. A military official said Palestinians must
get approval to bring $1,000 or more from neighboring Jordan, where
most hold citizenship and have family.
   The rules are intended to hamper the Palestine Liberation
Organization in organizing and financing the protests.
   Trials beginning Thursday involved the burial alive of four
Arabs by an army bulldozer Feb. 5 in Kfar Salem, a West Bank
village, and the beating Feb. 24 of two Palestinians near Nablus,
which was photographed by a CBS News crew.
   Neighbors soon rescued the buried Palestinians. The beating was
televised around the world and aroused international protest.
   Several weeks after trouble began in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, the army introduced a policy of beating rioters as an
alternative to firing live ammunition. At least 100 Palestinians
have been killed in more than three months of violence, and
hundreds wounded.
   Yair Nissimi and Dror Segen-Cohen, both army privates, pleaded
guilty in the burial case to reduced charges of shameful behavior.
The plea bargain would give Nissimi 2{ months in jail and
Segen-Cohen two months, and both would be placed on probation.
   A three-judge panel is to rule March 29 on whether to accept the
arrangement.
   Sgt. Maj. Charlie Danino pleaded innocent to assault and
unbecoming conduct, and is expected to argue that he was not at the
scene.
   Mustafa Hamdan, one of those buried, said of the plea bargain:
``They buried four people alive. If an Arab did that they would
have given him 200 years.''
   Defense lawyer Josef Danai said in court the burial was ``an
instance of letting off steam, revenge and deterrence'' by soldiers
in difficult circumstances.
   ``They spilled a little earth on them,'' he said. ``The tractor
driver said an ant could have gotten out of it.''
   Sgt. Amichai Vaturi, who was at the scene but is not charged,
testified that the Arabs were covered with about two feet of wet
earth but their heads and shoulders were exposed.
   Hamdan said the heads of three men were covered.
   In the beating case, Sagi Harpaz and Yehuda Angel, army
privates, pleaded innocent to assault and the case was recessed.
   Two other soldiers were sentenced Tuesday to 10 and 21 days in
jail for minor roles in the beating.
   In the Gaza Strip, a 25-year-old Khan Yunis resident, Subhi Abu
Sharar, was shot in the chest and seriously wounded, said Ilana
Ziv, spokeswoman for Barzilai Hospital in Ashkelon.
   Arab reports said Israeli soldiers shot him during a
demonstration.
   Also in Gaza, two Arabs shot 44-year-old Israeli contractor Adi
Tzabari four times in the legs near Jabalia refugee camp, Ms. Ziv
said.
   Tzabari told Israel army radio ``I threw a hammer'' at one Arab
with a pistol, ``then another one appeared with a Kalashnikov
(assault rifle) and opened fire.''
   The army confirmed the shooting. It was the first time an
Israeli, civilian or soldier, has been reported hit by Arab gunfire
since the beginning of what Palestinians now call ``the uprising.''
   An Arab truck driver in the same area tried to run down an
Israeli soldier earlier Thursday but the soldier escaped without
injury, the army said.
   Arab reports from Jabaliya said the army fired tear gas and
rubber bullets at 800 schoolgirls who stoned soldiers, raised
Palestinian flags and burned tires.
   Officials of a U.N. clinic said 25 girls were treated for minor
injuries. Palestine Press Service, an Arab-run news agency, said
soldiers in the West Bank arrested 150 Palestinians overnight in
Nablus, Jenin, Qabitiyeh, Ramallah and Hebron.
   Arab reporters said the army blocked dairy and produce
deliveries to Nablus, Tulkarm and Jericho.
   The army said these reports were being checked.
</TEXT>
