<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Flap,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawkins Seeks Resignation Of Education Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee chairman called Wednesday
for the resignation of a high-ranking Education Department official
who was quoted in a published report as saying students at black
colleges include ``a high level of thieves.''
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House Education
and Labor Committee, said the remarks by Deputy Undersecretary
Bruce Carnes make him ``incapable of objectively carrying out his
duties. He is not qualified for this or any position in federal
government.''
   In a story Tuesday about a crackdown on student loan defaults,
the Wall Street Journal quoted Carnes as saying: ``The sector that
will be hit hardest by this will be black colleges. It's possible
that their student bodies contain a high level of thieves.''
   But Carnes said in a statement that ``I have no recollection of
saying that or anything remotely like that. It's completely at
variance with everything I have said before on this topic, and with
what I believe.''
   Gary Putka, the reporter who wrote the story, said he has
Carnes' comment in his written notes and stands by the quote. ``He
hasn't denied it to us nor has he asked us for a correction or
retraction,'' Putka said.
   In a letter to the Journal, dated Tuesday, Carnes said the
newspaper article ``has grievously misrepresented my views
concerning black colleges and their students. In fact it ascribes
to me a view that is precisely the opposite of the one I hold and
have repeatedly stated.''
   Education Department spokesman Loye Miller said the letter did
not demand a retraction because the newspaper would have refused to
publish it that way.
   Hawkins called on Education Secretary William Bennett to remove
Carnes from his position if Carnes did not resign. Hawkins also
said he had written to President Reagan about the incident.
   Miller said Carnes has repeatedly said he does not believe
stiffer penalties and enforcement in the area of student loan
defaults will be a special problem for historically black colleges.
   Miller also said he has heard Carnes rebuff people who say such
colleges need an exemption from the default crackdown because their
students are less reliable about paying back loans.
   In his letter to the Journal, Carnes said students at
historically black colleges ``are as capable as others of meeting
their commitments.'' He said the department is holding workshops
and seminars to help historically black colleges with high default
rates manage their student loans.
</TEXT>
