<HEAD>Honduran Planes Attack Nicaraguan Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Honduras denying it sent
planes into Nicaragua; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``More than ...;
INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, ``Honduras has ... to UPDATE
with details.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MGA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planes from Honduras attacked a
Sandinista military headquarters in northern Nicaragua at noon
Thursday, but President Daniel Ortega's office said they caused no
casualties or damage.
   Reporters on the scene confirmed the raid, which came the day
after Honduras accused the Nicaraguans of sending thousands of
soldiers across the border in pursuit of U.S.-supported Contra
rebels.
   A Reagan administration source in Washington said the Honduran
air force had carried out the attack. However, a Honduran armed
forces spokesman in Tegucigalpa, the capital, denied the armed
forces had crossed into Nicaragua and said rockets were fired at
Sandinista forces in Honduran territory.
   More than 3,000 American soldiers began arriving in Honduras in
a show of support Thursday. Ortega declared his army ready to
``combat and liquidate'' the Americans and said his soldiers will
not withdraw from the border region.
   Nicaragua has committed an estimated 6,000 soldiers to an
anti-rebel operation in an area running from the central region to
the border, with most of them at the frontier.
   Manuel Espinoza Enriquez, spokesman for Ortega, said the attack
on Bocay, near the border, caused no injuries or damage. He said
Nicaraguan soldiers fired on the planes, forcing them to turn back.
   At least five rockets were fired at the headquarters, he said,
but did not say whether any hit the target.
   The U.S. official in Washington said two U.S.-built F-5s and
four Super-Mystere attack jets of the Honduran air force carried
out the assault, destroying one of Nicaragua's Soviet-made
helicopters on the ground.
   ``This was totally a Honduran operation,'' the official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Honduras has one of Central America's smallest armies and relies
on air superiority for defense. It and Mexico are the only nations
in the region with jet fighters.
   Manuel Suarez, the Honduran armed forces spokesman, said in a
telephone interview that the air force dropped at least five bombs
inside Honduras along the border region near Bocay. He said he had
no further information.
   Ortega called the dispatch of U.S. troops to Honduras ``one more
escalation of the war against Nicaragua'' and demanded a meeting of
the U.N. Security Council.
   A council meeting Thursday about British military maneuvers in
the Falkland Islands became an impromptu debate of the U.S. action,
with barbs exchanged by Nicaragua and Panama on one side and the
United States on the other.
   In Managua, Ortega said: ``We logically are going to maintain
our offensive. ... We are not going to withdraw our troops now that
we have recovered our territory.
   ``We are ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the
82nd Airborne Division.''
   Earlier, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Nicaragua already had
begun withdrawing troops from the border region after driving about
2,000 Contra rebels back into Honduras.
   ``The operations have succesfully been concluded, and we don't
plan to stay along the border region. In fact, this deescalation
has already begun,'' the spokesman, Alejandro Bendana, said on
NBC's ``Today'' show.
   Ortega spoke to reporters before meeting with 14 opposition
parties ``to explain to them the national and international
situation.''
   The 3,200 U.S. soldiers who began arriving in Honduras on
Thursday include two battalions from the 82nd Airborne at Fort
Bragg, N.C.
   Ortega accused the United States of pressuring Honduras into
asking for the American presence.
   The C-141 planes carrying the U.S. troops were arriving every 30
minutes at Palmerola air force base, the main center of U.S.
military operations in Honduras. The base is about 125 miles west
of the border, where heavy fighting was reported Wednesday.
   Bendana denied U.S. and Honduran allegations that Sandinista
troops entered Honduras, and he invited the United Nations and
Organization of American States to visit the area to ``establish
what the facts are and end these accusations.''
   Ortega himself wouldn't say if Sandinista troops crossed the
border.
   ``Here the question is not if (Nicaraguan) army troops
penetrated Honduran tserritory or not, but that we have dozens of
camps of mercenary forces in Honduran territory, in view of and
tolerated by the Honduran government,'' he said.
   But Honduran military officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said about 4,000 Honduran soldiers were surrounding
about 2,000 Nicaraguan soldiers Thursday. The sources said the
entire Honduran military was on alert.
   Ortega told reporters the Nicaraguan ``invasion only exists in
the warped imagination of the North American leaders.''
   ``We demand that the United States withdraw its troops from
Honduras immediately and, with this, contribute to the meeting that
is going to be held in Sapoa March 21 having positive results,'' he
said.
   Government and Contra representatives are scheduled to begin
three days of peace talks Monday in Sapoa, a town in southern
Nicaragua near the border with Costa Rica.
   Ortega said the United States would use the current situation to
give the Contras logistical and military aid not approved by
Congress.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuella called for
restraint in the conflict but had not decided whether to send in an
observer team.
</TEXT>
