<HEAD>Estonian-Americans Protest Visit Of Soviet Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel met with a
group of Estonian-Americans protesting the visit of a Soviet
government minister, Hodel's spokesman said Wednesday.
   Hodel ``listened to their concerns about threats to the
environment from phosphate mining, and human rights,'' and
reiterated American support for Estonian aspirations, said
spokesman David Prosperi.
   Estonia is one of the three Baltic countries who declared
independence on the breakup of the czar's empire in 1917 and were
taken over by the Soviet Union in 1940 under the Nazi-Soviet pact
of 1939. The United States still accords diplomatic recognition to
the governments-in-exile of the three countries, Estonia, Latvia
and Lithuania.
   Geology Minister Y.E. Kozlovsky paid a courtesy call on Hodel
after visiting the U.S. Geological Survey, part of Hodel's
department.
