<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IroquoisGas     03-17 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iroquois Gas,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Department Rejects Iroquois Gas Pipeline Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department said Wednesday a
proposed 358-mile Northeast natural gas pipeline is unacceptable
because its route across the Appalachian Trail would create scenic
and environmental problems.
   But the project developer vowed to work with federal park
officials to find a new route across the hiking trail that would be
acceptable.
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel, in a letter to Sen. Lowell
P. Weicker Jr. R-Conn., said he rejected the Iroquois proposal
because the pipeline would cross the 2,000-mile Appalachian Trail
at a point in New York near the Connecticut border where it would
have ``significant environmental and scenic impacts.''
   Gary B. Davis, spokesman for the Iroquois Gas Transmission
System, said he was confident the company could find a route across
the trail that would satisfy Hodel.
   ``The plan now is to find a place along the New York-Connecticut
border where we can cross,'' Davis said. ``We will have to sit down
with the Park Service again and discuss our concern. ... Something
will have to be worked out.''
   The pipeline, which would begin in Ontario, would have to cross
the Appalachian Trail at some point on any route to Long Island
because the trail runs from Maine to Georgia. The pipeline would
serve Connecticut, New York and New Jersey.
   The $384 million project is the first and most prominent
Northeast gas line proposal under consideration by the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission.
   But Deputy Assistant Interior Secretary Susan Recce said the
U.S. Park Service, which is under the Interior Department, has
jurisdiction over anything affecting the Appalachian Trail, which
is part of the national park system.
   Hodel's ruling was based on the recommendation of a Park Service
survey in January.
   The pipeline would have crossed the Appalachian Trail at Dover,
N.Y., in eastern Dutchess County, N.Y., near Sherman, Conn. Davis
said that site was chosen becaue AT&T telephone lines already cut
across the trail there.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission on Wednesday
took its first procedural step in reviewing the applications of 31
Northeast projects. Iroquois was the first application submitted,
nearly two years ago.
   ``It's important because a procedure is now moving forward,''
Davis said. ``After 22 months, finally FERC is starting to take
some action on our application.''
   The licensing consideration is going ahead under traditional
FERC guidelines.
   Iroquois had pushed to have the project considered under a
``fast-track'' procedure that would have avoided a series of
lengthy hearings. But that attempt, opposed by Weicker and other
officials in Connecticut, has been in effect been abandoned by the
company, Davis said.
   Opponents argued that the fast-track procedure was designed for
smaller projects.
</TEXT>
