<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Plane 4thLd-Writethru a0892 03-17 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Plane, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0892,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Plane with 137 Aboard Reportedly Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for grafs 7-8 pvs, `The teacher said ...' with
Civil Defense ending search Thursday night. ADDS one graf with
background on plane</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CUCUTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A domestic jetliner with 137 people
aboard crashed during a storm in the northern Colombia mountains
Thursday and burst into flames, with no immediate sign of
survivors, officials said.
   The Boeing 727 had just left Cucuta, about 250 miles northeast
of Bogota, and crashed on a mountain near Zulia, police at the town
said, quoting witnesses. Zulia is about 50 miles north of Cucuta.
   The Civil Aeronautics Agency, which reported the Avianca flight
missing soon after takeoff, said it could not confirm the crash. It
said two search planes and three helicopters searched for the
aircraft in the remote mountainous region where it was reported to
have crashed.
   Zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane
clipped some trees, then slammed into a mountain and burned, and
they saw no survivors.
   Passengers included a Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop and
members of two Colombian soccer teams.
   ``We heard a tremendous noise ... and ran toward the mountain
where we saw the ruins of the plane,'' said Victor Pineda
Villamizar, a schoolteacher, in an interview with the radio network
RCN.
   The teacher said local rescuers could not reach the crash site,
which he said was at about 8,000 feet.
   In Bogota, Col. Edgar Lozano, a spokesman for the government air
transport agency, said the search would continue at dawn Friday.
Civil Defense, police and Red Cross search teams suspended their
efforts late Thursday.
   According to the government agency, the plane left Cucuta near
the Venezuelan border at 1:16 p.m. for Barranquilla, a Caribbean
port 250 miles northwest, and then was to continue to the port city
of Cartagena.
   Avianca and the government air transport agency reported the
plane left with 131 passengers and six crew members. The agency and
airline earlier had given different numbers.
   The agency said the control tower at Cucuta lost radio contact
with the plane four minutes after takeoff as the aircraft traveled
in stormy weather. The agency said the plane did not report
mechanical problems.
   ``It was on the route, but it was flying at a very low
altitude,'' said a spokesman at the control tower, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The agency said the passenger list included a Roman Catholic
auxiliary bishop, Monsignor Horacio Olave Velandia of Tibu, and at
least 31 soccer players from two teams who were flying to a
tournament in Cartagena.
   Olave Velandia, 44, was named an auxiliary bishop last month.
The soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum company
Ecopetrol.
   Colombia's last major air crash occurred July 27, 1985, when an
air force transport plane went down in the Amazon jungle, killing
74 people. It was carrying passengers because of an airline strike.
   The Boeing 727 began flights in 1963 and is currently being
flown by more than 170 carriers. The 727 was the best-selling
jetliner in history until it was recently surpassed by the 737.
</TEXT>
