<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     03-17 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haiti Vows War on Drug Trade, But Ignores Paul Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government of President Leslie
Manigat vowed Wednesday to crack down on narcotics trafficking, but
made no specific mention of the U.S. indictment of Col. Jean-Claude
Paul on drug charges.
   A communique signed by Martial Celestin, the prime minister and
minister of justice, and by Foreign Affairs Minister Gerard
Latortue, declared:
   ``The government ... reiterates its determination to struggle
against drug (trafficking) ... and confirms its desire to cooperate
with foreign governments in the struggle against drug trafficking
in which Haiti could be used as a point of transit.
   ``In any precise case implicating an individual or institution .
.. the government would appreciate receiving ... a complete file,
solidly documented with evidence, which would be transferred to
(judicial) authorities.''
   A federal grand jury in Miami on March 9 indicted Paul, his
brother and Paul's former wife in connection with a 220-pound
shipment of cocaine allegedly flown to the Bahamas in a plane that
left Paul's ranch outside the capital Port-au-Prince. The cocaine
was said to be Florida-bound.
   Paul, a battalion commander in Port-au-Prince, denied the
charges, and Haitian officials said they never were officially
notified of the indictment.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeffrey Lite, however, said Ambassador
Brunson McKinley personally notified Manigat last Thursday. Lite
said a complete judicial file will be delivered to the Haitian
government within two weeks.
   The indictment was seen as putting Manigat in a touchy position.
He came to power in a Jan. 17 election that rival candidates said
was rigged by the army.
   Radio stations meanwhile reported Wednesday that the Chamber of
Deputies almost unanimously approved the Cabinet proposed by
Manigat and Celestin, with minor changes.
   Manigat has been without an official Cabinet since taking office
Feb. 7.
   Parliament rejected a proposed Cabinet last Thursday, arguing
that the state could not afford to maintain 14 ministries.
   Agreement on a Cabinet was reached Tuesday evening.
</TEXT>
