<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Vietnam     03-17 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Vietnam,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Accuses China of Blocking Rescue of Freighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam charged Wednesday that Chinese
warships attacked three Vietnamese freighters near disputed islands
in the South China Sea, then blocked rescue efforts.
   China blamed Vietnam for the raid and said some Chinese were
wounded in the exchange of gunfire. Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li
Jihua refused to say how many people were hurt.
   Vietnam has not reported any casualties.
   The official Voice of Vietnam radio said the freighters had been
on fire since the attack Monday near Sinh Ton Island in the Truong
Sa archipelago, which Vietnam claims.
   The islands, also known as the Spratly Islands, are claimed by
China, Taiwan and the Philippines.
   ``The Vietnamese side sent lifeboats flying Red Cross flags to
rescue those freighters, but they were obstructed by Chinese
warships,'' said the Vietnamese broadcast, monitored in Bangkok.
   ``The Vietnamese side urged the Chinese side to order its
warships to move away from this area and not to prevent the
Vietnamese ships from coming to the rescue of the crews on these
freighters. The Vietnamese side wishes a favorable and early reply
from the Chinese side,'' it added.
   The radio said Vietnam's Foreign Ministry made the charges in a
meeting Wednesday with Li Shuching, Beijing's ambassador to Hanoi.
   Vietnam said the clash began when three Chinese warships opened
fire without provocation on two Vietnamese freighters. The warships
then fired on other Vietnamese freighters that came to the rescue,
the radio said.
   But Ms. Li of China's Foreign Ministry said Vietnamese naval
ships fired on Chinese vessels and on teams doing a scientific
survey on a reef.
   Ms. Li refused to disclose how many Chinese were wounded,
whether they were civilians or military personnel or other details.
   Vietnam had charged that Chinese naval vessels interferred with
Vietnamese cargo ships near the archipelago on Jan. 31.
   There are believed to be oil deposits near the archipelago,
about 300 miles south of China's Hainan Island.
   China was a major arms supplier to the Vietnamese Communists
during the war against the French and the Americans, but relations
later deteriorated and the two countries fought a 17-day border war
in 1979.
</TEXT>
