<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Journalist     03-17 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Journalist,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Most Famous Journalist To Spend Year in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's most famous journalist, ousted from the
Communist Party last year for his reports critical of the
government, will spend a year in the United States on a fellowship,
his wife said Wednesday.
   Liu Binyan, a reporter and writer whose stories uncovered
official corruption and inefficiency, was a winner of Harvard
University's prestigious Nieman Fellowship, his wife Zhu Hong said.
She said he will leave Friday.
   The former senior reporter for the official People's Daily will
teach at the University of California in Los Angeles for two months
before going to Harvard in the fall, she said.
   Liu, 63, was expelled from the party in 1957 and again in
January 1987, when he was accused of vilifying the party and
attacking Marxism. He was dismissed from his post at People's
Daily, mouthpiece of the Communist Party, in May 1987.
   However, he has remained vice chairman of the Chinese Writers'
Association.
   In a statement on Liu's expulsion, the party charged that he
``confounded right and wrong and spread slanderous rumors.''
   Liu was one of three prominent intellectuals ousted from the
party in the campaign against ``bourgeois liberalization,'' or the
favoring of Western ideas, that began after student demonstrations
in support of democracy flared across China.
   Astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, accused of inciting the student
protests, and writer Wang Ruowang were also purged.
   Liu, who taught himself English, had a standing offer from
Harvard since 1983 to take the Nieman Fellowship, which is given
each year to a handful of American and foreign journalists, Zhu
said.
   Publication of three of Liu's books was suspended and a ban was
put on the sale of a collection of his articles, called ``Tell You
a Secret,'' after his ouster from the party.
   He has not been able to publish anything since.
   Liu's writing, whether investigative reporting or fiction, has
long irritated officials.
   During the ``hundred flowers'' movement in 1956, when
intellectuals were encouraged to express themselves, Liu wrote
``Bridge Worksite,'' in which he criticized a group of bureaucrats,
and a novel, ``News Behind the News,'' about the ideological
struggles and politics at a newspaper.
   Both works were branded ``poisonous weeds'' in the crackdown the
next year, and Liu was expelled from the party and sent to work as
a janitor.
   He was barred from writing for more than 20 years.
   During the chaotic 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, Liu was accused
of being a Soviet spy and a traitor, sent to a labor camp and
forbidden to speak to his family for four years.
   He was quoted as saying it was the worst period in his life and
only the thought that ``no one would know the truth'' prevented him
from committing suicide.
   Liu was rehabilitated in 1979 and joined the staff of the
People's Daily.
   That same year, he published his most famous work, ``Between Men
and Monsters,'' about a county party secretary who amassed a
fortune by taking bribes and using her power to extort money from
subordinates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
