<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Smith-Belushi     03-17 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Smith-Belushi,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Furnished John Belushi With Fatal Drugs Freed From
Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRONTERA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cathy Evelyn Smith, the rock 'n' roll
groupie who admitted giving comedian John Belushi the
heroin-cocaine ``speedballs'' that killed him in 1982, was freed
from prison Wednesday after serving 15 months.
   Ms. Smith, 40, a native of Canada, faces immediate deportation,
said Joe Flanders, a spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   She was paroled from the California Institution for Women in
Frontera after serving the full term imposed, said Hal Tanner,
chief deputy superintendent. She was a model prisoner, he said.
   Ms. Smith accompanied Belushi, the manic comic who parlayed his
popularity on the ``NBC Saturday Night'' TV show into starring
roles in such movies as ``Animal House'' and ``The Blues
Brothers,'' on a drug binge that ended in a bungalow at the Chateau
Marmont hotel on Hollywood's Sunset Strip.
   Belushi, 33, was found dead March 5, 1982, in the bungalow.
   Ms. Smith later admitted she and the comic injected
``speedballs,'' a potent combination of cocaine and heroin, but
denied any responsibility for his death.
   She fled to Canada but returned in 1986 to plead guilty to
involuntary manslaughter and furnishing and administering a
controlled substance. She originally was charged with second-degree
murder and drug counts, but accepted a plea bargain.
   She will appear within a few days at a deportation hearing,
Flanders said.
   Ms. Smith has been a companion and backup singer for such
entertainers as Hoyt Axton and Gordon Lightfoot and has been
acquainted over the years with members of the Rolling Stones and
The Band.
</TEXT>
