<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting of Central American Foreign Ministers Falls Through</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Nicaragua
^By OLDEMAR RAMIREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guatemala called Wednesday for a
meeting of Central American foreign ministers to discuss crises in
Nicaragua and Panama, but the planned session fell through,
officials in Costa Rica said.
   A Costa Rican Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition
he not be identified, did not say why the talks could not be
arranged.
   He said Guatemala's Foreign Ministry had called for the meeting
of the five countries that signed a peace accord last August.
   The ministers were to discuss ways to mediate a solution to the
Panama crisis, in which opposition forces and the United States are
pressing for the ouster of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, head of the
Defense Forces.
   The meeting also would have addressed Nicaragua's military
offensive against Contra rebels on the country's border with
Honduras, the official said. Honduran officials and the Reagan
administration said the Sandinistas crossed into the neighboring
country during the offensive.
   Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto, Costa Rica's foreign minister, told The
Associated Press earlier Wednesday his government was particularly
preoccupied with the increased fighting in Nicaragua, which
occurred just before the Sandinista government and the Contras were
to hold three days of cease-fire talks.
   The talks are scheduled to take place in the southern Nicaragua
town of Sapoa on Monday.
   President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica won the Nobel Peace Prize
for sponsoring the peace plan, which called for talks between
insurgents and governments in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Madrigal Nieto also expressed concern about Panama, where a
group of officers tried unsuccessfully to overthrow Noriega on
Wednesday. Thousands of Panamanians angry about his rule and the
government's inability to pay their salaries poured into the
streets.
   ``What happened today in Panama shows there is a very delicate
situation in Central America that does not cooperate with the
pacification efforts that have come about,'' the foreign minister
said.
   The Central American peace plan calls for cease-fires in El
Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua, an end to outside support for
the area's insurgencies, and negotiations aimed at installing
democratic governments, among other points.
</TEXT>
