<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0966 03-17 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0966,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Stands Firm on Peace Plan Despite Shamir Complaints</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with Shamir comments at dinner.
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday he will not
revise or abandon an American plan for Mideast peace talks even
though Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir complained that it was
``not conducive to peace.''
   Ending two hours of talks with Shamir in apparent deadlock,
Reagan warned that opponents of the U.S. proposal face certain
consequences.
   ``They'll need to answer to themselves and their people as to
why they've turned down a realistic and sensible plan to achieve
negotiations,'' the president said, standing alongside an unsmiling
Shamir during a White House departure ceremony.
   Reagan said Shamir did not specifically say ``no'' to an
international peace conference demanded by Jordan's King Hussein
with U.S. support.
   However, Shamir made clear that he rejected the idea. ``I have
strong reservations concerning the proposed international
conference, which in my view is not conducive to peace,'' he told
reporters.
   Shamir last October accepted a proposal by Secretary of State
George P. Shultz to hold direct talks with Jordan under U.S. and
Soviet auspices. ``I shall be ready to consider a similar
proposal,'' he told Reagan.
   However, Hussein has rejected the idea, holding out for a
full-scale international conference, and a senior U.S. official
said: ``Standing by itself, there would not be much point in
presenting that again.''
   The official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity, said
Reagan and Shamir dealt almost exclusively with differences over
the international conference.
   He said they did not review Israel's concerns about the U.S.
proposal that it cede at least part of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
it has held since the 1967 Six-Day War in exchange for recognition
by Arab nations.
   Shamir met for 20 minutes with a group of black congressmen who
raised their concerns about Israel's handling of the violence in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip and Israel's ties with South Africa.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., who heads the Congressional Black
Caucus, said he was ``dissatisfied'' with the short time alloted to
the meeting, saying it precluded serious discussion.
   Shamir will wrap up four days of talks Thursday with another
meeting with Shultz. ``We are where we expected to be,'' the U.S.
official said, since Shamir did not come to Washington with a
decision by the Israeli Cabinet on the U.S. plan.
   Shultz had hoped to convene the peace conference next month and
to open negotiations May 1. He asked for a prompt reply from Israel
and the Arabs. ``We are not setting our watches on any of them,''
the senior official said.
   But he stressed the need to make arrangements rapidly.
   At the departure ceremony in the East Room, Reagan promised to
work to strengthen U.S.-Israeli ties during his final months in
office.
   Without specifically mentioning the three months of Palestinian
rioting and the Israeli crackdown in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, he said the talks focused on the search for peace in
the Middle East.
   ``We've seen a new sense of urgency on the part of many in the
region, and a wide recognition of the reality that the status quo
is unacceptable,'' the president said.
   He said ``the present situation is a challenge and an
opportunity to move decisively to break the deadlock that has
lasted far too long. I hope we will not lose this opportunity.''
   Reagan said the U.S. plan ``offers a realistic and achievable
way to change the relationship between Israel and the Arabs. ... So
let's be clear about several things: the United States will not
slice this initiative apart and will not abandon it.''
   Explaining Reagan's stand later, the senior U.S. official said,
``You start pulling it apart, it's not going to be workable.''
   While rejecting the ntion of an international conference, Shamir
said, ``Israel firmly believes that those who are prepared to live
with each other in peace must learn to negotiate directly with each
other.''
   The U.S. official tried to put a positive face on the talks. He
said ``there was essentially no slamming of the door'' by Israel
and that the tone of the talks was excellent.
   Despite the apparent impasse, the president sought to reassure
the hesitant Israeli leader that the United States would not allow
terms to be dictated at a peace conference and shared Shamir's
distrust of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The official paraphrased Reagan as saying that peace cannot be
made under violence and terrorism.
   ``He said the PLO is revealing its real intent: no to peace and
yes to violence. We must find ways to give moderate Palestinians
and other Arabs a stake in the process.''
   Vice President George Bush, hosting a dinner for Shamir
Wednesday night at the State Department, assured him ``no wedge
will be driven between the United States and Israel.''
   Toasting Shamir, the vice president said: ``We are like
brothers; our two countries, friends and allies forever.''
   Shamir, in reply, said Israel was proud of its record as the
most consistent supporter of the United States in the United
Nations and of sharing military technology with Washington. He said
the U.S.-Israeli relationship ``is stronger than ever.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
