<DOCNO> AP880317-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Protest     03-17 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Protest,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Workers March to Denounce Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 students and
workers marched five miles through this capital Wednesday to
denounce approaching legislative elections and demand more money
for the National University of El Salvador.
   The march ended at the Treasury Ministry, where young men
wielding nail-encrusted clubs, their faces covered by bandannas or
ski masks, began jeering at troopers.
   The troopers fired tear gas, but the demonstrators set fire to a
half-dozen vehicles before they dispersed.
   Student groups at the university called the march to demand an
increase in the school's budget. It was joined by labor unions and
other organizations that sympathize with leftist guerrillas
battling the U.S.-backed government.
   The demonstration became more of a condemnation of Sunday's
legislative and municipal elections than a demand for increased
spending on education.
   Marchers carried posters ridiculing candidates of the governing
Christian Democrats and of the main opposition party, Arena, a
rightist group.
   Voters will choose mayors and councils in 262 municipalities and
fill 60 seats in the Legislative Assembly.
   Leftist parties are boycotting the vote. The guerrillas and
leftist union members say the elections are ``a farce,'' that no
free and fair balloting can be held in the middle of a civil war.
   Guerrillas from five leftist groups have been fighting since
1980 to overthrow the government. The war has killed about 65,000
people, displaced 500,000 and ravaged the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
