<DOCNO> AP880317-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForcedFeeding     03-17 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forced Feeding,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Says Nursing Homes Can Withhold Force-Feeding Of Dying
Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dying patients in Florida nursing homes
will not be forced to accept tube-feedings after July 1 under a
rule change instituted by the state Wednesday.
   ``It gives those choices back to those persons who are dying,
and not the state saying we're going to force you to accept a
tube-feeding,'' said Connie Cheren, director of the Department of
Health and Rehabilitative Services' licensing office.
   Currently the department permits life-support sytems to be
turned off but does not allow feeding tubes to be withdrawn.
   That rule ``has basically been intrepreted that if the facililty
does not do the forced feeding, it must discharge the resident,''
said Ms. Cheren.
   The new rule ``does not relieve a facility's responsibility to
do all the palliative things like giving ice chips, holding hands
and rubbing the back, easing somebody through the dying stages,''
said Ms. Cheren.
   ``It's better because sometimes forced feeding is more harmful
to the person than helpful,'' she said. ``Sometimes taking the food
during the dying stages is more painful for the person because the
body is shutting down at this time.''
</TEXT>
