<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Churches-Sharpville     03-17 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Churches-Sharpville,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Urge Clemency For Sharpville Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders in this country and abroad
Wednesday urged clemency for the Sharpville Six, scheduled for
execution Friday in South Africa.
   Church officials also expressed appreciation to President Reagan
for asking South Africa to halt the execution on ``compassionate
and humanitarian grounds.''
   The six blacks, a woman and five men, all in their 20s or 30s,
were convicted in the 1984 death of Jacob Dlamani, black council
member of Sharpville township, in a demonstration of about 2,000
people.
   The human rights office of the U.S. National Council of
Churches, which includes most major Protestant and Eastern Orthodox
bodies, urged that the six be spared.
   ``Their trial did not fulfill the norms of jurisprudence and
their executions will not serve the cause of justice in South
Africa,'' the council said. ``In God's name, grant clemency to the
Sharpville Six.''
   In a telegram to the South African government, the executive
council of the 1.7-million member United Church of Christ said:
   ``Since the judge in the case has admitted that none of the
defendants in the case has contributed causally to the alleged
crime, there is no basis for the proposed brutal punishment.
   ``We can only conclude that the planned executions are meant to
serve a political purpose in continuing efforts of your government
to deprive black South Africans of their political and human
rights.''
   From Geneva, Switzerland, the Rev. Emilio Castro, general
secretary of the World Council of Churches, sent messages to
ecumenical councils in a score of countries, urging them to ask
their governments to intervene with South Africa.
   Castro said the impending execution for an ``alleged role in
murder, which has not been proved in the case of any of the six
accused, according to the appeals court judge, is disturbing to
human conscience the world over.''
   Castro also urged continuing ``prayers of intercession for
victims and families of the apartheid system. ... May God restore
justice and peace to South Africans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
