<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Dooley Adv25-27   03-17 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Dooley, Adv 25-27,0718</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25-27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 25-27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Paul Dooley Plays Retiree While Own Career and Life Turn Busy</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Dooley wanted to act in silent movies.
   He missed that by a few years, but he's done OK in the talkies
and is a member of director Robert Altman's repertory company. He's
also done fine right in television, most recently starring as super
private eye William J. Burns in the NBC miniseries ``The Murder of
Mary Phagan.''
   Now he is starring in a new series on CBS, ``Coming of Age.'' He
plays an airline pilot who is forced, kicking and screaming into
retirement in Arizona.
   The half-hour comedy also stars Phyllis Newman as his wife and
Alan Young and Glynis Johns as an incredibly happy couple in the
retirement village.
   ``It's funny. Here I am playing a guy who's winding down. In
real life I've got a rejuvenation, a new family and a new job,''
said Dooley.
   ``The whole reason I wanted to do movies was to do silent
pictures,'' he said. ``Of course, the silents were long gone. But
when I did `The Ed Sullivan Show,' my dressing room was across from
Buster Keaton's. A few months later we did a commercial together.
We played Keystone Kops. He was so sweet. He never seemed to gain
any sophistication.
   ``The thing I loved about Laurel and Hardy was that they were so
sweet to each other. One reason I didn't want to do a series was
that in so many I saw people insulted each other. In this my
character is retired, which is why he's unhappy. He complains about
the heat of Arizona and the boredom of retirement. I find the
character enjoyable. He has his frustrations, but he doesn't insult
people. Most of my conflict is with Alan Young. Why is he so
happy?''
   Dooley, 60, has three college-age children from his first
marriage. He remarried and has a 2{-year-old daughter, Savannah.
   Dooley says he often plays younger because his hair hasn't
thinned or turned gray. ``It gives me a longer career,'' he said.
   He grew up in West Virginia with the hope of becoming a
cartoonist. ``I drew a lot,'' he said, ``and I kept that ambition
until about halfway through college. I was at the University of
West Virginia at Morgantown. I was doing plays and finally switched
my major to drama. I had $50 when I graduated and drove an old
Dodge to New York. I had to keep it in a friend's driveway in
Brooklyn because I couldn't afford to run it.
   ``Don Knotts and I had been in college together and he got me my
first job in New York. He mentioned my name and I got a job on a
children's TV show, `Bobby Benson and the Bar-B Ranch.' I played
Don's nephew for about six months.''
   Dooley, who had been a teen-age juggler and magician, next
landed the role of Coocoo the clown on a Saturday morning show.
``I'd pull a string and a bird came out of my hat,'' he said. ``I
brought my whole bag of tricks with me and I'd perform at birthday
parties. It paid the rent.''
   He became a member of Second City's New York improvisational
group and at about the same time began to do television guest star
work and small parts in movies. He was in an Off-Broadway play
written by Jules Feiffer when director Robert Altman saw him.
   ``He was looking for the father of the bride in `A Wedding,'''
he said. Dennis Christopher played his son in that movie and later
in a non-Altman film, ``Breaking Away.''
   Dooley didn't do the TV series ``Breaking Away'' because by that
time he was off to Malta to play Wimpy in Altman's ``Popeye.'' He
wore a fat suit, a fake moustache and had to cut off most of his
hair.
   For the last 10 years he's done mostly movies, such as ``Sixteen
Candles,'' ``Health,'' ``Kiss Me Goodbye,'' ``A Perfect Couple,''
``Endangered Species'' and ``Big Trouble.'' He was also a regular
on ``The Dom DeLuise Show.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend March 25-27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Rodriguez Adv01   03-17 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Rodriguez, Adv 01,0775</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 1-3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Paul Rodriguez Stars in New Comedy `Trial and Error'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Paul Rodriguez says he has never
been happy with television, either as a performer or a viewer, but
is willing to give it another shot.
   Rodriguez and Eddie Velez co-star in the new CBS comedy ``Trial
and Error'' as two young Hispanic men who share an apartment but
little else in life. They are as mismatched as Oscar and Felix in
``The Odd Couple'' or Balki and Larry in ``Perfect Strangers.''
   ``The only unique thing about this is that I'm in it,'' said
Rodriguez, a standup comic. ``It's contrived, but it's an attempt
to get more Latinos into television. Who cares? It's a job. Maybe
it will open some doors to other Latino actors. I'm happy with
everybody for going out ot the way to make the show more accessible
to Latinos. I'm dubbing it in Spanish for simulcast over radio
stations in 10 cities.''
   Rodriguez plays Tony Rivera, a funky entrepreneur who makes his
living selling T-shirts to tourists. Velez is John Hernandez, a
clean-cut, ambitious young attorney.
   ``John is typical of a lot of Latinos whose ambition is to cross
over and assimilate,'' Rodriguez said. ``He thinks if you get a
college education, work 9-to-5, people are going to forget your
background and ask you to join the California Club.
   ``My character's philosophy is that if you have enough money you
can do anything you want. His whole thing is to get enough money to
tell the world where to get off. Of course, neither of us are
right.''
   He describes John as the kind of young man all Latinos want
their sons to grow up to be. ``And my character is the kind most of
them actually grow up to be,'' he said.
   His first series was the short-lived ``A.K.A. Pablo'' on ABC in
1984.
   ``I was not anxious to get back into television,'' he said. ``My
experience with `A.K.A. Pablo' was not happy. I was at the Comedy
Store when Norman Lear came into my life. The show was over-hyped.
When it failed I was blamed by Latinos for its image.
   ``This time I said I wanted to be more involved. I wanted to do
some writing. I suggested we call the show `East L.A. Law.'''
   ``Trial and Error'' originated as an idea by Tommy Chong (of the
comedy team Cheech and Chong) and Howard Brown about an
up-and-coming young Latino attorney who still lived at home. It was
called ``The Family Martinez.''
   CBS liked the idea of the lawyer, but wanted the show recast and
changed to a buddy show. It then became ``Amigos.''
   ``When they called me I said I wouldn't be in a show called
`Amigos,''' said Rodriguez. ``I felt I had already over-stereotyped
myself.''
   Rodriguez was born in Mexico and was raised in various parts of
this country as the son of migrant farm workers.
   ``As a kid I had a love-hate relationship with television,'' he
said. ``Television showed me the things I would never have, cars I
would never drive, places I would never see. My favorite show was
`Route 66.' Two single men driving a Corvette down the highway,
wind blowing in their hair and always a blonde around the bend.
Then I'd look around my neighborhood. I didn't see any Corvettes or
blondes.
   ``That worries me because now that I'm in TV I'll be a part of
the problem as some Latino boy sees me with nice clothes and the
right people.''
   Besides TV and his concert appearances, Rodriguez has been in
five movies, ``D.C. Cab,'' ``Quicksilver,'' ``Born in East L.A.,''
``Miracles'' and ``Whoopee Boys.''
   ``My favorite is `Quicksilver,' because it gave me a chance to
do some dramatic acting,'' he said.
   Rodriguez said he is constantly asked if the show will advance
the cause of Latinos.
   ``Come on,'' he said, ``this is just another sitcom. And I'm not
that altruistic. We're happy to be working. If a byproduct is that
we help other Latinos, I'm all for it. But that's not my goal. My
goal is to become financially secure so that my kids don't have to
harvest someone else's vegetables. Not that that's not an honorable
job, but let somebody else do it. I'm not the Latino Moses. I'm
just a standup comic. My job is to make people laugh.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-PTL-Bakker Adv19-20   03-17 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PTL-Bakker, Adv 19-20,0841</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19-20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 19-20</NOTE>
<HEAD>One Year After Leaving PTL, Bakker Dreams of New Evangelical
Empire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled television evangelist Jim Bakker is
dreaming of attracting a new flock to a Christian retreat in the
California desert, even as PTL, the ministry he left behind one
year ago Saturday, struggles to survive.
   PTL, under the control of a U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Columbia,
continues to spend thousands of dollars a day more than it takes in.
   The ministry's television network is in the middle of a ``March
to Victory'' telethon with a goal of raising $4.2 million by April
1 to meet expenses, and PTL is considering the sale of hundreds of
undeveloped acres at the Heritage USA theme park to pay creditors.
   The woman Bakker admitted having sex with and paying money to
keep silent, Jessica Hahn, is living in the Playboy Mansion in Los
Angeles. She is writing more of her story for Playboy magazine,
spokesman Bill Farley said.
   The man Bakker originally accused of using blackmail to cause
his March 19 downfall at PTL, the Rev. Jimmy Swaggart, is dealing
with his own admitted sexual transgression that knocked him from
the pulpit.
   And the evangelist Bakker accused of stealing PTL, the Rev.
Jerry Falwell, is back preaching at his Old Time Gospel Hour in
Virginia.
   Falwell, who led PTL for six months, said it's been a dismal
year. ``It was obviously the toughest year evangelicals have ever
faced,'' he said. ``Credibility was gravely injured by the PTL
scandal.''
   The National Religious Broadcasters Association met in
Washington last month to set stricter standards of moral and
financial accountability.
   ``It is going to take me years to say all that I have learned
through this,'' Bakker told The Charlotte Observer recently. ``And
I'm going to be a different minister. I'm going to be less
judgmental.''
   Bakker calls his proposed new promised land Heritage Springs and
says it would be a 1,600-acre complex that would be similar to
Heritage USA outside Fort Mill, S.C. He says it would be located in
the California desert, but no specific plans have been made.
   The boyish-looking minister, newly ordained by a little-known
Oklahoma church, was used to preaching in a high-tech studio, his
sermons carried via satellite.
   The scene was very different last week when Bakker delivered his
first homily since heading west.
   For 30 minutes, he preached to elderly retirees at a trailer
park beside the Salton Sea in a desolate stretch of desert south of
Palm Springs, where he and his wife, Tammy, live.
   Tammy, who wept after introducing her husband to the
congregation in a tiny wooden chapel that doubles as a bingo hall,
said it has been a hard year for them.
   ``Some people will ask, `What have you learned in this last year
that you could share? The thing that I have learned the most is
that when everything is gone and what you worked 25 years to build
has crumbled to your feet, God doesn't change,'' Mrs. Bakker said.
   And what of the evangelical empire Bakker began building in 1978?
   The devout still travel to Fort Mill to vacation at the 500-acre
Heritage USA, with its hotel, water park and stables. The cable
television network still uses Bakker's upbeat formula of
entertainment mixed with preaching, prayer lines and pledges.
   But there are new faces and a new message: integrity and modesty.
   David Clark, a former Christian Broadcasting Network executive
who was appointed PTL trustee by bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds,
continually assures viewers the new guard isn't out for greed and
glory.
   ``The people here are living modestly and conservatively,'' he
said on the show recently. ``There are no seven-figure salaries
here and there are no celebrities. We're willing to be accountable
to you.''
   An Internal Revenue Service report filed in bankruptcy court
said the Bakkers and their top aides received $14.6 million in
excessive compensation from 1984 to 1987.
   A federal grand jury in Charlotte, N.C., is investigating Bakker
for possible tax, wire and mail fraud.
   Last week, Bakker fired his own salvo. He had a lawsuit filed in
York County against Roy Grutman, a New York attorney who used to
represent the ministry. Bakker is charging that Grutman tricked him
into resigning and turning the ministry over to Falwell.
   The Bakkers, who are seeking more than $10,000 in damages, claim
they did not know Grutman also represented Falwell at the time he
advised the Bakkers to step down.
   The suit says Grutman told the Bakkers that Swaggart was heading
a conspiracy to take over PTL.
   Grutman said the allegations were ``utterly meritless.''
   ``I think this is a publicity stunt by Bakker and his lawyers. I
was never retained by Mr. Bakker. I was not his lawyer,'' Grutman
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for weekend editions, March 19-20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-PTL-Hahn Adv19-20   03-17 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PTL-Hahn, Adv 19-20,0601</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19-20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 19-20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hahn Still Trying to Cast Away Doubters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-PTL-Bakker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BABYLON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the year since Jim Bakker disclosed
his sexual encounter with Jessica Hahn, many former friends have
turned against her. She's angry and hurt, and she's planning to
retaliate _ in print.
   ``I'm not exactly the most loved person. There are a lot of
angry people. My mother never gave me a middle name and I finally
figured out why, because it's `controversy,''' said the 28-year-old
former church secretary.
   Much has happened to her in the year since her tryst with Bakker
became public, forcing him to resign the PTL ministry.
   She was paid $1 million by Playboy to tell her story. She
claimed Bakker had forcibly taken away her virginity, though he
said she appeared to be sexually experienced and was a willing
participant.
   Her appearance in the pages of America's leading men's magazine
was just the start of her relationship with the Playboy empire. She
moved into founder Hugh Hefner's Los Angeles mansion; she denied
she had become his lover.
   She recuperated at the mansion after having her breasts lifted
and her teeth and nose fixed. She bought a red Mercedes 560 SL
convertible.
   And she was forced to contend with a series of allegations that
she was not the innocent Bible belle that she claimed.
   One married man said he had slept with her before 1980 while two
others said they had had affairs with her. She said all three lied.
   Then, a Long Island woman claimed in a Penthouse story that Miss
Hahn had worked as a call girl for her. Finally, the son of Barbara
Bencivenga Pietropaolo, a neighbor, claimed he had been seduced by
Miss Hahn when he was 14.
   ``People have made a career out of my name. It's unbelievable,''
Miss Hahn said. ``It's mean what people are doing. It's really bad.
The madam story, c'mon. I never left my house. I'm the one girl who
didn't even go out nightclubbing.''
   But Ms. Pietropaolo, who a year ago helped shield Miss Hahn from
reporters, brought her messages and drove her on errands, is angry.
   ``She makes herself like a madonna. But I still say she's like
the anti-Christ,'' she said.
   Miss Hahn has ``forgotten all her friends,'' Ms. Pietropaolo
said. ``There were times she seemed so sweet and so nice.''
   Ms. Pietropaolo said her 12-year-old daughter, Tiffany, still
misses Miss Hahn. ``Tiffany was so close to her that she said, `If
I ever make it big you'll be dripping in furs and diamonds.' She
didn't even say goodbye.''
   Jessica Hahn is working on her own kind of farewell _ another
magazine story she says will explain why so many people who used to
be her friends have attacked her. She spends her days writing at
the Los Angeles mansion, where she has her own room and can stay
indefinitely.
   She occasionally goes shopping, jogs and takes trips to New
York, where photographers have caught her at publicity parties.
Recently, she said, she bumped into entertainer Liza Minnelli at a
Los Angeles restaurant. She was pleased to learn that Miss Minnelli
did not believe the attacks on Jessica Hahn.
   Still, Miss Hahn said she thinks ``this other story needs to be
told.''
   ``I have to defend myself,'' she said. ``I'm going to have the
last word, believe me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for weekend editions, March 19-20</NOTE>
