<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0558</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industrial production edged up 0.2
percent in February as reductions in output at auto factories and
coal mines offset gains in other areas, the government reported.
   The Federal Reserve said Wednesday that the February advance,
which followed a 0.3 percent January gain, was the poorest showing
since output declined by 0.2 percent in September.
   But private economists said the gains, even at a much slower
pace, represented good news for the economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The housing industry, after staggering for two
months following the October stock market crash, enjoyed a sharp
8.9 percent increase in construction activity in February, the
biggest gain in more than a year, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said the increase boosted construction
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49 million units last
month following declines of 15.8 percent in December and 1.9
percent in January.
   Those setbacks raised concerns because housing is often the
first industry to weaken at the onset of a new recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of American Standard Inc. met to
review several alternative proposals to a hostile, $2.1 billion
buyout bid from Black & Decker Corp., including an offer topping
Black & Decker's proposal.
   Earlier Wednesday, a judge in Delaware granted Black & Decker's
request to temporarily prohibit American Standard from altering its
retirement and severance pay plan as a defense against the takeover
bid.
   Black & Decker had argued the changes unfairly would add to the
cost of acquiring American Standard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Embattled Koppers Co. said it was studying a
cash payout to shareholders, asset sale or employee stock ownership
to battle a takeover attempt by British investor Brian Beazer and a
New York investment bank.
   But before Koppers details the options under study, the company
is expected to launch a publicity campaign criticizing investment
banker Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Also on Wednesday, Pittsburgh filed suit in federal court
alleging that Shearson, as underwriter of city bonds, violated its
duty not to do anything to hurt the Pittsburgh economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the threat of a presidential veto, the
House labor committee approved and sent to the floor legislation to
raise the current federal minimum wage of $3.35 an hour to $5.05
over the next four years.
   The Democratic-controlled House Labor and Education Committee
approved the measure Wednesday after defeating several Republican
proposals, one of which would have established a ``new hire'' wage
of $3.35 an hour.
   Congressional action on the measure is expected to be completed
by the end of April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Job prospects for both production and service
workers are the brightest they have been in three years but are
declining slightly for technical, professional and office workers,
according to a private survey.
   Twenty-one percent of the 398 corporations polled in the survey
published Wednesday said they anticipate expanding their production
and service work forces from April through June.
   But only 19 percent of the companies surveyed by the Bureau of
National Affairs said they plan to increase their technical and
professional staffs, down from 21 percent for the first quarter of
this year.
</TEXT>
