<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers Bjt   03-17 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Studies Recapitalization Defense; Investors Await Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders are waiting for Koppers Co. to
say how much they could get under the company recapitalization plan
being considered as a defense against an unsolicited $45 per share
takeover bid from a British investor and the investment firm
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``That's what I'm waiting for,'' Robert Kanters of Legg Mason
Wood Walker Inc. of Pittsburgh said Wednesday. ``We really don't
know how much better the deal is until we get the particulars.''
   Koppers on Wednesday rejected as inadequate the $1.3 billion
tender offer from BNS Inc., a group led by Shearson and British
investor Brian Beazer, and said it was studying a recapitalization
as an alternative.
   The disclosures came as Shearson faced increasing state and
local government pressure over its unusual role in the takeover bid.
   Koppers stock dipped 87{ cents to $53.62{ a share Wednesday in
heavy New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Koppers said its recapitalization _ which analysts have
speculated could pay cash and securities worth $55 to $60 a share _
would include a substantial cash dividend to holders of Koppers'
nearly 28 million common shares, plus stock in the recapitalized
company.
   Recapitalization _ essentially making a major adjustment in a
company's relative levels of debt and equity _ has been used often
in recent years as a takeover defense. A recapitalizing company
generally must make huge borrowings to finance the special dividend
to shareholders, making a takeover much more expensive.
   Charles R. Pullin, Koppers' chairman, said the company also
would explore the public sale of all or a part of its construction
materials business _ one of its two business lines _ to help boost
the special dividend. It also would consider the sale of its common
stock to a new employee stock ownership plan.
   A Koppers spokesman said the board of directors set no timetable
for settling details of any recapitalization plan.
   Beazer quickly criticized Koppers' announcement, and claimed
that if Koppers explored a recapitalization the company was
obligated to give confidential corporate information to BNS.
   Beazer said that based on recent court decisions in similar
recapitalizations, Kopper essentially would be bidding for itself.
Koppers therefore was obligated to give BNS access to the same
confidential corporate data Koppers _ or any other bidder _ would
get for formulating the plan.
   Shearson, which holds a 46 percent share in BNS, came under
further fire from city and state lawmakers.
   Shearson's equity participation is an aggressive variation of
investment bankers' traditional role as adviser and financier in
hostile takeovers.
   The city of Pittsburgh filed a federal suit claiming that
Shearson _ an underwriter of city bonds _ by joining with Beazer
had violated its duty not to hurt the Pittsburgh economy.
   Under Beazer's plan to sell Koppers' chemical business, about
1,100 jobs could disappear in Pittsburgh, city officials contend.
   Separately, Mayor Richard Caliguiri ordered department heads to
exclude Shearson from consideration as an underwriter of future
financing, said spokesman David Welty.
   In addition, Pennsylvania Treasurer G. Davis Greene Jr.
suspended his department's dealings with Shearson. The state
purchased $565 million in commercial notes and bonds from the firm
in the past six months, according to Greene.
   Separately, Pennsylvania's State Employees Retirement System
approved a resolution expressing concern over the takeover attempt.
The system holds 544,650 shares of American Express, Shearson's
parent, and 17,900 shares of Koppers.
   Some analysts speculated Koppers soon would join the negative
publicity campaign against Shearson.
   ``I would expect the first thing you'll see...will be some
newspaper advertising that'll peel the hide off Shearson,'' said
Donald A. Pattison of Cyrus J. Lawrence Inc. of New York.
   Koppers alleged in a federal lawsuit filed March 11 that
Shearson violated disclosure requirements of securities laws and
that it offered to sell Koppers its services defending the company
against hostile takeovers after laying plans with Beazer to raid
the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
