<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Robins Bjt   03-17 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robins, Bjt,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Clears Robins-American Home Products Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, pressing for quick
payments of damage claims stemming from the Dalkon Shield birth
control device, has approved the merger of A.H. Robins Co. and
American Home Products Corp.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. signed an order
Wednesday to allow the merger between Robins, which sold the Dalkon
Shield in the early 1970s, and New York-based American Home.
   Attorneys for Robins, its shareholders and the 195,000 women who
have filed injury claims stemming from use of the device, endorsed
the merger of the two drug makers, which includes creation of a
$2.475 billion Dalkon Shield trust fund to compensate victims.
   Before approving the deal Merhige had to be satisfied that some
claims would be paid before final approval of Robins' bankruptcy
reorganization plan. Robins has been under Chapter 11 protection
from creditors since August 1985.
   The judge approved the Jan. 19 merger agreement only after
Robins offered to provide $100 million to cover administrative
start-up costs for the trust fund and to begin sending payments to
some of the victims.
   Merhige said he was concerned about a provision in the merger
agreement that allowed American Home to pull out of the deal if
appeals of the final reorganization plan remained pending a year
after the plan was confirmed by the court.
   The judge suggested American Home put up $100 million to cover
the start-up costs, and said he would not approve the merger
agreement without it.
   Later in the day, Robins offered to provide the $100 million and
the judge agreed to the merger deal. Roscoe E. Puckett Jr., a
Robins spokesman, said the first payments will involve smaller
amounts for women who claimed lesser use and injuries from the
Dalkon Shield.
   Any payments still are at least several months away. Court
approval of the merger is only one step in the reorganization of
Robins, a Richmond-based pharmaceutical manufacturer.
   The company's final reorganization plan also requires approval
by Robins' stockholders and creditors, including the Dalkon Shield
claimants.
   The merger with American Home involves an exchange of $700
million of American Home common stock and full payment to Robins'
trade creditors, in addition to the provision of the Dalkon Shield
trust fund.
   Merhige said he would conduct a hearing later to review a filing
by the Rorer Group Inc., which had sought to acquire Robins, for a
$25 million breakup fee stemming from a previous merger agreement
between Robins and Fort Washington, Pa.-based Rorer.
   After Merhige set the $2.475 billion figure for Dalkon Shield
claims late last year, Robins had three corporate suitors. Robins
rejected the Rorer deal and a similar proposal from France's Sanofi
SA in favor of American Home, which offered a substantially quicker
settlement of Dalkon Shield claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
