<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco     03-17 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco,0340</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Texaco and Small Shareholders Reach Agreement</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. says it will turn over
information sought by several small shareholders who have objected
to the company's bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   The company's largest shareholder, financier Carl Icahn, also
has objected to provisions of the plan that would release officers
of Texaco, Getty Oil Co. and various Getty trusts from any
liability in Texaco's acquisition of Getty Oil.
   A Texas jury decided in 1985 that Texaco had wrongly interfered
with Pennzoil Co.'s agreement to merge with Getty and awarded
Pennzoil $10.53 billion in damages.
   Texaco filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the federal bankruptcy code a year ago to avoid having to post a
potentially ruinous bond to appeal the decision.
   As part of its plan for emerging from Chapter 11, Texaco would
pay Pennzoil $3 billion cash to settle their case.
   The documents sought by the small shareholders covered
discussions on why the reorganization plan would release the
Texaco, Getty and trust officials from liability.
   The 16 shareholders had filed suit against those parties to seek
reimbursement of the settlement costs from them, and the
reorganization plan would cause those suits to be dismissed.
   Daniel Krasner, a lawyer for one of the shareholders, said the
attorneys for the shareholders would study the documents and decide
by Monday whether to continue opposing the plan.
   Texaco shareholders are voting on the reorganization proposal
and a bankruptcy court hearing is scheduled for next week to hear
the results of the vote as well as arguments on whether the judge
should confirm the plan.
   In papers filed with Bankruptcy Judge Howard Schwartzberg,
Icahn, who controls about 14.8 percent of Texaco's shares, said he
would vote for the reorganization proposal but urged the judge to
drop the liability release.
   ``The releases are a purely gratuitous act and an unconscionable
act of self-dealing by Texaco's directors,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
