<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessOutlook     03-17 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Outlook,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Outlook Remains Strong for Second Quarter, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued uncertainty in the financial markets
has not greatly undermined U.S. business executives' expectations
for second quarter sales and profits, according to a survey
published today by Dun & Bradstreet Corp.
   The business research company polled 1,500 executives nationwide
between Feb. 9 and Feb. 23 for its latest quarterly business
expectations survey.
   Based on the survey, Dun & Bradstreet's sales optimism index for
the second quarter remained strong at 69, down only slightly from
70 in the first three months of the year.
   The executives' outlook for higher profits in the coming quarter
improved modestly, with the profit expectations index rising to 64
from 63 in the first quarter.
   ``Expectations for higher sales and profits are still at the
highest levels since 1984, when the current business expansion was
at its peak,'' said Joseph W. Duncan, corporate economist and chief
statistician for Dun & Bradstreet. ``Business people remain
confident in the future, despite lingering uncertainty in the
financial markets.''
   Expectations for higher prices remained stable at an index of
41, unchanged from the first quarter.
   Results by industry sector differed widely. Among executives
from manufacturing companies, the price expectation index fell to
38 from 40 in the first quarter, while the index for retailing
companies moved up to 42 from 36.
   Expectations for increased business inventories were higher,
with the index rising to 28 from 23, with most of the gain
anticipated in the manufacturing sector. The employment
expectations index fell to 23 from 26, mainly because of
anticipated declines in retailing and wholesaling, while the index
for new orders rose to 69 from 67.
</TEXT>
