<DOCNO> AP880317-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexasImage Bjt   03-17 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Image, Bjt,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Bailout Request Further Tarnishes Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankruptcies, bank failures and a criminal
investigation of Texas' savings and loan industry continue to bash
the state's financial image as the nation's biggest and the best,
and analysts say the worst isn't over.
   Banking analyst Herb Jones of the investment firm Eppler, Guerin
& Turner says Texans used to brag that everything in the state was
bigger, better, the best.
   ``We can't say that now. We look at the Northeast and see their
growth is far superior to ours. That was never supposed to
happen,'' Jones said Wednesday.
   As the state's largest bank-holding company seeks federal
rescue, the nation's perception of Texas has become more negative,
analysts say.
   Dallas-based First RepublicBank Corp., with $33.2 billion in
deposits and 134 banking facilities statewide, acknowledged Tuesday
it was seeking federal help because of a deteriorating loan
portfolio and difficulty in raising deposits.
   Gerald W. Fronterhouse, chairman and chief executive officer,
said a loss of $1 billion in deposits since the beginning of
February contributed to the bank's decision.
   There are signs the state's battered economy is rebounding and
that the energy industry is revitalizing, but analysts say the
banking industry still lags, coping with mistakes made one to three
years ago and the continuing troubles in real estate.
   ``Real estate is still a real thorn here,'' Jones said. ``I
expect some further weakness in the real estate sector.''
   Also hurting the state's image are the bankruptcy court
petitions of such Texas notables as former Gov. John Connally, who
was U.S. Treasury Secretary under President Nixon; Connally's
lieutenant governor, Ben Barnes; oil heir Cullen Davis of Fort
Worth; famed heart surgeon Denton Cooley; some businesses of the
billionaire Hunt brothers; former Dallas Cowboys owner Clint
Murchison; and the Western Co. of North America, owned by Texas
Rangers owner Eddie Chiles.
   The number of Texas bank failures, meanwhile, continues soaring,
nearly doubling from 26 in 1986 to 50 in 1987, and stands at 15 so
far this year.
   ``We do have some other banks that are in trouble. I have no
reason to think we've hit the bottom of the problem. There could
still be some more (banks) to be heard from,'' Jones said.
   Staggering losses continue at other banks _ with the state's
seven largest bank-holding companies losing a combined $2.6 billion
last year. By contrast, all Texas banks lost $883.2 million in 1986.
   Regulators also say more than one-third of the state's 281
savings and loan institutions are insolvent. The FBI and the U.S.
Justice Department are in the midst of a criminal investigation of
some of the state's thrifts, called the largest white-collar probe
in the Southwest's history.
   Tuesday, Houston-based First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc.
extended its deadline for debt holders to redeem their securities
at a discount under a rescue plan representing the second-largest
bank bailout in U.S. history.
   Jones said he believes a major financial institution will come
into Texas and take over First RepublicBank, if the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. makes it an attractive deal.
   ``It's a very desirable institution, at a price,'' Jones said.
``A lot of worms are in there still. Will the FDIC pick them up?
That's the question. I think they will. They're going to have to.''
   First RepublicBank's plea for federal aid is a ``bittersweet
story,'' said Alan Coleman, director of the Southwestern Graduate
School of Banking at Southern Methodist University.
   The good news is that new capital will be brought into the
state, along with new faces and new investors. But the bad news, he
said, is that ``it's very tough on the people struggling with the
problems here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Firestone-Pirelli Bjt   03-17 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone-Pirelli, Bjt,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Motion Pirelli Sought In Firestone Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. has gained a court
victory in its attempt to thwart a takeover by Italian tiremaker
Pirelli, with a federal judge's refusal to block Ohio's
anti-takeover law as unconstitutional.
   U.S. District Judge Alice M. Batchelder ruled Wednesday that the
Ohio Control Share Acquisition Act does not violate federal law by
discriminating against interstate commerce, or causing inconsistent
state regulation.
   Pirelli Societe Generale SA had sought a preliminary injunction
against the law in attempting to press an unsolicited $58 a share,
or $1.9 billion, takeover bid for Firestone, which has its North
American tire headquarters in Akron.
   Firestone stock closed at $63.12{ a share Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange, unchanged from Tuesday's close.
   The Ohio statute requires a hostile bidder to wait up to 50 days
for shareholders to vote before it may purchase tendered shares.
Federal law requires that any tender offer remain open for no less
than 20 business days.
   Judge Batchelder said it was possible for companies to comply
with both Ohio and federal law.
   ``The Ohio act... by allowing the shareholders collectively to
evaluate the fairness of the tender offer and to vote as a group,
...furthers the policy of investor protection,'' Ms. Batchelder
wrote in a 14-page opinion.
   The Ohio statute does not discriminate against interstate
commerce or cause inconsistent state regulation because it has the
same effects on bidders from inside and outside of Ohio, she stated.
   Pirelli's $1.9 billion offer is contingent on Firestone dropping
its plans to sell 75 percent of its tire business to Bridgestone
Corp. of Japan.
   Firestone officials said Pirelli's offer effectively killed
earlier plans to sell most of the Firestone tire-making business to
Bridgestone, but it again was talking with Bridgestone about other
options.
   The U.S. tire maker said it would advise shareholders by Friday
on the Pirelli offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Henley     03-17 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Henley,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henley to Restructure, Buy Back 22 Pct of Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., a two-year-old
holding company, says it plans to split into two public companies
and buy back 22 percent of its stock.
   The stock buy-back announced Wednesday would cost about $512
million at current prices.
   Henley jumped $1.75 a share to close at $25.625 a share in
over-the-counter trading.
   Henley is an amalgam of 35 construction, environmental, energy,
chemcial, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off in April
1986 by Allied-Signal Inc., which itself was formed by a $5 billion
merger in 1985.
   Henley has gained a reputation for tightening operations to
boost profits in individual units and then taking those units
public. The current market value of Henley's investments in its
subsidiaries that have publicly traded shares and its other
long-term investment securities is $2 billion.
   In recent months Henley has been involved in a so-far
unsuccessful bid for Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp., the
Chicago-based railroad, land and natural resources giant.
   Under the restructuring, which was approved in principle by the
company's board on Wednesday, Henley's assets would be divided
between two public companies:
   _Wheelabrator Group Inc., which already is publicly traded,
would take over Henley's stake in its successful Wheelabrator
Technologies Inc. subsidiary and other assets related to the
refuse-to-energy business.
   Wheelabrator Group would have the flexibility and resources to
speed up the expansion of its businesses through mergers,
acquisitions and joint ventures.
   _A newly created entity, to be called Henley Group Inc., would
own Signal Capital Corp., Signal Landmark Holdings Inc., Henley
Manufacturing Corp. and Henley's stake in Fisher Scientific Group
Inc., plus other assets.
   ``This program will enable our shareholders to participate
directly in Henley's $650 million investment in Wheelabrator
Technologies, the nation's leading refuse-to-energy business,''
said Michael Dingman, Henley's chairman and chief executive.
   Shares of the new entity that will be created for Henley's other
holdings will be distributed to stockholders as a partially taxable
special dividend, the company said.
   Henley's board also authorized the repurchase of 20 million of
the company's 90 million outstanding shares. The number of
outstanding shares peaked at 129 million in November 1986 before
the company initiated a series of stock buy-backs.
   After the buy-back is completed, Henley will have repurchased
nearly 43 percent of its stock.
   Separately, Henley said it decided to waive protection under a
recently enacted Delaware statute providing that a holder of 15
percent of a company's stock is prohibited from merging with the
company or undertaking certain other actions for three years.
   ``We do not believe it is in the best interests of shareholders
to impose these restrictions,'' Dingman said. ``We prefer to give
investors a free hand to make those decisions.''
   Henley's top management owns about 6.5 million of the company's
shares. That stake would rise to 9.3 percent with the completion of
the stock repurchase.
   Henley spokesman Norman Ritter said management wasn't
considering a bid to take the company private.
   Henley also said it intends to raise $1 billion by issuing
notes, then using the proceeds to pay off its current $980 million
in bank debt. That will allow the company to arrange $2.5 billion
in new bank credit, Henley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
