<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Sears-WesternAuto Bjt   03-17 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sears-Western Auto, Bjt,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Acquisition Of Western Auto Signals Move To Specialty Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has agreed to buy Western
Auto Supply Co. in a $402 million deal that some industry watchers
call the biggest step Sears has taken to increase its specialty
retailing operations.
   Sears, the nation's largest general retailer, announced
Wednesday it would pay $19 a share to acquire 52.3 percent of
Western Auto's 13 million outstanding shares that are held by
company management and the investment firm Wesray Capital Corp.
   If Western Auto's board of directors approves the merger, Sears
would acquire the remaining shares at the same price. Sears said it
reserved the right to cancel the deal if the Western Auto board of
directors fails to give its approval to the tender offer by Friday.
   The stock buyout totals $250 million, and Sears also would
assume $152 million in debt held by the auto supply company.
   ``This is the first really significant step Sears has made into
specialty retailing,'' said John Landschultz, an analyst with
Mesirow & Co. in Chicago.
   Sears previously had acquired other specialty operations,
including its Eye Care Centers of America, Pinstripe Petites, its
paint and hardware store and Sears Business Systems stores.
   Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan called the acquisition ``an
important part of Sears' previously announced plan to expand its
presence in specialty retailing.''
   Brennan said Western Auto is ``an ideal complement to Sears
Merchandise Group, which for decades has been one of the nation's
leading retailers of automotive parts and services.''
   Western Auto share jumped $6 to $18.50 a share in national
over-the-counter stock trading. Sears rose 12{ cents to $37.87{ on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Western Auto will continue to operate under its name and
management, Sears said.
   The Kansas City-based company sells auto supplies, tires,
appliances and lawn and garden equipment through 278 retail stores
it owns and through 1,570 independently owned Western Auto outlets,
which buy the products wholesale.
   Sears said John T. Lundegard, Western Auto's chairman and chief
executive officer, would remain as head of the auto supply unit and
would report to Alfred G. Goldstein, president of Sears' specialty
merchandising.
   Last year, Western Auto had a profit of $10.5 million on sales
of $930.8 million.
   Sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenue of $48.4 billion last
year, including sales of about $2 billion in automotive parts and
services.
</TEXT>
