<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Market Back To Pre-Crash Level, Dollar Dips Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's main stock market barometer climbed today
to a level higher than just before the October crash, while the
dollar fell slightly in lackluster trading, traders said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
25,872.29, up 167.86 points, or 0.65 percent. On Oct. 19, the index
closed at 25,746.56, before plunging by 3,836.48 points the
following day.
   ``Individual investors played a big role in the strong market
activity,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It is the first time the
index has gone beyond the level recorded just prior to the Oct. 20
crash.''
   He said last minute transactions by many local businesses in
preparation for the fiscal year beginning April 1 also contributed
to the market's bullish performance.
   Today was the third consecutive trading day that the index
climbed. The Nikkei posted a 228.76-point, or 0.90 percent, gain
Wednesday.
   ``Investors are bullish for high prices lying ahead, and the
market will have to find some negative factors about the Japanese
economy before investors are going to back off,'' said Masahiro
Umemori, a stock analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage firm.
   Meanwhile, on the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar
closed at 127.43 yen, down 0.06 yen from Wednesday's close of
127.49 yen.
   The currency traded in a narrow range between 127.40 yen and
127.71 yen as market participants waited for the release later
today of U.S. trade figures for January.
   The dollar has been pressured lower in the past by U.S. trade
reports showing a growing imbalance of imports over exports. But as
recent reports have shown improvements in the trade gap, the U.S.
currency has stabilized.
   ``Basically, the foreign exchange market is real quiet,'' said a
trader from a major investment firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   There was no ``real action,'' he added.
   The United States posted a $12.1 billion deficit in December.
</TEXT>
