<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower Despite Rate Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Thursday, but
well above their worst levels, helped by a cut in bank base lending
rates.
   Trading was subdued, however, amid nervousness ahead of the
release of U.S. trade data for January.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 6.2
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,819.5 at midday.
   Volume was a light 277.4 million shares at midday, compared with
314.1 million shares at the same time Wednesday.
   Britain's major commercial banks cut their base lending rate by
half a percentage point to 8.5 percent after the Bank of England
signaled that it wanted such a cut by cutting its own money market
intervention rates.
   The cuts took the market by surprise and triggered a wave of
buying, lifting share prices from their lowest levels, dealers said.
   The rate cut came as the pound moved above 3.10 West German
marks and seemed to confirm a new unofficial government cap for the
pound at that level, which was seen as a positive development,
dealers said.
   But some dealers said the rate cut also raised worries about
overheating in the economy.
   ``The market is very vulnerable to bad news at the moment,'' a
dealer said.
</TEXT>
