<2ND_LINE>PM-First RepublicBank, 1st Ld-Wriethru,0487</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with report on FDIC loan. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, Bentsen said ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Bailout Could Cost $5 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is planning to
pump about $1 billion of capital into First RepublicBank Corp. to
offset a two-day drain of deposits, according to a report published
today.
   The Dallas Morning News quoted unidentified banking sources as
saying the run on funds would force the FDIC to transfer about $1
billion in interim assistance, perhaps as early as today.
   Sources also said such interim assistance is likely to include a
blanket guarantee of all deposits by the FDIC.
   ``Without a blanket guarantee from the FDIC, the deposits are
going to leave,'' a banking analyst who asked to remain
unidentified told the newspaper. ``You have to stabilize the
patient before you can do the surgery.''
   Officials of the bank and the FDIC declined comment late
Wednesday on the report.
   Meanwhile, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen estimated it could cost up
to $5 billion to prop up First RepublicBank, but he says federal
regulators were prepared to help the bank holding company avoid a
financial collapse.
   Bentsen said Wednesday he spoke with Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan, Robert L. Clarke, the comptroller of the currency,
and L. William Seidman, chairman of the FDIC.
   ``I've been assured that all of those financial institutions are
standing by to help,'' Bentsen said. ``They're going to do all they
can to see that this situation is stabilized.''
   Bentsen said the Senate Banking Committee gave him the $5
billion figure, but he also said he did not believe there were any
definitive figures yet on the cost of a rescue plan.
   First RepublicBank, the state's biggest banking company,
acknowledged Tuesday it had been forced to seek federal aid because
of a deteriorating loan portfolio and difficulty in raising
deposits.
   A First RepublicBank spokesman said Wednesday the bank
experienced a runoff of deposits on Tuesday, but that the situation
apparently had stabilized. An earlier drain of deposits and
customer defections had forced it to begin preliminary discussions
with the FDIC, the spokesman said.
   ``Tuesday there was a significant amount of activity, and there
were some deposit outflows,'' the spokesman said. ``But there were
no lines or confusion in our branches or banks.''
   The spokesman did not quantify the size of the deposit outflows.
   The FDIC is prepared to assist with capital and the Federal
Reserve with liquidity, Bentsen said.
   ``Each of these regulatory powers have assured me they will do
everything they can that is necessary to keep that situation from
unraveling,'' he said.
   Bentsen said the agencies would ensure First RepublicBank
branches statewide remained open, but would not comment on the
status of the holding company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
