<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   03-17 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing and Production Up, Markets Quiet Ahead of Trade Figures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with January trade report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's trade deficit widened slightly in January to $12.4
billion after two months of sharp improvements, the Commerce
Department said today in a report that left financial markets
uncertain.
   The dollar and the bond market rallied after the report, but
gave back most of their gains after a few minutes.
   The excess of imports over exports was up from the $12.2 billion
deficit in December.
   Exports, which had propelled improvement in November and
December, fell by 10 percent in January to $22.3 billion.
   Analysts had expected a deterioration of the trade balance in
January, noting that exports are traditionally down in that month.
   However, imports also fell in January, by 6 percent to $34.8
billion.
   Thus, the deficit for the month _ eagerly followed by financial
markets _ was somewhat better than most analysts had expected.
   Within half an hour of the report's 8:30 a.m. EST release, the
Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond was yielding 8.58 percent, little
changed from 8.60 percent late Wednesday. And the dollar was barely
higher against the Japanese yen, British pound and West German mark.
   On Wednesday, the Federal Reserve said industrial production
edged up 0.2 percent in February despite output reductions at auto
factories and coal mines.
   Economists said the gain, although slower than the January rise,
represented good news for the economy and further dampened concerns
about a severe slowdown in the aftermath of the October stock
market crash.
   A more positive signal came from the Commerce Department, which
said the housing industry after staggering for two months enjoyed
an 8.9 percent gain in construction activity in February, the
biggest rise in more than a year.
   ``With interest rates at low levels and the economy growing and
no recession in sight, we think we have all the ingredients in
place to generate a strong spring building season,'' said Warren
Lasko, executive vice president of the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   Nevertheless, the news hurt the bond market, a barometer of
interest rates and the economy. Stronger growth implies future
inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income investments.
   The Treasury's key 30-year issue fell $10 per $1,000 in face
amount. Its yield jumped from 8.51 percent to 8.60 percent, its
highest level since late January.
   But the stock market closed largely higher. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks, which most of the day showed a
modest loss, ended with a 16.91 point gain at 2,064.32 in slow
trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
