<HEAD>Dollar Mixed in Overseas Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with quotes following trade report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed against major foreign
currencies in European trading following today's release of U.S.
trade figures for January.
   Gold prices fell.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported that the merchandise trade
deficit widened slightly to $12.4 billion in January from $12.2
billion in December.
   The increase followed two consecutive months of sharp
improvements.
   The market had expected the deficit to widen to $12.8 billion.
   In trading before the report, the dollar was bolstered by
Wednesday's announcement that the Reagan administration is sending
3,200 soldiers to Honduras in response to an alleged Nicaraguan
incursion in pursuit of U.S.-backed Contra rebels based in Honduras.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8520 after the
trade report, compared to $1.8505 late Wednesday.
   The dollar rose to 127.85 Japanese yen in London after the
report. Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar dipped to a closing 127.43 yen
from 127.49 yen at Wednesday's close.
   Other dollar rates in Europe in afternoon trading, compared with
late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.6765 West German marks, up
from 1.6690; 1.3870 Swiss francs, up from 1.3810; 5.7025 French
francs, up from 5.6782; 1.8845 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8750;
1,243.50 Italian lire, up from 1,238.45; and 1.2493 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2518.
   The dollar was also higher in New York trading following the
Commerce Department's announcement.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $445.35 a troy ounce, down from $446.20 late
Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $445.25, down from $447.00 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, the metal had closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $448.75,
up from $447.79.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid of $6.31 a troy ounce,
down from $6.36 late Wednesday.
