<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose this morning, buoyed by
corporate takeover maneuvering and favorable investor response to
the government's report of a lower-than-expected January trade
deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials advanced 14.76 points to
2,079.08 by 11 a.m. EST. Broader market barometers also rose.
   Advancing issues outnumbered losers by nearly 2-to-1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 843 up, 442 down and 502 unchanged.
Volume on the Big Board totaled 81.56 million shares after 90
minutes.
   Although the trade deficit reported by the Commerce Department
widened slightly in January to $12.4 billion from $12.2 billion in
December, market economists had expected an even greater gap of
about $13 billion.
   The news therefore provided an optimistic tone to stock trading
and substantiated other evidence that the economy is growing
despite fears of a slowdown raised by the October crash.
   ``I think the trade number was just what everybody liked,'' said
Philip C. Puccio, manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read
& Co. in New York. ``It brought a sigh of relief.''
   Nevertheless, Puccio and other trading strategists said
investors still were reluctant to commit large amounts of cash to
the stock market until the conclusion of so-called ``triple
witching hour'' on Friday.
   That quarterly event is so-named because of the
near-simultaneous expiration of contracts to buy or sell
stock-index futures, stock options and futures. It has played a
role in wild price swings in the past.
   Chemical, forest-product and drug companies all did well,
reflecting optimism that their export businesses will continue to
improve. Dow rose 1 to 87], International Paper rose | to 44| and
Lilly rose 2 to 84.
   Takeover related buying also played a role in lifting stocks
today. Rumors of impending acquisition attempts on Pillsbury,
Philips Petroleum and U.S. Shoe sent those stocks sharply higher in
active trading. Pillsbury rose 2\ to 44\; Phillips rose } to 17 and
U.S. Shoe rose 2 to 24{.
   American Standard rose 1[ to 76| after investment firm Kelso &
Co. agreed to buy the company for $78 a share, topping a hostile
$73 a share offer from Black & Decker Corp.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.77 to 152.05. The American Stock Exchange's market value index
rose 0.67 to 298.18.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 16.91 to
2,064.32.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 945 up, 540 down and 481 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 153.59 million shares, against 133.17 million in the
previous session.
