<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose in active trading this
morning, buoyed by corporate takeover maneuvering and favorable
investor response to the government's report of a
lower-than-expected January trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials advanced 13.43 points to
2,077.75 by 12 noon EST.
   Among broader market barometers, the NYSE's composite index of
all its listed common stocks rose 0.73 to 152.01. The American
Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.78 to 298.29.
   Advancing issues outnumbered losers by nearly 2-to-1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 858 up, 495 down and 478 unchanged.
Volume on the Big Board totaled 110.51 million shares in the
morning session, vs. 68.46 million Wednesday morning.
   Although the trade deficit reported by the Commerce Department
widened slightly in January to $12.4 billion from $12.2 billion in
December, market economists had expected an even greater gap of
about $13 billion.
   The news therefore provided an optimistic tone to stock trading
and substantiated other evidence that the economy is growing
despite fears of a slowdown raised by the October crash.
   ``I think the trade number was just what everybody liked,'' said
Philip C. Puccio, manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read
& Co. in New York. ``It brought a sigh of relief.''
   Nevertheless, Puccio and other trading strategists said
investors still were reluctant to commit large amounts of cash to
the stock market, at least until the conclusion of so-called
``triple witching hour'' on Friday.
   That quarterly event is so-named because of the
near-simultaneous expiration of contracts to buy or sell
stock-index futures, stock options and futures. It has contributed
to wild price swings in the past.
   Takeover related buying played a role in lifting stocks today.
Rumors of impending acquisition attempts on Pillsbury, Philips
Petroleum and U.S. Shoe sent those stocks sharply higher in active
trading. Pillsbury rose 2| to 44|; Phillips rose ~ to 17[ and U.S.
Shoe rose 2{ to 25.
   American Standard rose 1[ to 76| after investment firm Kelso &
Co. agreed to buy the company for $78 a share, topping a hostile
$73 a share offer from Black & Decker Corp.
   Digital fell 3| to 114, apparently in response to Merrill
Lynch's reduced earnings estimates for the computer company.
