<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Canada-Dollar     03-17 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Dollar,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Dollar Above 80 U.S. Cents for First Time in Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian dollar traded above 80 U.S. cents
today for the first time in four years.
   Buoyed by Wednesday's report of an increase in Canada's foreign
trade surplus, the Canadian currency was quoted as high as 80.08
U.S. cents in mid-morning trading on foreign exchange markets.
   The Canadian dollar last traded above 80 U.S. cents on Feb. 24,
1984. It is now more than 10 cents above its all-time low of 69.13
U.S. cents recorded in February 1986.
   The currency, which ended 1987 at 76.93 U.S. cents, has risen
steadily this year.
   The trend is good news for Canadians who buy goods imported from
the United States and who travel south of the border. But it is bad
news for Canadian manufacturers, who send 80 percent of their
exports to the United States.
</TEXT>
