<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1352EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PostalPrivatization     03-17 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Privatization,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Recommends Allowing Mail Competition</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source; also running on
general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allowing private companies to go into the mail
delivery business could improve service, but such a drastic change
must be phased in gradually, the President's Commission on
Privatization says.
   Over time, the government monopoly on delivering letters should
be ended, with immediate steps to allow private firms to deliver
advertising and to operate in rural areas, the commission
recommends.
   The mail recommendations are part of a detailed report on
privatizing various government operations, scheduled to be released
Friday at the White House.
   Other aspects of the study include developing a system of
private air traffic control towers; issuing vouchers for low-income
housing instead of building public housing units; selling the
government's $250 billion loan portfolio; and issuing vouchers for
public school education.
   In general, the study reports, the benefits of switching to a
competitive mail delivery system would outweigh the problems,
although the changeover could be confusing and costly.
   The overall costs of postal service should be reduced through
competition, the commission concluded, and efficiency could be
improved. The report noted that the growth of competition in parcel
delivery has provided consumer with more alternatives and price
competition.
   Officials of the U.S. Postal Service said Thursday they could
not comment on the report until they have had a chance to study it.
   However, major unions representing postal workers already have
fired a volley at the study based on preliminary reports of what it
would contain.
   If mail delivery is opened to competition, private companies
will skim off the money-making city delivery routes and leave the
more expensive rural deliveries to the Postal Service, the National
Association of Letter Carriers contended. The American Postal
Workers Union also has opposed privatization plans.
   Such a change would destroy the nation's system of universal
service, the letter carrier's union charged, ``rural and inner-city
residents would not be served by private firms and-or would receive
reduced service at exorbitant postage rates.''
   Former Postmaster General Preston R. Tisch last fall termed the
idea of privatization a ``dubious'' solution, contending that the
changeover would be ``chaotic and impractical.''
   The conservative Heritage Foundation, however, has lent its
support to at least limited privatization, calling for rule changes
to allow private firms to deliver third-class advertising mail and
for increased contracting out of postal services.
   The recommendations of the privatization commission are more
sweeping, however, if tempered with the caution that the changeover
could be confusing, as was the switch from a telephone monopoly to
a system of competing systems.
   Changing to a private system could cause problems for many of
the Postal Services' 800,000 workers, and tax money could be
required to assist in finding new jobs and in retraining, the study
indicates.
   In addition, the change could result in varying postage rates
according to which company a mailer used, perhaps including
differing rates depending on distance traveled.
   Questions also arise about liability for lost mail and the
process of notifying a variety of companies about changes of
address, the study noted.
   Even so, it contends, the long-run benefits should outweigh the
problems associated with a change.
   The recommendation comes at a trying time for the Postal
Service, caught in a public relations bind between congressional
budget cutting which has forced it to reduce window hours and
collections at the same time rates are being raised.
   Here is a rundown of the basic postal service recommendations of
the commission:
   _Open mail delivery to competition, but on a gradual basis with
compensation for postal workers and managers for loss of benefits
and earnings.
   _Consider turning the Postal Service itself into a private
business, perhaps by selling stock in the agency to its employees.
   _Immediately end restrictions on private firms delivering
third-class advertising, widely known as ``junk'' mail.
   _Immediately open up rural delivery to competition.
   _End restrictions on private firms placing mail in letter boxes
at people's homes.
   _Ease restrictions on delivery of express mail.
   _Actively pursue all possibilities for contracting out services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
