<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-17 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rise, Gold Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against all major foreign
currencies except the Canadian dollar in European trading Thursday
following the release of better-than-expected U.S. trade figures.
Gold prices fell.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported that the merchandise trade
deficit widened slightly to $12.4 billion in January from $12.2
billion in December. Many traders had expected a trade deficit in
the range of $12.8 billion.
   ``The market was very nervous immediately after the release (of
the trade figures) because the dollar didn't immediately shoot
up,'' said a foreign currency dealer in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   ``But gradually the dollar started moving up and that built up
some momentum.''
   In Tokyo, before the trade figures were announced, the dollar
dipped to a closing 127.43 yen from 127.49 yen at Wednesday's
close. In later London trading, it was quoted at 128.15 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained more than one cent against the
British pound. One pound cost $1.8385 in London late Thursday, down
from $1.8505 late Wednesday.
   The pound began falling Thursday morning after major banks cut
their base lending rates to 8.5 percent from 9 percent.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.6775 West German marks, up from
1.6690; 1.3940 Swiss francs, up from 1.3810; 5.7175 French francs,
up from 5.6782; 1.8885 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8750; 1,244.37
Italian lire, up from 1,238.45; and 1.2493 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2518.
   Gold prices eased in sluggish European trading as the dollar's
rise made gold less attractive for investors.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $443 a troy ounce, compared
with late Wednesday's $446.20. In Zurich, it closed at a bid $445,
slightly lower than $445.25 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $448.75, up from
$447.79.
   Silver bullion prices dipped on the London market, where silver
was trading at a late bid of $6.34 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $6.36 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
