<DOCNO> AP880317-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Canada-Dollar Bjt   03-17 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Dollar, Bjt,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Dollar Tops 80 U.S. Cents For First Time In Four Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian dollar, buoyed by higher interest
rates north of the border, rose to 80 U.S. cents Thursday for the
first time in four years.
   Analysts said the possibility that Central American instability
might drive prices higher for oil and other commodities was one
reason the Canadian currency's overnight rise from 79.9 U.S. cents
to 80.08 cents.
   Because of Canada's dependence on oil, grain, mineral and lumber
exports, the Canadian dollar is viewed on international exchanges
as a semi-commodity based currency.
   It had been testing the psychologically important 80-cent mark
for the past two weeks.
   ``The fundamentals support the Canadian dollar right now,'' said
money market specialist June Riley of the Royal Bank of Canada.
   ``The fact that we have not had strong intervention by the Bank
of Canada suggests that as long as the Canadian dollar is moving in
an orderly fashion, it could go higher.''
   She also attributed some of the overnight strengthening to
speculators, riding the Canadian currency's recent upswing.
   The higher Canadian dollar is bad news for American tourists,
who got $1.40 for their U.S. dollars two years ago and now get
$1.20 at hotels and stores. But for thousands of Canadians making
their annual late-winter pilgrimage to Florida or Arizona, the new
exchange rate is a windfall.
   The two dollars were last at par in 1976, and the Canadian
currency dipped to an all-time low of 69.13 U.S. cents in February
1986. It was last worth 80 cents on Feb. 24, 1984.
   It has risen 15 percent since then, with a 4-cent surge this
year after Governor John Crow of the Bank of Canada made it clear
that high interest rates will prevail until inflation is virtually
eradicated. Canada's annual inflation rate is now 4.1 percent.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservative government has been
more equivocal on the issue, under pressure from exporters whose
goods cost more as the dollar appreciates. Nearly 80 percent of
Canadian exports go to the United States.
   Finance Minister Michael Wilson said last week that interest
rates may dip as soon as inflation falls below 4 percent.
   But exporters' concerns were undermined this week when the
government reported better-than-expected merchandise trade figures
for January. Canada's surplus of 633 million dollars, or $506
million U.S., was up from December's surplus of 207 million
dollars, or $165 million.
   Key Canadian interest rates, such as for Eurodollar deposits,
are 1.5 percent higher than U.S. dollar rates.
   Other factors behind the Canadian currency's rise include the
anticipated strengthening of oil and commodity prices in the wake
of U.S. troop deployment in Honduras and the closing of the
trans-Panama oil pipeline, Riley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1358EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-PanamaPipeline     03-17 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama Pipeline,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Cuts Off Power to Alaskan Oil Pipeline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE CROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by electrical workers cut off
power to the trans-Panama oil pipeline Wednesday, halting the flow
of Alaska North Slope crude oil to markets on the U.S. Gulf Coast,
state officials said.
   Electrical service was restored early Thursday, but then was
interrupted again, prompting the Panamanian government to announce
it was taking over all public utilities.
   The pipeline carries 650,000 barrels a day of Alaska oil,
roughly 10 percent of U.S. domestic production. A barrel is
equivalent to 42 gallons.
   BP America Inc. and its subsidiary Sohio Oil own two-thirds to
three-quarters of the oil flowing through the pipeline. The rest is
owned by Exxon Co. USA.
   The flow was halted at 2 p.m. EST Wednesday when electrical
workers joined a widespread strike against Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, said Tim Reynolds, a BP America spokesman in Washington,
D.C. The strike cut off power to a pump station at the foot of a
mountain, he said.
   BP America has a one-day supply of oil already on the Gulf of
Mexico side of Panama, and does not expect to initiate contingency
plans yet, Reynolds said.
   ``Nonetheless we are taking steps to set up a ship-to-ship
transfer operation so if necessary we can put at least some oil
through the Panama canal,'' he said.
   BP America is not sure how much oil it could move through the
canal. The amount would depend on the availability of small tankers
and canal congestion, Reynolds said.
   State officials, the Alaska congressional delegation and oil
companies also are studying alternatives including taking the oil
around Africa's Cape Horn or getting a waiver to the federal ban on
exports of Alaska oil.
   State officials have been worried about a Panama pipeline
shutdown because it could slow sales of Alaska crude, which account
for the bulk of state revenues.
   West Coast oil markets are glutted with Alaska oil, and the
federal export ban prevents its sale overseas.
   Chuck Logsdon, chief oil revenue analyst for the state, said the
Gulf Coast markets have been handling more than 600,000 barrels of
the total daily Alaska production of 1.8 million to 1.9 million
barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TexasForeclosures     03-17 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Foreclosures,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreclosures, Delinquencies Rise in Texas, Reversing National
Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-First RepublicBank, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increase in mortgage foreclosure and
delinquency rates in Texas is further evidence of regional economic
problems, the Mortgage Bankers Association said.
   The nationwide foreclosure and delinquency rates are improving,
but MBA spokesman Tom Marder said the figures, released Wednesday,
show that economic problems remain, particularly in the oil and
farm states.
   ``The trend nationally for two years has been toward lower
delinquency and foreclosure rates,'' Marder said. ``Obviously, some
of the regional problems still exist.''
   The association's figures show that at the end of the last
quarter, 1.56 percent of the mortgages surveyed in Texas were in
foreclosure, up from 1.53 percent for the same period last year.
   This gives Texas the ninth-highest foreclosure rate in the
nation.
   Another 8.72 percent were at least 30 days delinquent as of
December, a substantial increase from the 7.92 percent delinquent
as of the year before.
   Foreclosures nationwide represented 1.06 percent of the total
home loans, and 5.37 percent of the loans were delinquent.
   The association speculated three months ago that problems in the
oil patch appeared to be drying up after an improvement in the
third quarter. In that quarter, the survey showed 1.19 percent of
the loans in Texas were in foreclosure and another 7.64 percent
were delinquent.
   The MBA reported that although some regions have had
disappointing foreclosure and delinquency levels, ``the solutions
to these regional problems are of a long-term nature ... there is
reason to expect delinquencies to resume their previous downward
trend in due course.''
   Alaska and Wyoming ranked first and second on the list of
foreclosure and delinquency rates, while Rhode Island was last.
   Alaska, which also has been severely affected by the plunge in
oil prices, had 5.92 percent mortgages in foreclosure, up from 3.55
percent for the same period of last year. Alaska's delinquencies
also increased, to 11.85 percent in the past quarter, up from 10.18
percent.
   Next on the list was Wyoming, with 5.39 percent in foreclosure
last quarter, a decline from 5.84 percent in the same period of
last year. Wyoming also saw a slight improvement in its delinquent
loans, to 6.26 percent, a decline from the 7.90 registered last
year in the same quarter.
   Rhode Island had the lowest foreclosure rate of all states at
0.09 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
