<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1449EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-EuropeanBank     03-17 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-European Bank,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Supports Calls for European Central Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany officially gave its
support to the proposed establishment of a Western European central
bank that would be independent of Common Market governments.
   Finance Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said Thursday that the
12-nation Common Market should free all movements of capital within
its borders and strengthen the European Monetary System in its
efforts to achieve closer economic cooperation and integration.
   ``Free capital movement without controls and limitations is the
most important monetary policy reform for the near future,''
Stoltenberg said.
   In a memorandum prepared for his fellow cabinet ministers and
other Western European governments, Stoltenberg reaffirmed West
Germany's commitment to closer economic integration among the
member nations of the European Economic Community.
   He also said that, at the end of the process, there should be a
European central bank.
   Stoltenberg's statement came less than three weeks after West
German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher proposed setting up
a European committee of experts to outline a course of action for
further European economic integration.
   The document adds further momentum to a discussion that started
late last year when French Economics Minister Edouard Balladur
proposed establishing a European central bank.
   Stoltenberg said in his memorandum that a European central bank
should be committed to price stability and should be independent of
both Common Market authorities and member governments.
   The central bank issue is expected to be discussed at the EEC
summit in Hanover, West Germany, on June 27 and 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1453EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CableTV     03-17 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable TV,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Warns Cable TV Industry On Rising Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, warned cable
television operators Thursday that Congress will consider
reregulating the industry if rates continue to rise and programming
is withheld from competitors.
   ``Some of us feel we were had'' by the congressional decision
that freed most cable operators of municipal rate control in
January 1987 and let them set their own prices, Metzenbaum said.
   ``This Congress is ready to re-examine that whole issue,'' said
Metzenbaum at a hearing of the Senate Judiciary's subcommittee on
antitrust, monopolies and business rights, which he chairs.
   Metzenbaum, the only senator present during much of the hearing,
said Congress is concerned that cable TV operators, an $11 billion
a year industry that serves 51 percent of American households,
enjoy a monopoly that can freeze out competing TV distribution
systems and raise prices.
   James P. Mooney, president of the National Cable Television
Association, disputed Metzenbaum's charge that cable prices have
``zoomed upwards'' by up to 400 percent in some areas since
deregulation.
   Mooney said an NCTA study shows that the average cable
subscriber's monthly bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months
after deregulation. While basic service prices rose about 10.6
percent, rates for premium or pay channels, like Home Box Office,
dropped 2.5 percent, according to the study.
   Mooney said that while some people saw large increases in their
rates as cable companies realigned their services, most people paid
only a small increase and also received more channels than they did
before deregulation.
   Metzenbaum also said he was concerned about complaints by cable
competitors that distribute TV programming via microwave and
satellite that they are being strangled by the cable industry's
control over programming.
   Cable operators have a stake in many of the major satellite
programmers, like HBO, Showtime, Turner Broadcasting and MTV, he
said.
   George Kocian, spokesman for the Home Satellite Television
Association, which represents owners and dealers of home satellite
dishes, told the committee the cable industry has tried to prevent
the growth of the home dish market by controlling access to and the
price of programming.
   About 2 million households receive TV directly from backyard
dishes. Most programming is now scrambled, so a dish owner must
purchase a decoder costing about $400 to unscramble the signals.
   Kocian said the association does not oppose scrambling, but he
said dish owners should not have to pay the same prices as cable
subscribers since they have to incur more of the cost of service,
like buying a decoder and maintaining their dish antenna.
   ``Consumers are willing to pay a fair price,'' he said. ``But we
are not being treated fairly or equally.''
   Joseph Collins, president of HBO, the nation's largest pay TV
company, said backyard dish owners can subscribe to HBO's scrambled
signal directly from HBO or from a cable operator. Dish subscribers
pay about two-thirds the price that cable subscribers do, he said.
   ``There is no denial of access,'' he said.
   However, he said the company has had problems with
microwave-based TV delivery systems that distribute HBO programming
unscrambled. In such cases, nonsubscribers with an appropriate
antenna can intercept these transmissions and watch HBO for free,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
