<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated     03-17 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Tells Judge Campeau Bid Is an Amended Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission dealt
R.H. Macy & Co. Inc.'s bid for Federated Department Stores Inc. a
setback today by recommending to a federal judge that Campeau
Corp's. revised tender offer for Federated be regarded as an
amendment to a previous offer rather than a new bid.
   If the judge agrees, the Campeau bid could expire as scheduled,
more than two weeks before Macy's competing offer. Macy fears that
Federated shareholders will feel pressured to tender their shares
to Campeau because of the earlier deadline.
   In a ``friend of the court'' brief, the SEC told U.S. District
Judge Leonard Sand the revised bid announced by Campeau March 2 was
not a new offer, and as such did not have to remain open for 20
business days past its publication.
   The revised offer changed the number of shares Campeau was
seeking and the price to be paid for those shares.
   Macy has asked Sand to declare the latest Campeau bid a new
offer, which would keep it open past its scheduled expiration.
   Campeau announced today it was extending its offer beyond Friday
to midnight March 22. However, Sand ruled earlier this week that
both companies' offers must remain open for three business days
after his decision on the Macy challenge and on a Campeau suit that
seeks to invalidate Federated's shareholders rights plan.
   Sand had sought the SEC opinion on the Macy argument. It was not
known when he would make his ruling.
   Macy had no comment on the SEC's opinion, said Maureen Milano, a
spokeswoman for the retailer.
   A Campeau spokeswoman, Joele Frank, said ``We're pleased'' about
the SEC's opinion, but ``It's really up to the judge.''
   Macy, whose bid expires on April 4, wants a later expiration for
the Campeau offer because it would put the competing bids on a more
equal footing.
   Campeau claimed its offer cannot go forward while the rights
plan, known as a ``poison pill,'' remains in effect. The plan
allows current Federated shareholders to buy more of the company's
stock at a steep discount, making a takeover prohibitively
expensive.
   Macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million
Federated shares, for a total of $6.3 billion. Macy will exchange
shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities
for the remainder of Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares.
   Campeau is offering $75 in cash per share for 70.5 million
Federated shares, or a total of $6.18 billion. The remaining of
Federated stock would be acquired later for $44 cash per share in a
subsequent merger, giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per
share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
