<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     03-17 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0423</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose today, buoyed by corporate
takeover maneuvering and favorable investor response to the
government's report of a lower-than-expected January trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.81 points to
2,070.13 by 3 p.m. EST.
   Among broader market barometers, the NYSE's composite index of
all listed common stocks rose 0.48 to 151.76. The American Stock
Exchange's market value index rose 1.04 to 298.55.
   Advancing issues outnumbered losers by slightly more than a
3-to-2 margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with 857 up, 614 down
and 480 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled 169.45 million
shares with one hour of trading left.
   Although the trade deficit reported by the Commerce Department
widened slightly in January to $12.4 billion from $12.2 billion in
December, market economists had expected an even greater gap of
about $13 billion.
   The news therefore provided an optimistic tone to stock trading
and substantiated other evidence that the economy is growing
despite fears of a slowdown raised by the October crash.
   ``I think the trade number was just what everybody liked,'' said
Philip C. Puccio, manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read
& Co. in New York. ``It brought a sigh of relief.''
   Nevertheless, Puccio and other trading strategists said
investors still were reluctant to commit large amounts of cash to
the stock market, at least until the conclusion of ``triple
witching hour'' on Friday.
   That quarterly event is so-named because of the
near-simultaneous expiration of contracts to buy or sell
stock-index futures, stock options and futures. It has contributed
to wild price swings in the past.
   Takeover related buying played a role in lifting stocks today.
Rumors of impending acquisition attempts on Pillsbury, Philips
Petroleum and U.S. Shoe sent those stocks sharply higher in active
trading. Pillsbury rose 3 to 45; Phillips rose 1 to 17\ and U.S.
Shoe rose 2[ to 24|.
   American Standard rose 1 to 76{ after the investment firm of
Kelso & Co. agreed to buy the company for $78 a share, topping a
hostile $73 a share offer from Black & Decker Corp. Black & Decker
rose 1 to 19{.
   Digital slumped 5~ to 111}, apparently in response to Merrill
Lynch's reduced earnings estimates for the computer company. Some
other key computer stocks also fell, including industry leader IBM,
down 1[ to 114[, and Hewlett Packard, down 1} to 63[.
</TEXT>
