<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Wickes     03-17 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Wickes,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asset Sales, Tax Credits Boost Wickes Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturing and retailing
conglomerate Wickes Cos. Inc. on Thursday posted a turnaround in
fourth-quarter earnings and a 116 percent jump in profits for its
fiscal year.
   However, earnings for the year ended Jan. 30 were boosted
primarily by $126.7 million in gains on assets sales and
extraordinary items.
   For the fourth quarter, the company netted $8.3 million, or 15
cents per share, compared to the year-earlier period when it had a
loss of $2.5 million.
   Revenues for the period were up 9.6 percent to $832.5 million
from $759.8 million, reflecting Wickes' acquisition of Collins &
Aikman Corp., the New York-based textile concern, in December 1986
for $1.16 billion.
   For the full year, the Wickes earned $180.5 million, or $3.68
per share, compared to the previous year when it earned $83.7
million, or $1.65 per share. The per-share figures for fiscal 1987
were restated to reflect a one-for-five reverse stock split that
took effect last August.
   Revenues for the past year were up 61.9 percent to $3.48 billion
from $2.15 billion.
   The company's income from continuing operations, which does not
include taxes or gains from assets sales and extraordinary items,
rose to $14.6 million from $3.1 million for the quarter, and
slipped to $69.1 million from $69.6 million for the year.

</TEXT>
