<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed higher today, helped by
takeover-related buying and a better-than-expected report on the
nation's trade deficit.
   But Wall Street strategists said the volume of trading did not
reflect a surge of investor confidence and probably was caused by
fears about the market's unpredictable behavior on ``triple
witching hour'' Friday.
   That quarterly event, so-named because of the near-simultaneous
expirations of contracts to buy or sell stock-index futures,
options and futures on individual stocks, has injected wildness
into the market in the past.
   ``I suspect traders are waiting for the triple witching hour to
get out of the way,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon, Read & Co. in New York.
