<DOCNO> AP880317-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Irradiation     03-17 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irradiation,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irradiation Company Pleads Guilty To Safety Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A food and medical supply irradiation
company pleaded guilty Wednesday to covering up safety violations,
and authorities revealed that its founder _ a leading spokesman for
the preservation process _ was negotiating a plea arrangement with
prosecutors.
   Radiation Technology Inc. admitted that a false memorandum
saying it had stopped bypassing safety measures at its Rockaway
plant was prepared and given to Nuclear Regulatory Commission
investigators.
   Both the company and federal authorities have said no employees
or members of the public were injured because of the violations.
   The Morris Plains company, represented by its president, Allan
Booth, also admitted telling the NRC that a radiation safety
monitor was removed for only one night when it was actually removed
for several days while the plant was irradiating products.
   Radiation Technology, which also has plants in West Memphis,
Ark., Haw River, N.C., and Salem, uses radioactive Cobalt-60 to
sterilize medical supplies and foodstuffs, mainly spices.
   On Tuesday, prosecutors said Thomas Powell, who worked as
operations manager at the Rockaway plant from 1980 to 1985, pleaded
guilty to related charges.
   Powell admitted conspiring with others to have employees bypass
devices called conveyor door safety interlocks required under its
license. The safety locks automatically lower the highly
radioactive Cobalt-60 materials into a safety pool if they sense
the presence of people. Powell faces five years in prison, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Jacqueline Wolff.
   The company, which faces a $1 million penalty, admitted that
company officials prepared and backdated a memo dated Sept. 21,
1984, falsely saying that its employees had been ordered to stop
bypassing the interlock system.
   During a hearing, U.S. District Judge Maryanne Trump Barry asked
if there was a problem with plea negotiations with the company's
founder and former chairman, Martin Welt.
   Ms. Wolff responded that Welt had signed a plea agreement
admitting to related charges but had decided not to enter the plea.
   Later, Ms. Wolff said Welt's attorneys and her office had been
negotiating over a plea and that she did not know the reason why
Welt did not enter it.
   Welt has spoken frequently in the national media about the value
of food irradiation, and even traveled to China last year to
promote the process.
   Welt was forced to sever his links to Radiation Technology in
mid-1986 along with Powell after the NRC briefly suspended the
company's license for the interlock safety violations.
   Ms. Wolff said the safety systems were bypassed ``to keep the
business going.
   ``The interlocks were not operating properly. The thing to do is
shut it down,'' she said.
   In a prepared statement, the company said:
   ``By this guilty plea, RTI has acknowledged its legal
responsibility for the actions of an officer who submitted false
information to the NRC relating to known deficiences in equipment
designed to insure operator safety at RTI's Rockaway facility.''
   The company referred all further comment, including who the
official was, to its public relations firm, Solakian Associates.
   Mary Solakian said she was not familiar enough with Wednesday's
hearing to comment, and said her husband was out of the office and
could not be reached.
   In exchange for the company's guilty plea, the government agreed
not to further prosecute the firm on the matter and take no
position on sentencing unless the judge asks, said Ms. Wolff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880317-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1800EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     03-17 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose in the week ended March 7, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally
adjusted $2,954.5 billion in the latest week from $2,947.4 billion
te previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased to a seasonally adjusted
$3,725.4 billion from $3,721.6 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose to a
seasonally adjusted $755.6 billion from a revised $755 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures
   The Fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for
M2 and M3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly
lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. The Fed
has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $1.24 billion in
the week ended March 9, compared with a gain of $1.3 billion a week
earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $153 million a day
in the week ended Wednesday, compared with $378 million in the
previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $272.1 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, down from $272.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
