<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Citicorp-Reed     03-17 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citicorp-Reed,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citicorp Chairman Predicts Improved Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Back interest payments on Brazilian loans could
add $250 million to Citicorp's 1988 earnings, Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer John S. Reed said Wednesday.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company with assets
of $203.6 billion, is the leader of negotiations between banks and
the Brazilian government aimed at restructuring that country's debt.
   ``I believe Brazil is likely to reach an agreement with the
banks, but it is difficult to be assured of it,'' Reed told a news
conference before a luncheon address to the Economic Club of
Detroit.
   Whatever the success of the debt-restructuring talks, Brazil's
resumption of interest payments will be a boost, Reed said.
   And he said, ``We are quite positive about our own situation.''
   ``They have paid the interest for the fourth quarter of last
year. They are paying now the interest due for the first quarter of
this year but no one has booked it yet,'' he said. ``We are short
$200 million after tax, $333 million before tax, from Brazil. So we
have the potential of booking in this year one-quarter billion
dollars.''
   Brazil, which owes more than $112 billion abroad and has not
repaid any principal since 1983, stopped paying interest on bank
debts in February 1987.
   Citicorp was the first bank to respond, in May 1987, by boosting
loan-loss reserves, increasing them during the year by about $3
billion.
   That and other steps ``confused'' Citicorp's earnings picture
for 1987, Reed said. Citicorp reported a loss of $1.13 billion for
1987, compared with net income of $1.05 billion in 1986.
   In 1988, he said, ``We expect to return to a normal year.''
   Reed said predictions of slower consumer-spending growth this
year may have been excessively conservative, as indicated by
healthy auto sales and home mortgage activity thus far.
   Mortgage applications to Citicorp, which accounts for 6 percent
of the nation's single-family home loans, have been higher than
expected in the past 30 days, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
