<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chrysler-UAW     03-17 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler-UAW,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW, Chrysler Looking at April 18th Start of Early Contract Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. would like to begin early contract
negotiations with the United Auto Workers on April 18 _ that is, if
Chrysler's top bargainer isn't serving on a jury.
   Anthony St. John, the company's lead negotiator, said Wednesday
that Chrysler has settled on the tentative date for the start of
talks on a contract covering 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off
workers and wants a settlement deadline for sometime in June.
   UAW spokesman Bob Barbee said the date won't be confirmed until
UAW Vice President Marc Stepp is sure it will fit into a schedule
crammed with negotiations with other companies including General
Dynamics.
   In general, Barbee said, ``it sounds reasonable.''
   But St. John, Chrysler's vice president for human resources,
also has a conflict: He's been called to jury duty in Oakland
County Circuit Court for April 18-19.
   ``I'm trying to get out of jury duty,'' he said. ``This is my
third summons. I asked to postpone one to attend a board meeting.''
   As a lawyer _ he began his labor relations career arguing cases
for the National Labor Relations Board _ St. John said he is
automatically excluded from jury duty in most states, but not in
Michigan.
   Next week, the UAW's elected 10-member bargaining committee
meets in Tampa, Fla., with Stepp and other union officials to
prepare demands. Its 140-member national Chrysler council meets
April 5-7 in Missouri to approve them.
   Chrysler's three-year contract expires Sept. 14. Talks normally
begin in mid-July, but Chrysler asked for the early start after the
UAW forced it to reverse a plan to sell its 28,000-worker Acustar
Inc. parts subsidiary.
   In cooperative union-management programs that reach from the
executive suite to the plant floor, the two sides have begun
working together to find ways to improve Chrysler's production
quality and efficiency.
   They are considered crucial to the survival of any auto company
battling for its share of an intensely competitive market. But
``negotiations tend to put everything into a kind of holding
pattern,'' St. John said.
   Chrysler will work within the job-protecting pattern contracts
established for the industry last fall at Ford Motor Co. and
General Motors Corp., but will try to mold the pattern to
Chrysler's needs, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
